{"title_page": "Moreland Zebras FC", "text_new": "{{About|the 1997 break off club based in [[Fawkner, Victoria|Fawkner]]|the original 1948 club based in [[Brunswick East, Victoria|Brunswick East]]|Brunswick Zebras FC}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| nickname = Zebras\n| ground = [[CB Smith Reserve]]\n| capacity = \n| pattern_la1 = _black_stripes\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = \n| pattern_ra1 = _black_stripes\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| leftarm1 = ffffff\n| leftarm2 = 0000ff\n| body1 = ffffff\n| body2 = 0000ff\n| rightarm1 = ffffff\n| rightarm2 = 0000ff\n| shorts1 = \n| shorts2 = 0000ff\n| socks1 = \n| socks2 = 0000ff\n| clubname = Moreland Zebras\n| image = Moreland Zebras FC.png\n| image_size = 150px\n| fullname = Moreland Zebras Football Club\n| founded = 1948 as part of ''[[Brunswick Juventus|Juventus]]''<br>1997 as ''Bulleen Inter Kings''<br>2000 as ''Bulleen Zebras''<br>2007 as ''Whittlesea Zebras''<br>2011 as ''Moreland Zebras''<br>\n| manager = [[Fausto De Amicis]]\n| league = [[National Premier Leagues Victoria 2|NPL Victoria 2]]\n| website = http://www.morelandzebras.com/\n| pattern_b1 = _blackstripes\n}}\n\n'''Moreland Zebras Football Club''' is an Australian [[association football|soccer]] club based in the [[Melbourne]] municipality of [[Moreland, Victoria]]. The club currently competes in the [[National Premier Leagues Victoria 2]] and is based at [[CB Smith Reserve]] in the suburb of [[Fawkner, Victoria|Fawkner]]. The earliest traces of the club date back to 1948 with the founding of [[Brunswick Zebras FC|Juventus]], and was officially founded in 1997 with mergers and de-mergers occurring between [[List of Italian soccer clubs in Victoria, Australia|Italian backed clubs]] within the [[Italian community of Melbourne]].\n\n==History==\n===Foundings, mergers and de-mergers (1997\u20132008)===\nThe club was founded in 1997 as a merger of several [[Italian community of Melbourne|Italian backed]] football clubs in Melbourne, being the senior teams of [[Box Hill United SC|Box Hill Inter]], [[Brunswick Zebras FC|Brunswick Zebras]] (partially) and [[FC Bulleen Lions|Bulleen Lions]], to become 'Bulleen Inter Kings' being based at the Veneto Club in [[Bulleen, Victoria|Bulleen]]. As the Brunswick senior team was broken into two separate entities, one being the part that makes Moreland Zebras today, and the other part later becoming part of rivals [[Whittlesea Ranges FC|Whittlesea Ranges]], the history of the club regarding events prior to 1997 have been [[Pseudohistory|disputed]] since. Whilst the senior teams had merged, all three original standalone clubs maintained junior academies at their respective original home venues. In 2000 Box Hill completely de-merged, resulting in the club becoming 'Bulleen Zebras FC'. Bulleen would follow suit in 2007 becoming a standalone club again, with the former Brunswick senior side moving [[Epping Stadium]]. The Brunswick senior team did not return to its original Sumner Park in [[Brunswick East, Victoria|Brunswick East]] and not formally re-merge with its junior side, as the junior had developed its own a senior side in response to player surplus.<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Clubs/VIC/Vic_Active_B.html#BrunswickZebras</ref>\n\nThe separated senior side would later merge with the Whittlesea group of the de-merged [[Fawkner-Whittlesea Blues]] to become Whittlesea Stallions. Two years later in 2009, the Whittlesea group would de-merge with the Brunswick seniors and merge with the Thomastown Devils to become [[Whittlesea Ranges FC|Whittlesea Ranges]]. The senior side would rename itself to its current name of '''Moreland Zebras''', formally relocating to [[CB Smith Reserve]] and develop its own junior academy. As of 2019, the original club [[Brunswick Zebras FC|Brunswick Zebras]], the Moreland Zebras, and Whittlesea Ranges all claim a lineage to the history and accolades achieved prior to 1997.<ref>https://docs.google.com/file/d/0B-GeBc7j6xA6ZHNuY3ZTaVBHWXc/edit</ref><ref>https://www.theffacup.com.au/news/moreland-zebras-ultimate-guide-former-austalian-champions-primed-shine-national-stage-34-years-later</ref>\n\n===2009\u2013present===\nIn 2011, the club was crowned [[Victorian State League Division 1]] champions. After being crowned champions, club members decided at the annual general meeting that the club would relocate to the [[City of Moreland]]. The club's name was then changed to Moreland Zebras FC and played out of DeChene Reserve in [[Coburg, Victoria|Coburg]].\n\nIn 2015, the club's seniors moved into the facilities at [[CB Smith Reserve]], while the juniors continued to be based out of DeChene Reserve. The Zebras finished in second place in the NPL 1 West division in 2015 and qualified for a playoff match against [[Melbourne Victory]]'s NPL team. Despite scoring early, the Zebras lost the game 2\u20131 and remained in the NPL1 division for 2016, now named NPL2.\n\nAfter the departure of senior head coach Danny Gnjidic at the end of the 2016 NPL2 West season, in which Moreland finished in 5th place, the Zebras appointed former player [[Fausto De Amicis]] as the new manager of the first team.<ref name=\"Zebras Appoint De Amicis\">{{cite web|title=NEWS: COACHING ANNOUNCEMENT|url=http://websites.sportstg.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-8746-124209-0-0&sID=308736&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=48660102|website=Moreland Zebras Football Club|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref> Moreland finished in 2nd place in 2017, five points off promoted [[Northcote City FC|Northcote City]]. In the promotion playoff, the Zebras lost 1-0 to [[Dandenong City SC|Dandenong City]].\n\nFor the 2018 season, Juventus signed former A-League players [[Jake Barker-Daish]], [[Rashid Mahazi]] and [[Jakob Williams]]. The Zebras held second position of the table for extended periods of the 2018 season, but with just one win from their last six games, Moreland were overtaken by both [[St Albans Saints SC|St Albans]] and [[North Geelong Warriors FC|North Geelong Warriors]] in the table, leaving them in 4th place at the end of the 2018 season.\n\nIn the 2019 season, Zebras qualified for the final stages of the [[2019 FFA Cup|FFA Cup]], beating Victorian top division side [[Altona Magic SC|Altona Magic]] in the qualifying rounds. In the Round of 32, Moreland beat fellow Victorian NPL2 qualifiers Bulleen Lions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theffacup.com.au/match/fc-bulleen-lions-v-moreland-zebras-ffa-cup-24-07-2019/1068744|title=FC Bulleen Lions vs Moreland Zebras, FFA Cup, Round of 32, 24th Jul 2019|website=FFA Cup|language=en|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> In the Round of 16, Zebras beat [[National Premier Leagues Queensland|NPL Queensland]] side [[Magpies Crusaders]] 4-0 in front of over 1,300 at CB Smith Reserve and became the first ever third-tier side to qualify for the FFA Cup quarter-finals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theffacup.com.au/match/moreland-zebras-v-magpies-crusaders-ffa-cup-21-08-2019/2024811|title=Moreland Zebras vs Magpies Crusaders, FFA Cup, Round of 16, 21st Aug 2019|website=FFA Cup|language=en|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyfootballshow.com/npl2-side-moreland-zebras-gatecrash-ffa-cup-quarterfinals-with-4-0-over-magpies-crusaders-fc/,%20https://dailyfootballshow.com/?amp=1|title=NPL2 side Moreland Zebras gatecrash FFA Cup quarter-finals with 4-0 win over Magpies Crusaders FC {{!}} Daily Football Show|last=Lynch|first=Joey|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>https://www.smh.com.au/sport/soccer/moreland-zebras-make-history-with-ffa-cup-quarter-final-spot-20190821-p52jig.html</ref><ref>https://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/football/secondtier-moreland-zebras-trounce-queenslanders-to-make-ffa-cup-history/news-story/f505b16ab97c5b46fe38d1eba0b06dec</ref><ref>https://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/football/secondtier-moreland-zebras-trounce-queenslanders-to-make-ffa-cup-history/news-story/f505b16ab97c5b46fe38d1eba0b06dec</ref><ref>https://www.a-league.com.au/news/confirmed-squads-ffa-cup-2019-quarter-finals</ref><ref>https://www.theffacup.com.au/news/bring-them-strikers-pip-roar-make-ffa-cup-history</ref><ref>https://www.theroar.com.au/2019/09/20/footballs-us-versus-them-mentality-is-the-next-problem-to-fix/</ref><ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/football/ffa-cup/ffa-cup-live-melbourne-city-v-western-sydney-wanderers-semifinals-wsw-live-stream-how-to-watch-live-blog-news-scores-start-time-update-team-news-preview/news-story/0a47f8d6f10c5162a0598c9fec7ec479</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Zebras midfielder Dhour Chol was called up for the [[South Sudan national football team|South Sudan national team]].<ref>https://www.a-league.com.au/news/south-sudan-name-12-australia-based-players-afcon-qualifier</ref>\n\n==Recent Honours==\n*'''[[National Premier Leagues Victoria|Victorian First Tier]]'''\n:Champions (2): 1998,<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/States/VIC/1998PLT.html</ref> 2004<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/States/VIC/2004PLT.html</ref>\n*'''[[National Premier Leagues Victoria 2|Victorian Second Tier]]'''\n:Premiers (1): 2011<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/States/VIC/2011SD1T.html</ref>\n\n==Notable former players==\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Andrew Nabbout]]\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Jake Barker-Daish]]\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Marco Bresciano]]\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Michael Theo]]\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Rashid Mahazi]]\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ricky Diaco]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Australia}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.morelandzebras.com/ Official Site]\n\n{{Football Federation Victoria}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moreland Zebras FC}}\n[[Category:Soccer clubs in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Soccer clubs in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Victorian Premier League teams]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Italian-Australian culture in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Italian-Australian backed sports clubs of Victoria]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1997 break off club based in [[Fawkner, Victoria|Fawkner]]|the original 1948 club based in [[Brunswick East, Victoria|Brunswick East]]|Brunswick Zebras FC}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| nickname = Zebras\n| ground = [[CB Smith Reserve]]\n| capacity = \n| pattern_la1 = _black_stripes\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = \n| pattern_ra1 = _black_stripes\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| leftarm1 = ffffff\n| leftarm2 = 0000ff\n| body1 = ffffff\n| body2 = 0000ff\n| rightarm1 = ffffff\n| rightarm2 = 0000ff\n| shorts1 = \n| shorts2 = 0000ff\n| socks1 = \n| socks2 = 0000ff\n| clubname = Moreland Zebras\n| image = Moreland Zebras FC.png\n| image_size = 150px\n| fullname = Moreland Zebras Football Club\n| founded = 1948 as part of ''[[Brunswick Zebras FC|Juventus]]''<br>1997 as ''Bulleen Inter Kings''<br>2000 as ''Bulleen Zebras''<br>2007 as ''Whittlesea Zebras''<br>2011 as ''Moreland Zebras''<br>\n| manager = [[Fausto De Amicis]]\n| league = [[National Premier Leagues Victoria 2|NPL Victoria 2]]\n| website = http://www.morelandzebras.com/\n| pattern_b1 = _blackstripes\n}}\n\n'''Moreland Zebras Football Club''' is an Australian [[association football|soccer]] club based in the [[Melbourne]] municipality of [[Moreland, Victoria]]. The club currently competes in the [[National Premier Leagues Victoria 2]] and is based at [[CB Smith Reserve]] in the suburb of [[Fawkner, Victoria|Fawkner]]. The earliest traces of the club date back to 1948 with the founding of [[Brunswick Zebras FC|Juventus]], and was officially founded in 1997 with mergers and de-mergers occurring between [[List of Italian soccer clubs in Victoria, Australia|Italian backed clubs]] within the [[Italian community of Melbourne]].\n\n==History==\n===Foundings, mergers and de-mergers (1997\u20132008)===\nThe club was founded in 1997 as a merger of several [[Italian community of Melbourne|Italian backed]] football clubs in Melbourne, being the senior teams of [[Box Hill United SC|Box Hill Inter]], [[Brunswick Zebras FC|Brunswick Zebras]] (partially) and [[FC Bulleen Lions|Bulleen Lions]], to become 'Bulleen Inter Kings' being based at the Veneto Club in [[Bulleen, Victoria|Bulleen]]. As the Brunswick senior team was broken into two separate entities, one being the part that makes Moreland Zebras today, and the other part later becoming part of rivals [[Whittlesea Ranges FC|Whittlesea Ranges]], the history of the club regarding events prior to 1997 have been [[Pseudohistory|disputed]] since. Whilst the senior teams had merged, all three original standalone clubs maintained junior academies at their respective original home venues. In 2000 Box Hill completely de-merged, resulting in the club becoming 'Bulleen Zebras FC'. Bulleen would follow suit in 2007 becoming a standalone club again, with the former Brunswick senior side moving [[Epping Stadium]]. The Brunswick senior team did not return to its original Sumner Park in [[Brunswick East, Victoria|Brunswick East]] and not formally re-merge with its junior side, as the junior had developed its own a senior side in response to player surplus.<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Clubs/VIC/Vic_Active_B.html#BrunswickZebras</ref>\n\nThe separated senior side would later merge with the Whittlesea group of the de-merged [[Fawkner-Whittlesea Blues]] to become Whittlesea Stallions. Two years later in 2009, the Whittlesea group would de-merge with the Brunswick seniors and merge with the Thomastown Devils to become [[Whittlesea Ranges FC|Whittlesea Ranges]]. The senior side would rename itself to its current name of '''Moreland Zebras''', formally relocating to [[CB Smith Reserve]] and develop its own junior academy. As of 2019, the original club [[Brunswick Zebras FC|Brunswick Zebras]], the Moreland Zebras, and Whittlesea Ranges all claim a lineage to the history and accolades achieved prior to 1997.<ref>https://docs.google.com/file/d/0B-GeBc7j6xA6ZHNuY3ZTaVBHWXc/edit</ref><ref>https://www.theffacup.com.au/news/moreland-zebras-ultimate-guide-former-austalian-champions-primed-shine-national-stage-34-years-later</ref>\n\n===2009\u2013present===\nIn 2011, the club was crowned [[Victorian State League Division 1]] champions. After being crowned champions, club members decided at the annual general meeting that the club would relocate to the [[City of Moreland]]. The club's name was then changed to Moreland Zebras FC and played out of DeChene Reserve in [[Coburg, Victoria|Coburg]].\n\nIn 2015, the club's seniors moved into the facilities at [[CB Smith Reserve]], while the juniors continued to be based out of DeChene Reserve. The Zebras finished in second place in the NPL 1 West division in 2015 and qualified for a playoff match against [[Melbourne Victory]]'s NPL team. Despite scoring early, the Zebras lost the game 2\u20131 and remained in the NPL1 division for 2016, now named NPL2.\n\nAfter the departure of senior head coach Danny Gnjidic at the end of the 2016 NPL2 West season, in which Moreland finished in 5th place, the Zebras appointed former player [[Fausto De Amicis]] as the new manager of the first team.<ref name=\"Zebras Appoint De Amicis\">{{cite web|title=NEWS: COACHING ANNOUNCEMENT|url=http://websites.sportstg.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-8746-124209-0-0&sID=308736&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=48660102|website=Moreland Zebras Football Club|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref> Moreland finished in 2nd place in 2017, five points off promoted [[Northcote City FC|Northcote City]]. In the promotion playoff, the Zebras lost 1-0 to [[Dandenong City SC|Dandenong City]].\n\nFor the 2018 season, Juventus signed former A-League players [[Jake Barker-Daish]], [[Rashid Mahazi]] and [[Jakob Williams]]. The Zebras held second position of the table for extended periods of the 2018 season, but with just one win from their last six games, Moreland were overtaken by both [[St Albans Saints SC|St Albans]] and [[North Geelong Warriors FC|North Geelong Warriors]] in the table, leaving them in 4th place at the end of the 2018 season.\n\nIn the 2019 season, Zebras qualified for the final stages of the [[2019 FFA Cup|FFA Cup]], beating Victorian top division side [[Altona Magic SC|Altona Magic]] in the qualifying rounds. In the Round of 32, Moreland beat fellow Victorian NPL2 qualifiers Bulleen Lions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theffacup.com.au/match/fc-bulleen-lions-v-moreland-zebras-ffa-cup-24-07-2019/1068744|title=FC Bulleen Lions vs Moreland Zebras, FFA Cup, Round of 32, 24th Jul 2019|website=FFA Cup|language=en|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> In the Round of 16, Zebras beat [[National Premier Leagues Queensland|NPL Queensland]] side [[Magpies Crusaders]] 4-0 in front of over 1,300 at CB Smith Reserve and became the first ever third-tier side to qualify for the FFA Cup quarter-finals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theffacup.com.au/match/moreland-zebras-v-magpies-crusaders-ffa-cup-21-08-2019/2024811|title=Moreland Zebras vs Magpies Crusaders, FFA Cup, Round of 16, 21st Aug 2019|website=FFA Cup|language=en|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyfootballshow.com/npl2-side-moreland-zebras-gatecrash-ffa-cup-quarterfinals-with-4-0-over-magpies-crusaders-fc/,%20https://dailyfootballshow.com/?amp=1|title=NPL2 side Moreland Zebras gatecrash FFA Cup quarter-finals with 4-0 win over Magpies Crusaders FC {{!}} Daily Football Show|last=Lynch|first=Joey|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>https://www.smh.com.au/sport/soccer/moreland-zebras-make-history-with-ffa-cup-quarter-final-spot-20190821-p52jig.html</ref><ref>https://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/football/secondtier-moreland-zebras-trounce-queenslanders-to-make-ffa-cup-history/news-story/f505b16ab97c5b46fe38d1eba0b06dec</ref><ref>https://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/football/secondtier-moreland-zebras-trounce-queenslanders-to-make-ffa-cup-history/news-story/f505b16ab97c5b46fe38d1eba0b06dec</ref><ref>https://www.a-league.com.au/news/confirmed-squads-ffa-cup-2019-quarter-finals</ref><ref>https://www.theffacup.com.au/news/bring-them-strikers-pip-roar-make-ffa-cup-history</ref><ref>https://www.theroar.com.au/2019/09/20/footballs-us-versus-them-mentality-is-the-next-problem-to-fix/</ref><ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/football/ffa-cup/ffa-cup-live-melbourne-city-v-western-sydney-wanderers-semifinals-wsw-live-stream-how-to-watch-live-blog-news-scores-start-time-update-team-news-preview/news-story/0a47f8d6f10c5162a0598c9fec7ec479</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Zebras midfielder Dhour Chol was called up for the [[South Sudan national football team|South Sudan national team]].<ref>https://www.a-league.com.au/news/south-sudan-name-12-australia-based-players-afcon-qualifier</ref>\n\n==Recent Honours==\n*'''[[National Premier Leagues Victoria|Victorian First Tier]]'''\n:Champions (2): 1998,<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/States/VIC/1998PLT.html</ref> 2004<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/States/VIC/2004PLT.html</ref>\n*'''[[National Premier Leagues Victoria 2|Victorian Second Tier]]'''\n:Premiers (1): 2011<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/States/VIC/2011SD1T.html</ref>\n\n==Notable former players==\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Andrew Nabbout]]\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Jake Barker-Daish]]\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Marco Bresciano]]\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Michael Theo]]\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Rashid Mahazi]]\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ricky Diaco]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Australia}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.morelandzebras.com/ Official Site]\n\n{{Football Federation Victoria}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moreland Zebras FC}}\n[[Category:Soccer clubs in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Soccer clubs in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Victorian Premier League teams]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Italian-Australian culture in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Italian-Australian backed sports clubs of Victoria]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Victoryboy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moreland_Zebras_FC"}
{"title_page": "Dianne Kornberg", "text_new": "{{short description|American artist born 1945}}\n{{Primary sources|date=April 2020}}\n'''Dianne Kornberg''' (born 1945) is an American artist.<ref name=\"PAM\"/><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://fotografmagazine.cz/en/magazine/photography-and-painting/profiles/dianne-kornberg/ | title=Dianne Kornberg}}</ref> \n\nKornberg received a [[BFA degree]] in painting in 1967 and a [[Master of Fine Arts]] in painting in 1970, both from [[Indiana University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ddPpAAAAMAAJ&q=kornberg+MFA+Indiana+University+in+1970&dq=kornberg+MFA+Indiana+University+in+1970&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2hrS_6uboAhXCnOAKHdgqBeYQ6AEINzAC|title=Contemporary art in the Northwest|first=Lois|last=Allan|date=October 14, 1995|publisher=Craftsman House|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nHer work is included in the collections of the [[Portland Art Museum]],<ref name=\"PAM\">{{Cite web | url=http://portlandartmuseum.us/mwebcgi/mweb.exe?request=record;id=1413;type=701 |title = Dianne Kornberg}}</ref> the [[Henry Art Gallery]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.henryart.org/results.php?term=Kornberg,+Dianne&module=objects&type=keyword|title=Henry Art Gallery|website=collections.henryart.org}}</ref> the [[Seattle Art Museum]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://art.seattleartmuseum.org/people/2830/dianne-kornberg |title = Dianne Kornberg \u2013 Artists \u2013 eMuseum}}</ref> the [[Princeton University Art Museum]] <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://artmuseum.princeton.edu/es/collections/maker/4361 | title=Dianne Kornberg &#124; Princeton University Art Museum}}</ref> and the [[U.S. Department of State]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://art.state.gov/personnel/dianne_kornberg/ | title=Dianne Kornberg \u2013 U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kornberg, Diane}}\n\n{{US-artist-stub}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American artist born 1945}}\n{{Primary sources|date=April 2020}}\n'''Dianne Kornberg''' (1945) is an American artist.<ref name=\"PAM\"/><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://fotografmagazine.cz/en/magazine/photography-and-painting/profiles/dianne-kornberg/ | title=Dianne Kornberg}}</ref> \n\nKornberg received a [[BFA degree]] in painting in 1967 and a [[Master of Fine Arts]] in painting in 1970, both from [[Indiana University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ddPpAAAAMAAJ&q=kornberg+MFA+Indiana+University+in+1970&dq=kornberg+MFA+Indiana+University+in+1970&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2hrS_6uboAhXCnOAKHdgqBeYQ6AEINzAC|title=Contemporary art in the Northwest|first=Lois|last=Allan|date=October 14, 1995|publisher=Craftsman House|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nHer work is included in the collections of the [[Portland Art Museum]],<ref name=\"PAM\">{{Cite web | url=http://portlandartmuseum.us/mwebcgi/mweb.exe?request=record;id=1413;type=701 |title = Dianne Kornberg}}</ref> the [[Henry Art Gallery]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.henryart.org/results.php?term=Kornberg,+Dianne&module=objects&type=keyword|title=Henry Art Gallery|website=collections.henryart.org}}</ref> the [[Seattle Art Museum]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://art.seattleartmuseum.org/people/2830/dianne-kornberg |title = Dianne Kornberg \u2013 Artists \u2013 eMuseum}}</ref> the [[Princeton University Art Museum]] <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://artmuseum.princeton.edu/es/collections/maker/4361 | title=Dianne Kornberg &#124; Princeton University Art Museum}}</ref> and the [[U.S. Department of State]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://art.state.gov/personnel/dianne_kornberg/ | title=Dianne Kornberg \u2013 U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kornberg, Diane}}\n\n{{US-artist-stub}}\n\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Lopifalko", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:FIRST", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dianne_Kornberg"}
{"title_page": "Front Cover", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Front Cover\n| image          = Front Cover poster.jpg\n| director       = Ray Yeung\n| producer       = Kaer Vanice, Chowee Leow, Stan Guingon\n| screenplay     = Ray Yeung\n| starring       = Jake Choi, James Chen, Elizabeth Sung, Jennifer Neals Page, Sonia Villani, Li Jun Li, Ming Lee, Benjamin Thys, Tom Ligon\n| music          = Paul Turner, Darren Morze\n| cinematography = Eun-ah Lee\n| editing        = Joseph Gutowski\n| distributor    = Strand Releasing\n| released       = {{Film date|2015|05|28|Seattle International Film Festival}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes\n| country        = United States\n}}\n'''''Front Cover''''' is a 2015 drama romance film written and directed by [[Ray Yeung]]. The story follows Ryan Fu, a gay Chinese American fashion stylist ([[Jake Choi]]), who rejects his ethnic heritage, who is assigned to style Ning ([[James Chen (actor)|James Chen]]), an ostensibly heterosexual patriotic actor from Beijing. ''Front Cover'' received mixed critical reviews and received awards from festivals such as San Diego Outfest, Boston Asian American Film Festival, and Outflix Film Festival.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Plot ==\n''Front Cover'' tells the story of Ryan Fu, a gay Chinese American who rejects his Asian heritage and has learnt to suppress it to climb up the social ladder. Through talent and hard work he has attained his dream job as an assistant to Francesca, a celebrity fashion stylist. One day Francesca assigns Ryan to style Ning, an actor who has just arrived from Beijing, for a top magazine photo shoot. Ning dismisses Ryan's initial Western styling and demands Ryan creates an image for him which represents the power of the new China. Their opinions clash resulting in a strained working relationship. Over the following days, they socialize whilst working together and discover not only do they share a lot in common, a mutual attraction begins to develop. As they get closer Ryan reveals that he detests his Chinese heritage because he is ashamed of his impoverished upbringing. Ning also opens up and confesses that he is closeted. As they fall in love, a Chinese tabloid magazine exposes Ning as gay. Terrified of the impact it will have on his career, Ning begs Ryan to lie for him at a press conference. Ryan must now decide whether to help Ning or stay true to himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/front-cover-2016|title=Front Cover movie review & film summary (2016) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Cheshire|first=Godfrey|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Jake Choi]] as Ryan Fu\n*[[James Chen (actor)|James Chen]] as Qi Xiao Ning\n* [[Elizabeth Sung]] as Yen Fu\n*Jennifer Neala Page as Janet\n* Sonia Villani as Francesca\n*[[Li Jun Li]] as Miao\n*Ming Lee as Ba\n*Benjamin Thys as James\n*[[Tom Ligon]] as Gus LaMar\n\n== Release ==\n''Front Cover'' premiered in 2015 at the [[Seattle International Film Festival]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.siff.net/media/press/press-releases/awards-2015|title=SEATTLE INTERNATIONAL FILM FESTIVAL ANNOUNCES AUDIENCE & COMPETITION AWARDS|website=www.siff.net|language=en|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> in the Catalyst Competition section, and was again in Competition at the 2015 [[Chicago International Film Festival]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.frontcoverthemovie.com/2015/09/25/front-cover-will-compete-at-the-chicago-international-film-festival/|title=FRONT COVER WILL COMPETE AT THE CHICAGO INTERNATIONAL FILM FESTIVAL|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> It was the closing film for the [[Asian American International Film Festival]] in New York in 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmfestivals.com/blog/aviva_press/aaiff16_closing_night_premiere_of_front_cover_carpet_arrivals|title=AAIFF16 Closing Night Premiere of Front Cover Carpet Arrivals|website=www.filmfestivals.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> as well as for the 2016 Sacramento Asian Pacific Film Festival,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sapff.org/2016-festival-programming/|title=2016 Sacramento Asian Pacific Film Festival Program|last=|first=|date=2016-05-28|website=Sacramento Asian Pacific Film Festival|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and the Poland LGBT Film Festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.frontcoverthemovie.com/2016/03/28/front-cover-premieres-as-the-closing-film-at-the-poland-lgbt-film-festival/|title=FRONT COVER PREMIERES AS THE CLOSING FILM AT THE POLAND LGBT FILM FESTIVAL|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>  \n\n[[Strand Releasing]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tiff-2015-ray-yeungs-front-822582|title=TIFF: Ray Yeung's 'Front Cover' Goes to Strand Releasing|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> and Edko Films Ltd.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/busan-edko-films-snags-cover-rights-1201609019/|title=Busan: Edko Films Snags \u2018Cover\u2019 Rights|last=Frater|first=Patrick|last2=Frater|first2=Patrick|date=2015-10-03|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> acquired USA and Hong Kong distribution rights. It was released in the US in August 2016 and in Hong Kong in October 2016. [[Sahamongkol Film International Co. Ltd.|Sahamongkolfilm International Co, Ltd.]] released the movie in Bangkok, Thailand in August 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sahamongkolfilm.com/saha-movie/front-cover/|title=Front Cover|website=Sahamongkolfilm|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n''Front Cover'' holds an 82% approval rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Front Cover (2016)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/front_cover_2016|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> Godfrey Cheshire of ''[[RogerEbert.com]]'' describes it as, \"A skillfully written and acted gay love story about two young men of Chinese ancestry...The transition from distrust to wary friendship to something more passionate in a movie like this depends a lot on the writing, and Yeung\u2019s is subtle and assured, tracing an emotional arc that\u2019s believably nuanced.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/front-cover-2016|title=Front Cover movie review & film summary (2016) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Cheshire|first=Godfrey|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> Robyn Bahr of the [[The Village Voice|''Village Voice'']] described it as a \"sexy, ambitious queer rom-com(ish) drama.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2016/08/02/queer-rom-comish-drama-front-cover-is-an-ambitious-breakthrough/|title=Queer Rom-Com(ish) Drama \u2018Front Cover\u2019 Is an Ambitious Breakthrough {{!}} The Village Voice|website=www.villagevoice.com|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> Jeannette Catsoulis reviewed the movie for the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' and called the film a \"sensitive, decorous and buffed by Eun-ah Lee\u2019s warm photography.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/05/movies/front-cover-review.html|title=Review: In \u2018Front Cover,\u2019 Struggling for Self-Acceptance|last=Catsoulis|first=Jeannette|date=2016-08-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\n\n=== Awards ===\n\n*Winner Best Screenplay at the FilmOut San Diego Film Festival 2016 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmoutsandiego.com/2016-festival-awards.htm|title=FilmOut San Diego Sponsors|website=www.filmoutsandiego.com|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n* Winner Jury Award Best Domestic Feature Outflix Film Festival Memphis 2016 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outmemphis.org/outflix-2016-award-winners/|title=Outflix 2016 Award Winners!|last=OUTMemphis|date=2016-09-16|website=OUTMemphis|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n* Winner Audience Award for Best Narrative Film at the [[Boston Asian American Film Festival]] 2016 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0004211/2016/1/|title=Boston Asian American Film Festival (2016)|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n* Winner Best Full Feature at Serile Filmului Gay International Film Festival Romania 2016 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0002866/2016/1/|title=Serile Filmului Gay International Film Festival, Romania (2016)|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n* Winner Best Actor (to [[James Chen (actor)|James Chen]]) at Australia Golden Koala Chinese Film Festival 2017 <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://concreteplayground.com/sydney/event/golden-koala-chinese-film-festival-2017|title=Golden Koala Chinese Film Festival 2017|work=Concrete Playground|access-date=2018-12-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Nominations ===\n\n* Nominated New American Cinema Award at [[Seattle International Film Festival]] 2015 <ref name=\":2\" />\n* Nominated Q Hugo Award [[Chicago International Film Festival]] 2015 <ref name=\":3\" />\n* Nominated Best Director at Australia Golden Koala Chinese Film Festival 2017 <ref name=\":0\" />\n* Nominated Best Film at Australia Golden Koala Chinese Film Festival 2017 <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3185602}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|front_cover_2016}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.frontcoverthemovie.com}}\n\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related drama films]]\n[[Category:Gay-related films]]\n[[Category:Films by Chinese directors]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Front Cover\n| image          = Front Cover poster.jpg\n| director       = Ray Yeung\n| producer       = Kaer Vanice, Chowee Leow, Stan Guingon\n| screenplay     = Ray Yeung\n| starring       = Jake Choi, James Chen, Elizabeth Sung, Jennifer Neals Page, Sonia Villani, Li Jun 