{"title_page": "Valleyspeak", "text_new": "{{short description|American sociolect}}'''Valleyspeak''' or '''Valspeak''' is an American [[sociolect]], originally of the [[San Fernando Valley]] in [[Southern California]]. It is associated with young, upper-middle-class white women called [[Valley girl]]s, although elements of it have spread to other demographics, including men called \"Val dudes\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-25232387|title=More men speaking in girls' 'dialect', study shows|last=Hogenboom|first=Melissa|date=2013-12-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-07-19|language=en-GB}}</ref> This sociolect became an international fad for a certain period in the 1980s and 1990s, with a peak period from around 1981 to 1985. According to the Los Angeles Almanac, Valleyspeak is often characterized by both the steady use of [[High rising terminal|uptalk]] and its vocabulary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.laalmanac.com/LA/la10c.php|title=Valspeak or Valley Speak|website=www.laalmanac.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Many phrases and elements of Valleyspeak, along with [[Surf culture|surfer slang]] and [[skateboarding]] [[slang]], have become stable elements of the [[California English]] dialect lexicon, and in some cases wider [[American English]] such as the widespread use of \"like\" as a [[discourse marker]].\n\n== Language ideology ==\nDue to its place at the center of the entertainment industry, California is one of the main sources worldwide for new cultural and youth trends, including those of language. This lends itself to explicit language ideologies about dialects in the area as they receive more scrutiny than dialects in other nearby regions. Linguistic characteristics of \"[[valley girl]]\" or \"California\" speak are often thought to be \"silly\" and \"superficial\" and seen as a sign of low intelligence. Speakers are also often perceived as \"materialistic\" and \"air-headed\". The use of \"like\" or the quotative phrase \"be like\" are often ideologically linked to California and valley speak despite the now widespread use of the terms among youth, which results to them also receiving the \"superficial\" cast. In the national understanding, California speech is thought to be a product of the combination of valley girl and surfer dude speech, and \"is associated with good English, but never proper\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nA study on regional language ideologies done in California in 2007 found that, despite its prevalence and association with California in past decades, Californians themselves do not consider \"valley girls\" to be an overly prevalent social or linguistic group within the state. State residents listed factors such as immigrant populations and North-South regional slang as more relevant than valley speak within the state.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bucholtz |first=M. |last2=Bermudez |first2=N. |last3=Fung |first3=V. |last4=Edwards |first4=L. |last5=Vargas |first5=R. |year=2007 |title=Hella Nor Cal or Totally So Cal?: The Perceptual Dialectology of California |journal=Journal of English Linguistics |volume=35 |issue=4 |pages=325\u2013352 |doi=10.1177/0075424207307780 |url=https://escholarship.org/content/qt6492j904/qt6492j904.pdf?t=nukrb0 }}</ref>\n\nAmanda Ritchart, a doctoral candidate studying linguistics at the University of California San Diego, analyzed 23-year olds (college age students) from diverse socioeconomic backgrounds and ethnicities, specifically in the Southern California region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/41714-valley-girl-talk-is-like-everywhere.html|title=Valley Girl Talk Is, Like, Everywhere in Southern California|last=December 2013|first=Tia Ghose 05|website=livescience.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> After this study, Ritchart once stated, \"Women used uptalk more frequently than men did. Their pitch rose higher overall, and the rise began much later in the phrase.\" Even though the gender difference is notable, the majority of both men and women speak in uptalk in Southern California. In fact, 100% of the participants used uptalk when they asked a confirming question, such as \"Go all the way to the right in the middle where it says Canyon Hills?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wcuquad.com/6001586/op-ed/the-word-like-used-more-often-than-not-valleyspeak/|title=The word \"like\" used more often than not; valleyspeak|date=2014-04-14|website=The Quad|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the article ''\"What's Up With Upspeak?\"'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://matrix.berkeley.edu/research/whats-upspeak|title=What's Up With Upspeak?|date=2015-09-21|website=Berkeley Social Science|language=en|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref> when women use valleyspeak, it is assumed that they have \"inferior speech\" patterns. For men, the high rise of intonation usually \"plateaued\" at certain points, especially in situations where they didn\u2019t want to be interrupted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/is-valley-girl-speak--like--on-the-rise-/|title=Is Valley Girl Speak, Like, on the Rise?|date=2013-12-07|website=National Geographic News|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref>\n\n== Features and qualifiers  ==\nThe sound of Valleyspeak has these main habits: nasal sound; a duck quack sound; fast-paced run-on sentences; breathiness; uptalk, or the sound of a question; and vocal fry.\n\n*[[Vocal fry]] is usually spoken by young adult women in the United States who speak American English. This speech pattern can be characterized by \"low, creaky vibrations\" or a \"guttural vibration\". Researchers have studied two qualities of this speech pattern, such as the ''jitter'' (variation in pitch) and ''shimmer'' (variation in volume). When women tend to speak with these mannerisms, they are perceived as less competent, less hirable, less trustworthy, or less educated. Prominent examples are [[Kim Kardashian]] and [[Britney Spears]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Naomi |title=Young women, give up the vocal fry and reclaim your strong female voice |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jul/24/vocal-fry-strong-female-voice | issn=0261-3077 | accessdate=6 March 2019 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=24 July 2015}}</ref>\n* [[High rising terminal]] (also called \"up speak\" or \"uptalk\") is a defining feature of Valleyspeak. Statements have a rising intonation, causing declarative language to appear interrogative to listeners unfamiliar with the dialect. Research on uptalk has found a number of [[Pragmatics|pragmatic]] uses, including confirming that the interlocutor follows what is being said and indicating that the speaker has more to say and so their conversation partner should not interrupt them (also called \"floor holding\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/12/23/overturning-the-myth-of-valley-girl-speak/|title=Overturning the Myth of Valley Girl Speak|last=Hoffman|first=Jan|date=2013-12-23|website=Well|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref> Another use is as a confirmation statement of general agreement, such as \"I know, right?\" or simply \"right?\". The difference between the intonation of a question, confirmation statements, and floor holding is determined by the extent of the rise and its location within the phrase.<ref>Ritchart, A. and Arvaniti, A., 2013. Do we all speak like valley girls? Uptalk in Southern Californian English. ''ASA Lay Language Papers''. from http://2yearamenglish.ucoz.ru/_ld/1/128_uptalk_in_soCal.doc</ref> The high rising terminal feature is most commonly used by women, but it has been adopted by speakers beyond the traditional users of Valleyspeak, including men<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/is-valley-girl-speak--like--on-the-rise-/|title=Is Valley Girl Speak, Like, on the Rise?|date=2013-12-07|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref> and New Zealanders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/articles/200511/valley-girl-talk|title=Valley Girl Talk|website=Psychology Today|language=en|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref>\n* \"[[Like]]\" as a [[discourse marker]]. \"Like\" is used as a [[Filler (linguistics)|filler word]], similar to \"um\" or \"er\", as in, \"I'm, like, about to totally blow chunks.\" When \"like\" is functioning as a discourse marker, the word itself does not semantically change the phrase or sentence. Instead, it provides time for the speaker to formulate what they will say next. The word is always unstressed when used in this way. It is important to note that \"like\" does not always function as a discourse marker in Valspeak. Consider the following two sentences: \"It was like 8 feet deep\" and \"I think that, like, it is entertaining.\" Even though both sentences contain the word \"like,\" they employ it differently. In the former, \"like\" serves as an adverb that is synonymous with \"approximately,\" whereas the latter \"like\" is a discourse marker, adding no additional meaning to the sentence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partofspeech.org/what-part-of-speech-is-like/|title=What Part of Speech is \u201cLIKE\u201d?|date=2014-11-29|website=Part of Speech|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Furthermore, \"like\" is frequently used to introduce quoted speech. For example, a person can recount a conversation by stating, \"So, um, I'm like 'Where did he go?' and she was um, like, 'I don't know, I haven't seen him.'\"<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/8799381/_Valley_girl_-_A_dialect_its_stereotypes_and_the_reality_|title=\u201c \u2018Valley girl\u2019 - A dialect, its stereotypes and the reality\u201d|first=Patrick|last=Ploschnitzki|via=www.academia.edu}}</ref>\n* \"To be like\" as a [[Colloquialism|colloquial]] [[quotative]]. \"Like\" (always unstressed) is used to indicate that what follows is not necessarily an exact quotation of what was said, but captures the meaning and intention of the quoted speech. As an example, in \"And I was like, 'don't ever speak to my boyfriend again'\", the speaker is indicating that they may or may not have literally said those words, but they conveyed that idea. \"Be like\" can introduce both a monologue or direct speech, allowing a speaker to express an attitude, reaction, or thought, or to use the phrase to signal quotation.<ref>Blyth, C., Recktenwald, S., & Wang, J. (1990). I'm like, \"Say What?!\": A New Quotative in American Oral Narrative. ''American Speech,'' ''65''(3), 215-227. doi:10.2307/455910</ref>\n* \"To be all\" or \"to be all like\" are used in the same manner as \"to be like\".\n*\"[[Whatever (slang)|Whatever]].\" or \"As if.\", literally used to express any disbelief.\n*\"Totally\" meaning \"quite\" or \"very\", as in \"I was like, totally surprised that he actually showed up to the party.\"\n*\"Seriously\" is a frequent interjection of approval, or an inquiry of veracity. \n*\"Omigod this is happening...\" Part of the chorus of the opening song \"Omigod You Guys\" from the ''[[Legally Blonde: The Musical \u2013 The Search for Elle Woods|Legally Blonde: The Musical]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lasocialscience.ucla.edu/2018/10/05/what-does-the-l-a-valley-girl-stereotype-say-about-language-and-power/|title=What Does the L.A. Valley Girl Stereotype Say About Language and Power?|last=Editor|first=Managing|date=2018-10-05|website=LA Social Science|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.songfacts.com/facts/cast-of-legally-blonde/omigod-you-guys|title=Omigod You Guys by Cast of Legally Blonde - Songfacts|last=Songfacts|website=www.songfacts.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref>\n*\"So\" in lieu of \"very\"\n*\"Fer shur\" as opposed to \"absolutely\"\n*\"Bitchin'\" instead of \"excellent\"\n*\"Grody\" in place of \"dirty\"\n\n==In popular culture==\nValspeak and the term \"Valley Girl\" were given a wider circulation with the release of a hit 1982 single by [[Frank Zappa]] titled \"[[Valley Girl (song)|Valley Girl]]\", on which his fourteen-year-old daughter [[Moon Zappa]] delivered a monologue in \"Valleyspeak\" behind the music. This song popularized phrases such as \"[[wikt:grody|grody]] to the max\" and \"[[wikt:gag me with a spoon|gag me with a spoon]]\". It also popularized the use of the term \"like\" as a discourse marker, though it did not originate in Valleyspeak.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Nycum|first=Reilly|date=May 2018|title=In Defense of Valley Girl English|url=https://scholarworks.arcadia.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1039&context=thecompass|journal=The Compass|volume=1|pages=23-29|via=}}</ref>\n\nAn early appearance of Valleyspeak and the Valley Girl stereotype was through the character of Jennifer DiNuccio, played by [[Tracy Nelson (actress)|Tracy Nelson]] in the 1982\u20131983 [[sitcom]] ''[[Square Pegs]]''. According to an interview with Nelson included on the 2008 [[DVD]] release of the series, she developed the character's Valleyspeak and personality prior to the Zappa recording becoming popular.<ref>\"Weemawee Yearbook Memories: Tracy Nelson and Claudette Wells\", a featurette on the DVD release ''Square Pegs: The Like, Totally Complete Series&nbsp;... Totally'' (Sony Pictures Home Entertainment, 2008).</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Los Angeles|1980s|1990s}}\n* [[Filler (linguistics)]]\n* [[Jive filter]], a novelty program that translates English into parody forms\n* [[Like (discourse particle)]]\n* ''[[Clueless (film)|Clueless]]'', a 1995 film that prominently features Valleyspeak\n* ''[[Pink Five]]'', a ''[[Star Wars]]'' parody fanfilm about a Valley girl character\n* [[Preppy]]\n* [[Gap Girls]] and [[The Californians (Saturday Night Live)|The Californians]], ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' sketches based on Valley people.\n* [[Sexy baby voice]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9stWRMxc-7k&t=4m27s Origins of Valspeak], YouTube video with Tracy Nelson from [[Square Pegs]] DVD commentary.\n*Language Dossier, \"[https://language-dossier.webs.com/americanslangvalspeak.htm American Slang: Valspeak.]\" \n*cs.utexas.edu: [http://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/jbc/home/chef.html \"Valspeak\" text translator]\n*[https://funtranslations.com/valspeak Valspeak Translator]\n*Blyth, C., Recktenwald, S., & Wang, J. (1990). I'm like, \"Say What?!\": A New Quotative in American Oral Narrative. ''American Speech,'' ''65''(3), 215-227. doi:10.2307/455910\n*Bucholtz, M., Bermudez, N., Fung, V., Edwards, L., & Vargas, R. (2007). Hella Nor Cal or Totally So Cal?: The Perceptual Dialectology of California. Journal of English Linguistics, 35(4), 325\u2013352. doi:10.1177/0075424207307780\n* {{cite journal\n |first       = Eils\n |last        = Lotozo\n |date        = September 4, 2002\n |title       = The way teens talk, like, serves a purpose\n |journal     = [[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]\n |url         = http://www2.jsonline.com/enter/gen/sep02/71334.asp\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081213205331/http://www2.jsonline.com/enter/gen/sep02/71334.asp\n |archivedate = December 13, 2008\n}} Citing {{cite journal\n| first =Muffy E. A. | last =Siegel | year =2002 | month =\n| title =Like: The Discourse Particle and Semantics\n| journal =Journal of Semantics | volume = 19 | issue = 1 | pages =35\u201371\n| url =http://jos.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/19/1/35\n| doi =10.1093/jos/19.1.35\n}}\n*Ploschnitzki, P. (n.d.). \" [https://www.academia.edu/8799381/_Valley_girl_-_A_dialect_its_stereotypes_and_the_reality_ 'Valley girl' - A dialect, its stereotypes and the reality]\".\n*Ritchart, A. and Arvaniti, A., 2013. [http://2yearamenglish.ucoz.ru/_ld/1/128_uptalk_in_soCal.doc Do we all speak like valley girls? Uptalk in Southern Californian English]. ''ASA Lay Language Papers''.\n*Tschorn, A. (2007, August 19). [http://articles.latimes.com/2007/aug/19/image/ig-girls19 You know her type].\n\n*Woo, M. (2015, April 30). [https://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/is-valley-girl-speak--like--on-the-rise-/ Is Valley Girl Speak, Like, on the Rise?] \n*Wolf, N. (2015, July 24). [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jul/24/vocal-fry-strong-female-voice Young women, give up the vocal fry and reclaim your strong female voice]. \n\n[[Category:American slang]]\n[[Category:American English]]\n[[Category:Valleyspeak| ]]\n[[Category:San Fernando Valley]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American sociolect}}'''Valleyspeak''' or '''Valspeak''' is an American [[sociolect]], originally of the [[San Fernando Valley]] in [[Southern California]]. It is associated with young, upper-middle-class white women called [[Valley girl]]s, although elements of it have spread to other demographics, including men called \"Val dudes\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-25232387|title=More men speaking in girls' 'dialect', study shows|last=Hogenboom|first=Melissa|date=2013-12-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-07-19|language=en-GB}}</ref> This sociolect became an international fad for a certain period in the 1980s and 1990s, with a peak period from around 1981 to 1985. According to the Los Angeles Almanac, Valleyspeak is often characterized by both the steady use of [[High rising terminal|uptalk]] and its vocabulary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.laalmanac.com/LA/la10c.php|title=Valspeak or Valley Speak|website=www.laalmanac.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Many phrases and elements of Valleyspeak, along with [[Surf culture|surfer slang]] and [[skateboarding]] [[slang]], have become stable elements of the [[California English]] dialect lexicon, and in some cases wider [[American English]] such as the widespread use of \"like\" as a [[discourse marker]].\n\n== Language ideology ==\nDue to its place at the center of the entertainment industry, California is one of the main sources worldwide for new cultural and youth trends, including those of language. This lends itself to explicit language ideologies about dialects in the area as they receive more scrutiny than dialects in other nearby regions. Linguistic characteristics of \"[[valley girl]]\" or \"California\" speak are often thought to be \"silly\" and \"superficial\" and seen as a sign of low intelligence. Speakers are also often perceived as \"materialistic\" and \"air-headed\". The use of \"like\" or the quotative phrase \"be like\" are often ideologically linked to California and valley speak despite the now widespread use of the terms among youth, which results to them also receiving the \"superficial\" cast. In the national understanding, California speech is thought to be a product of the combination of valley girl and surfer dude speech, and \"is associated with good English, but never proper\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nA study on regional language ideologies done in California in 2007 found that, despite its prevalence and association with California in past decades, Californians themselves do not consider \"valley girls\" to be an overly prevalent social or linguistic group within the state. State residents listed factors such as immigrant populations and North-South regional slang as more relevant than valley speak within the state.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bucholtz |first=M. |last2=Bermudez |first2=N. |last3=Fung |first3=V. |last4=Edwards |first4=L. |last5=Vargas |first5=R. |year=2007 |title=Hella Nor Cal or Totally So Cal?: The Perceptual Dialectology of California |journal=Journal of English Linguistics |volume=35 |issue=4 |pages=325\u2013352 |doi=10.1177/0075424207307780 |url=https://escholarship.org/content/qt6492j904/qt6492j904.pdf?t=nukrb0 }}</ref>\n\nMany researchers, such as Amanda Ritchart, a doctoral candidate studying linguistics at the University of California San Diego, has analyzed 23-year olds (college age students) of many socioeconomic backgrounds and ethnicities, specifically in the Southern California region. Regarding gender and Valleyspeak, especially from research that has been done, \"Women used uptalk more frequently than men did. Their pitch rose higher overall, and the rise began much later in the phrase.\" According to the article ''\"What's Up With Upspeak?\"'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://matrix.berkeley.edu/research/whats-upspeak|title=What's Up With Upspeak?|date=2015-09-21|website=Berkeley Social Science|language=en|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref> when women use valleyspeak, it is assumed that they have \"inferior speech\" patterns. For men, the high rise of intonation usually \"plateaued\" at certain points, especially in situations where they didn\u2019t want to be interrupted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/is-valley-girl-speak--like--on-the-rise-/|title=Is Valley Girl Speak, Like, on the Rise?|date=2013-12-07|website=National Geographic News|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref>\n\n== Features and qualifiers  ==\nThe sound of Valleyspeak has these main habits: nasal sound; a duck quack sound; fast-paced run-on sentences; breathiness; uptalk, or the sound of a question; and vocal fry.\n\n*[[Vocal fry]] is usually spoken by young adult women in the United States who speak American English. This speech pattern can be characterized by \"low, creaky vibrations\" or a \"guttural vibration\". Researchers have studied two qualities of this speech pattern, such as the ''jitter'' (variation in pitch) and ''shimmer'' (variation in volume). When women tend to speak with these mannerisms, they are perceived as less competent, less hirable, less trustworthy, or less educated. Prominent examples are [[Kim Kardashian]] and [[Britney Spears]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Naomi |title=Young women, give up the vocal fry and reclaim your strong female voice |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jul/24/vocal-fry-strong-female-voice | issn=0261-3077 | accessdate=6 March 2019 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=24 July 2015}}</ref>\n* [[High rising terminal]] (also called \"up speak\" or \"uptalk\") is a defining feature of Valleyspeak. Statements have a rising intonation, causing declarative language to appear interrogative to listeners unfamiliar with the dialect. Research on uptalk has found a number of [[Pragmatics|pragmatic]] uses, including confirming that the interlocutor follows what is being said and indicating that the speaker has more to say and so their conversation partner should not interrupt them (also called \"floor holding\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/12/23/overturning-the-myth-of-valley-girl-speak/|title=Overturning the Myth of Valley Girl Speak|last=Hoffman|first=Jan|date=2013-12-23|website=Well|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref> Another use is as a confirmation statement of general agreement, such as \"I know, right?\" or simply \"right?\". The difference between the intonation of a question, confirmation statements, and floor holding is determined by the extent of the rise and its location within the phrase.<ref>Ritchart, A. and Arvaniti, A., 2013. Do we all speak like valley girls? Uptalk in Southern Californian English. ''ASA Lay Language Papers''. from http://2yearamenglish.ucoz.ru/_ld/1/128_uptalk_in_soCal.doc</ref> The high rising terminal feature is most commonly used by women, but it has been adopted by speakers beyond the traditional users of Valleyspeak, including men<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/is-valley-girl-speak--like--on-the-rise-/|title=Is Valley Girl Speak, Like, on the Rise?|date=2013-12-07|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref> and New Zealanders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/articles/200511/valley-girl-talk|title=Valley Girl Talk|website=Psychology Today|language=en|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref>\n* \"[[Like]]\" as a [[discourse marker]]. \"Like\" is used as a [[Filler (linguistics)|filler word]], similar to \"um\" or \"er\", as in, \"I'm, like, about to totally blow chunks.\" When \"like\" is functioning as a discourse marker, the word itself does not semantically change the phrase or sentence. Instead, it provides time for the speaker to formulate what they will say next. The word is always unstressed when used in this way. It is important to note that \"like\" does not always function as a discourse marker in Valspeak. Consider the following two sentences: \"It was like 8 feet deep\" and \"I think that, like, it is entertaining.\" Even though both sentences contain the word \"like,\" they employ it differently. In the former, \"like\" serves as an adverb that is synonymous with \"approximately,\" whereas the latter \"like\" is a discourse marker, adding no additional meaning to the sentence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partofspeech.org/what-part-of-speech-is-like/|title=What Part of Speech is \u201cLIKE\u201d?|date=2014-11-29|website=Part of Speech|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Furthermore, \"like\" is frequently used to introduce quoted speech. For example, a person can recount a conversation by stating, \"So, um, I'm like 'Where did he go?' and she was um, like, 'I don't know, I haven't seen him.'\"<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/8799381/_Valley_girl_-_A_dialect_its_stereotypes_and_the_reality_|title=\u201c \u2018Valley girl\u2019 - A dialect, its stereotypes and the reality\u201d|first=Patrick|last=Ploschnitzki|via=www.academia.edu}}</ref>\n* \"To be like\" as a [[Colloquialism|colloquial]] [[quotative]]. \"Like\" (always unstressed) is used to indicate that what follows is not necessarily an exact quotation of what was said, but captures the meaning and intention of the quoted speech. As an example, in \"And I was like, 'don't ever speak to my boyfriend again'\", the speaker is indicating that they may or may not have literally said those words, but they conveyed that idea. \"Be like\" can introduce both a monologue or direct speech, allowing a speaker to express an attitude, reaction, or thought, or to use the phrase to signal quotation.<ref>Blyth, C., Recktenwald, S., & Wang, J. (1990). I'm like, \"Say What?!\": A New Quotative in American Oral Narrative. ''American Speech,'' ''65''(3), 215-227. doi:10.2307/455910</ref>\n* \"To be all\" or \"to be all like\" are used in the same manner as \"to be like\".\n*\"[[Whatever (slang)|Whatever]].\" or \"As if.\", literally used to express any disbelief.\n*\"Totally\" meaning \"quite\" or \"very\", as in \"I was like, totally surprised that he actually showed up to the party.\"\n*\"Seriously\" is a frequent interjection of approval, or an inquiry of veracity. \n*\"Omigod this is happening...\" Part of the chorus of the opening song \"Omigod You Guys\" from the ''[[Legally Blonde: The Musical \u2013 The Search for Elle Woods|Legally Blonde: The Musical]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lasocialscience.ucla.edu/2018/10/05/what-does-the-l-a-valley-girl-stereotype-say-about-language-and-power/|title=What Does the L.A. Valley Girl Stereotype Say About Language and Power?|last=Editor|first=Managing|date=2018-10-05|website=LA Social Science|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.songfacts.com/facts/cast-of-legally-blonde/omigod-you-guys|title=Omigod You Guys by Cast of Legally Blonde - Songfacts|last=Songfacts|website=www.songfacts.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref>\n*\"So\" in lieu of \"very\"\n*\"Fer shur\" as opposed to \"absolutely\"\n*\"Bitchin'\" instead of \"excellent\"\n*\"Grody\" in place of \"dirty\"\n\n==In popular culture==\nValspeak and the term \"Valley Girl\" were given a wider circulation with the release of a hit 1982 single by [[Frank Zappa]] titled \"[[Valley Girl (song)|Valley Girl]]\", on which his fourteen-year-old daughter [[Moon Zappa]] delivered a monologue in \"Valleyspeak\" behind the music. This song popularized phrases such as \"[[wikt:grody|grody]] to the max\" and \"[[wikt:gag me with a spoon|gag me with a spoon]]\". It also popularized the use of the term \"like\" as a discourse marker, though it did not originate in Valleyspeak.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Nycum|first=Reilly|date=May 2018|title=In Defense of Valley Girl English|url=https://scholarworks.arcadia.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1039&context=thecompass|journal=The Compass|volume=1|pages=23-29|via=}}</ref>\n\nAn early appearance of Valleyspeak and the Valley Girl stereotype was through the character of Jennifer DiNuccio, played by [[Tracy Nelson (actress)|Tracy Nelson]] in the 1982\u20131983 [[sitcom]] ''[[Square Pegs]]''. According to an interview with Nelson included on the 2008 [[DVD]] release of the series, she developed the character's Valleyspeak and personality prior to the Zappa recording becoming popular.<ref>\"Weemawee Yearbook Memories: Tracy Nelson and Claudette Wells\", a featurette on the DVD release ''Square Pegs: The Like, Totally Complete Series&nbsp;... Totally'' (Sony Pictures Home Entertainment, 2008).</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Los Angeles|1980s|1990s}}\n* [[Filler (linguistics)]]\n* [[Jive filter]], a novelty program that translates English into parody forms\n* [[Like (discourse particle)]]\n* ''[[Clueless (film)|Clueless]]'', a 1995 film that prominently features Valleyspeak\n* ''[[Pink Five]]'', a ''[[Star Wars]]'' parody fanfilm about a Valley girl character\n* [[Preppy]]\n* [[Gap Girls]] and [[The Californians (Saturday Night Live)|The Californians]], ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' sketches based on Valley people.\n* [[Sexy baby voice]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9stWRMxc-7k&t=4m27s Origins of Valspeak], YouTube video with Tracy Nelson from [[Square Pegs]] DVD commentary.\n*Language Dossier, \"[https://language-dossier.webs.com/americanslangvalspeak.htm American Slang: Valspeak.]\" \n*cs.utexas.edu: [http://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/jbc/home/chef.html \"Valspeak\" text translator]\n*[https://funtranslations.com/valspeak Valspeak Translator]\n*Blyth, C., Recktenwald, S., & Wang, J. (1990). I'm like, \"Say What?!\": A New Quotative in American Oral Narrative. ''American Speech,'' ''65''(3), 215-227. doi:10.2307/455910\n*Bucholtz, M., Bermudez, N., Fung, V., Edwards, L., & Vargas, R. (2007). Hella Nor Cal or Totally So Cal?: The Perceptual Dialectology of California. Journal of English Linguistics, 35(4), 325\u2013352. doi:10.1177/0075424207307780\n* {{cite journal\n |first       = Eils\n |last        = Lotozo\n |date        = September 4, 2002\n |title       = The way teens talk, like, serves a purpose\n |journal     = [[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]\n |url         = http://www2.jsonline.com/enter/gen/sep02/71334.asp\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081213205331/http://www2.jsonline.com/enter/gen/sep02/71334.asp\n |archivedate = December 13, 2008\n}} Citing {{cite journal\n| first =Muffy E. A. | last =Siegel | year =2002 | month =\n| title =Like: The Discourse Particle and Semantics\n| journal =Journal of Semantics | volume = 19 | issue = 1 | pages =35\u201371\n| url =http://jos.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/19/1/35\n| doi =10.1093/jos/19.1.35\n}}\n*Ploschnitzki, P. (n.d.). \" [https://www.academia.edu/8799381/_Valley_girl_-_A_dialect_its_stereotypes_and_the_reality_ 'Valley girl' - A dialect, its stereotypes and the reality]\".\n*Ritchart, A. and Arvaniti, A., 2013. [http://2yearamenglish.ucoz.ru/_ld/1/128_uptalk_in_soCal.doc Do we all speak like valley girls? Uptalk in Southern Californian English]. ''ASA Lay Language Papers''.\n*Tschorn, A. (2007, August 19). [http://articles.latimes.com/2007/aug/19/image/ig-girls19 You know her type].\n\n*Woo, M. (2015, April 30). [https://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/is-valley-girl-speak--like--on-the-rise-/ Is Valley Girl Speak, Like, on the Rise?] \n*Wolf, N. (2015, July 24). [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jul/24/vocal-fry-strong-female-voice Young women, give up the vocal fry and reclaim your strong female voice]. \n\n[[Category:American slang]]\n[[Category:American English]]\n[[Category:Valleyspeak| ]]\n[[Category:San Fernando Valley]]\n", "name_user": "King nick", "label": "safe", "comment": "added more detail to the ritchart study", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valleyspeak"}
{"title_page": "Denel NTW-20", "text_new": "{{short description|A South African anti-materiel rifle}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name= Denel NTW-20\n| image=File:NTW-20 rifle.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n|caption= A Denel NTW-20 on display\n|origin= South Africa\n|type= [[Anti-materiel rifle]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged=yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n|service= 1998\u2013present\n|wars=\n<!-- Production history -->\n|designer=Tony Neophytou\n|design_date=1995\n|manufacturer=[[Denel Land Systems]]\n|production_date=\n|number=\n|variants= NTW 20, NTW 14.5, NTW 20\u00d7110mm\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight= 31 kg (NTW 20),<br />34 kg (NTW 14.5)\n|length= 1,795 mm (NTW 20),<br />2,015 mm (NTW 14.5)\n|part_length= 1,000 mm (NTW 20),<br />1,220 mm (NTW 14.5)\n|crew= Two; rifle breaks down into two parts for transport and fits into two backpacks weighing 15kg each, one containing the weapon receiver section, while the other contains the barrel and ammunition\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge= [[20\u00d782mm]] (NTW 20)<br>[[Hispano-Suiza HS.404|20\u00d7110mm Hispano]] (NTW 20\u00d7110mm)<br> [[14.5\u00d7114mm]] (NTW 14.5)\n|calibre=\n|action= [[Bolt action]], recoiling barrel\n|rate=\n|velocity= 720 m/s (20\u00d782mm)<br>820 m/s (20\u00d7110mm)<br>1,000 m/s (14.5\u00d7114mm)\n|range= 1,500m (20\u00d782mm)<br>1,800m (20\u00d7110mm)<br>2,300m (14.5\u00d7114mm)\n|max_range=\n|feed= 3-round detachable [[box magazine]] (20\u00d782mm and 14.5\u00d7114mm)<br>Single shot (20\u00d7110mm)\n|sights=  8 \u00d7 56 Lynx [[Telescopic sight]]\n}}\n\nThe '''NTW-20''' is a South African [[anti-materiel rifle]], developed by Denel Mechem in the 1990s. It is intended for deployment against targets including parked aircraft, telecommunication masts, power lines, missile sites, [[radar]] installations, refineries, [[satellite dish]]es, gun emplacements, [[bunker]]s and personnel, using a range of specialised projectiles.<ref name=\"Kokalis\">Kokalis, Peter: ''Weapons Tests And Evaluations: The Best Of Soldier Of Fortune'', page 223. Paladin Press, 2001.</ref> As with other weapons of this type, it can also be used for [[Counter-sniper tactics|counter sniping]] and [[ordnance disposal]] (shooting explosive ordnance from a safe distance).{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n==Development==\nThe weapon was designed by Tony Neophytou (co-designer of the [[Neostead]] combat [[shotgun]]). Development of the system began in August 1995 under the \"Aerotek\" name and a working prototype was ready for testing four and a half months later. This rapid progress was made possible by Neophytou's expertise in the field of recoil reduction systems, having worked on helicopter turrets in the past. To further reduce the amount of research and development, the project recycled the barrel, bolt and barrel extension of the existing [[Vektor GA-1|Vektor GA1]] [[automatic cannon]].<ref name=\"Kokalis_224\">Kokalis, 224</ref> It was put into production by [[Denel Land Systems]] in two versions; 20 x 110<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denellandsystems.co.za/infantry_weapons/NTW20_110.html |title=Infantry Weapons \u2013 NTW 20 X 110 |publisher=Denel Land Systems |date= |accessdate=21 May 2013}}</ref> and 20 x 82.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denellandsystems.co.za/infantry_weapons/NTW20_82.html |title=Infantry Weapons \u2013 NTW 20 X 82 |publisher=Denel Land Systems |date= |accessdate=21 May 2013}}</ref> The latter model is also available in 14.5 x 114 and conversion between the calibres can be done in the field by swapping the barrel and bolt assembly. The significantly larger 20 x 110 model cannot be converted to another calibre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.militaryfactory.com/smallarms/detail.asp?smallarms_id=267 |title=Denel NTW-20 \u2013 Anti-Materiel Rifle \u2013 History, Specs and Pictures \u2013 Military, Security and Civilian Guns and Equipment |publisher=Militaryfactory.com |date=20 August 2012 |accessdate=21 May 2013}}</ref> The rifle was accepted into service with the [[South African National Defence Force]] in 1998.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}.\n\n==Features==\nSwitching between the two calibres of the NTW ([[20\u00d782mm]] and [[14.5\u00d7114mm]]) requires changing the bolt, barrel, sighting gear and magazine.  (A third variant, the NTW 20\u00d7110mm has been developed, but is not designed for barrel calibre switching.) Caliber switching the NTW 20/14.5 can be accomplished in the field without specialised tools. The magazine protrudes from the left side of the receiver. The NTW can be disassembled and packed into two backpacks for carriage. A [[muzzle brake]] is fitted on the end of the barrel which absorbs an estimated 50%\u201360% of recoil. This is further supplemented by a buffered slide in the receiver.\n\n==Variants==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:98%;\"\n!\n! style=\"width:170px;\"| 20\u00d782mm\n! style=\"width:170px;\"| 14.5\u00d7114mm\n! style=\"width:170px;\"| 20\u00d7110mm\n|-\n!Cartridge\n| [[20\u00d782mm]]\n| [[14.5\u00d7114mm]]\n| [[Hispano-Suiza HS.404|20\u00d7110mm Hispano-Suiza]]\n|-\n!Weight (empty)\n| {{convert|30.0|kg|lbs|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| {{convert|34.0|kg|lbs|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|32.0|kg|lbs|abbr=on}}\n|-\n!Overall length\n| {{convert|1800|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|2016|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|1800|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n|-\n!Rifling (1 full turn)\n| {{convert|560|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|408|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n|\n|-\n!Length of barrel\n| {{convert|1000|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|1220|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|1000|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n|-\n!Muzzle velocity\n| {{convert|720|m/s|ft/s|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|1000|m/s|ft/s|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|820|m/s|ft/s|abbr=on}}\n|-\n!Muzzle energy\n| 28,000 J ||32,000 J || ~40,000 J\n|-\n!Effective range\n| > {{convert|1600|m|yd|abbr=on}}\n| > {{convert|2400|m|yd|abbr=on}}\n| > {{convert|1800|m|yd|abbr=on}}\n|}\n\n==Influence==\n[[Denel Land Systems]] was contracted to supply weapon systems for the [[Indian Armed Forces]], including anti-materiel rifles and [[Self-propelled artillery|self-propelled howitzers]]. However, following allegations that it had paid kickbacks to secure a deal for anti-materiel rifles, Denel was black-listed by the government. Subsequently, the [[Ordnance Factory Tiruchirappalli]] (OFT), in association with the [[Defence Research and Development Organisation]] ([[DRDO]]), began developing an indigenous anti-material rifle called [[Vidhwansak]], which borrowed heavily from the Denel NTW-20. The development of [[Vidhwansak]] was completed in November 2005.<ref name=\"Tribune 2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060206/nation.htm#7|title=Ordnance factories bag order for 30,000 carbines|date=5 February 2006|accessdate=7 June 2009|author=Girja Shankar Kaura|publisher=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]}}</ref> The embargo against Denel was lifted in 2018 after investigations found the allegations to have been false.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Guy |title=Denel finally removed from Indian blacklist {{!}} defenceWeb |url=http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=53050:denel-finally-removed-from-indian-blacklist7:Industry |accessdate=19 November 2018 |work=www.defenceweb.co.za |date=10 September 2018 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n*In the 2009 film ''[[District 9]]'', a Denel NTW-20 rifle is used to attack an alien [[Mecha|mech suit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2009/08/27/the-weapons-of-district-9/|title=The Weapons of District 9 -|date=2009-08-27|work=The Firearm Blog|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=District 9 (2009)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1136608/trivia|access-date=2018-11-25}}</ref>\n\n*The designers of the Sniper Rifle System 99 Anti-Mat\u00e9riel (SRS99, formally known as the Special Applications Rifle) from the ''[[Halo (franchise)|Halo]]'' video game franchise used the Denel NTW-20 as inspiration.<ref>http://www.giantbomb.com/forums/off-topic-31/meet-the-real-life-version-of-the-halo-sniper-rifl-5509/</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[RT-20 (rifle)]]\n* [[Truvelo Sniper Rifles]]\n* [[Longest recorded sniper kills]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book| last = Kokalis| first = Peter| authorlink = | author2 = | year = 2001| chapter =| title = Weapons Tests And Evaluations: The Best Of Soldier Of Fortune| publisher = Paladin Press| location = Boulder, CO| isbn = 978-1-58160-122-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180121043801/http://www.denellandsystems.co.za/products/infantry-weapons NTW 20 anti-materiel rifle 20 x 82 mm]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180121043801/http://www.denellandsystems.co.za/products/infantry-weapons NTW 20 anti-materiel rifle 20 x 110 mm HS]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090203114928/http://modernfirearms.net/sniper/sn55-e.htm Modern Firearms Page]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180917034810/http://admin.denel.co.za/uploads/NTW_20x82.pdf]\n\n{{Denel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Denel Ntw-20}}\n[[Category:14.5\u00d7114mm sniper rifles]]\n[[Category:20 mm artillery]]\n[[Category:Bolt-action rifles]]\n[[Category:20mm sniper rifles]]\n[[Category:Post\u2013Cold War weapons of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Denel]]\n[[Category:Anti-materiel rifles]]\n[[Category:Single-shot rifles]]\n[[Category:Weapons and ammunition introduced in 1998]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A South African anti-materiel rifle}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name= Denel NTW-20\n| image=File:NTW-20 rifle.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n|caption= A Denel NTW-20 on display\n|origin= South Africa\n|type= [[Anti-materiel rifle]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged=yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n|service= 1998\u2013present\n|wars=\n<!-- Production history -->\n|designer=Tony Neophytou\n|design_date=1995\n|manufacturer=[[Denel Land Systems]]\n|production_date=\n|number=\n|variants= NTW 20, NTW 14.5, NTW 20\u00d7110mm\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight= 31 kg (NTW 20),<br />34 kg (NTW 14.5)\n|length= 1,795 mm (NTW 20),<br />2,015 mm (NTW 14.5)\n|part_length= 1,000 mm (NTW 20),<br />1,220 mm (NTW 14.5)\n|crew= Two; rifle breaks down into two parts for transport and fits into two backpacks weighing 15kg each, one containing the weapon receiver section, while the other contains the barrel and ammunition\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge= [[20\u00d782mm]] (NTW 20)<br>[[Hispano-Suiza HS.404|20\u00d7110mm Hispano]] (NTW 20\u00d7110mm)<br> [[14.5\u00d7114mm]] (NTW 14.5)\n|calibre=\n|action= [[Bolt action]], recoiling barrel\n|rate=\n|velocity= 720 m/s (20\u00d782mm)<br>820 m/s (20\u00d7110mm)<br>1,000 m/s (14.5\u00d7114mm)\n|range= 1,500m (20\u00d782mm)<br>1,800m (20\u00d7110mm)<br>2,300m (14.5\u00d7114mm)\n|max_range=\n|feed= 3-round detachable [[box magazine]] (20\u00d782mm and 14.5\u00d7114mm)<br>Single shot (20\u00d7110mm)\n|sights=  8 \u00d7 56 Lynx [[Telescopic sight]]\n}}\n\nThe '''NTW-20''' is a South African [[anti-materiel rifle]], developed by Denel Mechem in the 1990s. It is intended for deployment against targets including parked aircraft, telecommunication masts, power lines, missile sites, [[radar]] installations, refineries, [[satellite dish]]es, gun emplacements, [[bunker]]s and personnel, using a range of specialised projectiles.<ref name=\"Kokalis\">Kokalis, Peter: ''Weapons Tests And Evaluations: The Best Of Soldier Of Fortune'', page 223. Paladin Press, 2001.</ref> As with other weapons of this type, it can also be used for [[Counter-sniper tactics|counter sniping]] and [[ordnance disposal]] (shooting explosive ordnance from a safe distance).{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n==Development==\nThe weapon was designed by Tony Neophytou (co-designer of the [[Neostead]] combat [[shotgun]]). Development of the system began in August 1995 under the \"Aerotek\" name and a working prototype was ready for testing four and a half months later. This rapid progress was made possible by Neophytou's expertise in the field of recoil reduction systems, having worked on helicopter turrets in the past. To further reduce the amount of research and development, the project recycled the barrel, bolt and barrel extension of the existing [[Vektor GA-1|Vektor GA1]] [[automatic cannon]].<ref name=\"Kokalis_224\">Kokalis, 224</ref> It was put into production by [[Denel Land Systems]] in two versions; 20 x 110<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denellandsystems.co.za/infantry_weapons/NTW20_110.html |title=Infantry Weapons \u2013 NTW 20 X 110 |publisher=Denel Land Systems |date= |accessdate=21 May 2013}}</ref> and 20 x 82.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denellandsystems.co.za/infantry_weapons/NTW20_82.html |title=Infantry Weapons \u2013 NTW 20 X 82 |publisher=Denel Land Systems |date= |accessdate=21 May 2013}}</ref> The latter model is also available in 14.5 x 114 and conversion between the calibres can be done in the field by swapping the barrel and bolt assembly. The significantly larger 20 x 110 model cannot be converted to another calibre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.militaryfactory.com/smallarms/detail.asp?smallarms_id=267 |title=Denel NTW-20 \u2013 Anti-Materiel Rifle \u2013 History, Specs and Pictures \u2013 Military, Security and Civilian Guns and Equipment |publisher=Militaryfactory.com |date=20 August 2012 |accessdate=21 May 2013}}</ref> The rifle was accepted into service with the [[South African National Defence Force]] in 1998.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}. It is also more limited in that it is a single shot-only rifle, rather than feeding rounds from a magazine.\n\n==Features==\nSwitching between the two calibres of the NTW ([[20\u00d782mm]] and [[14.5\u00d7114mm]]) requires changing the bolt, barrel, sighting gear and magazine.  (A third variant, the NTW 20\u00d7110mm has been developed, but is not designed for barrel calibre switching.) Caliber switching the NTW 20/14.5 can be accomplished in the field without specialised tools. The magazine protrudes from the left side of the receiver. The NTW can be disassembled and packed into two backpacks for carriage. A [[muzzle brake]] is fitted on the end of the barrel which absorbs an estimated 50%\u201360% of recoil. This is further supplemented by a buffered slide in the receiver.\n\n==Variants==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:98%;\"\n!\n! style=\"width:170px;\"| 20\u00d782mm\n! style=\"width:170px;\"| 14.5\u00d7114mm\n! style=\"width:170px;\"| 20\u00d7110mm\n|-\n!Cartridge\n| [[20\u00d782mm]]\n| [[14.5\u00d7114mm]]\n| [[Hispano-Suiza HS.404|20\u00d7110mm Hispano-Suiza]]\n|-\n!Weight (empty)\n| {{convert|30.0|kg|lbs|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| {{convert|34.0|kg|lbs|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|32.0|kg|lbs|abbr=on}}\n|-\n!Overall length\n| {{convert|1800|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|2016|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|1800|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n|-\n!Rifling (1 full turn)\n| {{convert|560|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|408|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n|\n|-\n!Length of barrel\n| {{convert|1000|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|1220|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|1000|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n|-\n!Muzzle velocity\n| {{convert|720|m/s|ft/s|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|1000|m/s|ft/s|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|820|m/s|ft/s|abbr=on}}\n|-\n!Muzzle energy\n| 28,000 J ||32,000 J || ~40,000 J\n|-\n!Effective range\n| > {{convert|1600|m|yd|abbr=on}}\n| > {{convert|2400|m|yd|abbr=on}}\n| > {{convert|1800|m|yd|abbr=on}}\n|}\n\n==Influence==\n[[Denel Land Systems]] was contracted to supply weapon systems for the [[Indian Armed Forces]], including anti-materiel rifles and [[Self-propelled artillery|self-propelled howitzers]]. However, following allegations that it had paid kickbacks to secure a deal for anti-materiel rifles, Denel was black-listed by the government. Subsequently, the [[Ordnance Factory Tiruchirappalli]] (OFT), in association with the [[Defence Research and Development Organisation]] ([[DRDO]]), began developing an indigenous anti-material rifle called [[Vidhwansak]], which borrowed heavily from the Denel NTW-20. The development of [[Vidhwansak]] was completed in November 2005.<ref name=\"Tribune 2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060206/nation.htm#7|title=Ordnance factories bag order for 30,000 carbines|date=5 February 2006|accessdate=7 June 2009|author=Girja Shankar Kaura|publisher=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]}}</ref> The embargo against Denel was lifted in 2018 after investigations found the allegations to have been false.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Guy |title=Denel finally removed from Indian blacklist {{!}} defenceWeb |url=http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=53050:denel-finally-removed-from-indian-blacklist7:Industry |accessdate=19 November 2018 |work=www.defenceweb.co.za |date=10 September 2018 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n*In the 2009 film ''[[District 9]]'', a Denel NTW-20 rifle is used to attack an alien [[Mecha|mech suit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2009/08/27/the-weapons-of-district-9/|title=The Weapons of District 9 -|date=2009-08-27|work=The Firearm Blog|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=District 9 (2009)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1136608/trivia|access-date=2018-11-25}}</ref>\n\n*The designers of the Sniper Rifle System 99 Anti-Mat\u00e9riel (SRS99, formally known as the Special Applications Rifle) from the ''[[Halo (franchise)|Halo]]'' video game franchise used the Denel NTW-20 as inspiration.<ref>http://www.giantbomb.com/forums/off-topic-31/meet-the-real-life-version-of-the-halo-sniper-rifl-5509/</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[RT-20 (rifle)]]\n* [[Truvelo Sniper Rifles]]\n* [[Longest recorded sniper kills]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book| last = Kokalis| first = Peter| authorlink = | author2 = | year = 2001| chapter =| title = Weapons Tests And Evaluations: The Best Of Soldier Of Fortune| publisher = Paladin Press| location = Boulder, CO| isbn = 978-1-58160-122-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180121043801/http://www.denellandsystems.co.za/products/infantry-weapons NTW 20 anti-materiel rifle 20 x 82 mm]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180121043801/http://www.denellandsystems.co.za/products/infantry-weapons NTW 20 anti-materiel rifle 20 x 110 mm HS]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090203114928/http://modernfirearms.net/sniper/sn55-e.htm Modern Firearms Page]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180917034810/http://admin.denel.co.za/uploads/NTW_20x82.pdf]\n\n{{Denel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Denel Ntw-20}}\n[[Category:14.5\u00d7114mm sniper rifles]]\n[[Category:20 mm artillery]]\n[[Category:Bolt-action rifles]]\n[[Category:20mm sniper rifles]]\n[[Category:Post\u2013Cold War weapons of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Denel]]\n[[Category:Anti-materiel rifles]]\n[[Category:Single-shot rifles]]\n[[Category:Weapons and ammunition introduced in 1998]]\n", "name_user": "Awweccshon1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDevelopment", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denel_NTW-20"}
{"title_page": "Heather Ashton", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Heather Ashton\n| birth_name = Chrystal Heather Champion\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1929|07|11|df=y}}\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2019|09|15|1929|08|11|df=y}}\n| alma_mater = [[Somerville College, Oxford]]\n| workplaces = [[Newcastle University]]\n| birth_place = [[Dehradun]], India\n| death_place = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England\n| fields = Medicine, [[Psychopharmacology]]\n}}\n\n'''Heather Ashton''' {{Post-nominals|country=UK|FRCP}} (11 July 1929 \u2013 15 September 2019) was a British [[Psychopharmacology|psychopharmacologist]] and physician.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2019/nov/18/heather-ashton-obituary|title=Heather Ashton obituary|last=Ferry|first=Georgina|date=2019-11-18|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> She is best known for her clinical and research work on [[Benzodiazepine dependence|benzodiazepene dependence]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/03/science/dr-heather-ashton-dead.html|title=Dr. Heather Ashton, 90, Dies; Helped People Quit Anxiety Drugs|last=Sheikh|first=Knvul|date=2020-01-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://benzo.org.uk/ashcv.htm|title=Professor C Heather Ashton, DM, FRCP - CV|website=benzo.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2019/nov/18/heather-ashton-obituary|title=Heather Ashton obituary|date=2019-11-18|website=Foundation for Excellence in Mental Health Care|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\nChrystal Heather Champion was born in [[Dehradun]], northern [[India]], to [[Harry George Champion|Harry Champion]], a British [[Silviculture|silviculturalist]], and Chrystal (Parsons) Champion, a secretary.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> From the age of six, she attended a boarding school in [[Swanage]], [[Dorset]], England.<ref name=\":0\" /> When WWII began, she was evacuated to [[West Chester, Pennsylvania|West Chester]], [[Pennsylvania]]; during the crossing, her ship was attacked by a [[U-boat]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAshton went on to study Medicine at [[Somerville College, Oxford]],<ref name=\":1\" /> graduating with a First Class Honours Degree (BA) in [[Physiology]] in 1951.<ref name=\":2\" /> She earned her medical degree ([[Doctor of Medicine|DM]]) in 1956.<ref name=\":2\" /> She completed professional training at [[Middlesex Hospital]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She was elected as a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians]], London, in 1975.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1965, Ashton joined the faculty at [[Newcastle University]], first in the Department of Pharmacology and later in the Department of Psychiatry.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> From 1982 to 1994, she ran a [[Benzodiazepine withdrawal syndrome|benzodiazepine withdrawal]] clinic at the [[Royal Victoria Infirmary]] in Newcastle.<ref name=\":1\" /> She was on the executive committee of the North East Council on Addictions.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neca.co.uk/|title=Neca Homepage|website=Neca}}</ref> Ashton also helped set up the British organisation Victims of Tranquillisers (VOT).<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://benzo.org.uk/peart.htm|title=Victims of Tranquillisers - Objectives & Activities|website=benzo.org.uk}}</ref> She also gave evidence to British government committees on tobacco smoking, cannabis and benzodiazepines.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://benzo.org.uk/manual/|title=Benzodiazepines: How They Work & How to Withdraw|website=benzo.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nAshton died on 15 September 2019 at her home in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], at age 90.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Research ==\n\nAshton's developed her expertise in the effects of [[Psychoactive drug|psychoactive drugs]] and the effects of substances such as [[nicotine]] and [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] on the [[brain]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDuring the 1960s, [[Benzodiazepine|benzodiazepines]], like [[diazepam]] and [[temazepam]], had become popular and were seen as safe and effective treatment for anxiety or insomnia.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> One study found that the overdose death rate among patients taking both benzodiazepines and opioids was 10 times higher than among those who only took opioids.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAshton's research on these drugs found that they could be used in the short term, but could lead to physical dependence over the long-term.<ref name=\":1\" /> She also recognised that this form of [[addiction]] was very different from those addicted to illegal drugs.<ref name=\":0\" /> This led to her writing an important manual to help those who were trying to quit their addiction, which is now recognised and used all over the world.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> This book, ''Benzodiazepines: How They Work and How to Withdraw,'' was first published in 1999<ref name=\":4\" />; it has become known as the Ashton Manual and has been translated into 11 languages.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Ashton's research was influential, leading to changes in prescribing practices and guidelines recommended for benzodiazepines in 2013.<ref name=\":1\" /> Her research on [[psychotropic]] drugs led to over 200 journal articles, chapters and books, including over 50 papers concerning benzodiazepines alone.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== References ==\n\n<references />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashton, Heather}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Newcastle University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Somerville College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British psychiatrists]]\n[[Category:Women scientists]]\n[[Category:People from Uttarakhand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Heather Ashton\n| birth_name = Chrystal Heather Champion\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1929|07|11|df=y}}\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2019|09|15|1929|08|11|df=y}}\n| alma_mater = [[Somerville College, Oxford]]\n| workplaces = [[Newcastle University]]\n| birth_place = [[Dehradun]], India\n| death_place = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England\n| fields = Medicine, [[Psychopharmacology]]\n}}\n\n'''Heather Ashton''' {{Post-nominals|country=UK|FRCP}} (11 July 1929 \u2013 15 September 2019) was a British [[Psychopharmacology|psychopharmacologist]] and physician.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2019/nov/18/heather-ashton-obituary|title=Heather Ashton obituary|last=Ferry|first=Georgina|date=2019-11-18|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> She is best known for her clinical and research work on [[Benzodiazepine dependence|benzodiazepene dependence]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/03/science/dr-heather-ashton-dead.html|title=Dr. Heather Ashton, 90, Dies; Helped People Quit Anxiety Drugs|last=Sheikh|first=Knvul|date=2020-01-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://benzo.org.uk/ashcv.htm|title=benzo.org.uk : Professor C Heather Ashton, DM, FRCP - CV|website=benzo.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2019/nov/18/heather-ashton-obituary|title=Heather Ashton obituary|date=2019-11-18|website=Foundation for Excellence in Mental Health Care|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> \n\n== Biography ==\nChrystal Heather Champion was born in [[Dehradun]], northern [[India]], to [[Harry George Champion|Harry Champion]], a British [[Silviculture|silviculturalist]], and Chrystal (Parsons) Champion, a secretary.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> From the age of six, she attended a boarding school in [[Swanage]], [[Dorset]], England.<ref name=\":0\" /> When WWII began, she was evacuated to [[West Chester, Pennsylvania|West Chester]], [[Pennsylvania]]; during the crossing, her ship was attacked by a [[U-boat]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nAshton went on to study Medicine at [[Somerville College, Oxford]],<ref name=\":1\" /> graduating with a First Class Honours Degree (BA) in [[Physiology]] in 1951.<ref name=\":2\" /> She earned her medical degree ([[Doctor of Medicine|DM]]) in 1956.<ref name=\":2\" /> She completed professional training at [[Middlesex Hospital]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She was elected as a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians]], London, in 1975.<ref name=\":2\" />  \n\nIn 1965, Ashton joined the faculty at [[Newcastle University]], first in the Department of Pharmacology and later in the Department of Psychiatry.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> From 1982 to 1994, she ran a [[Benzodiazepine withdrawal syndrome|benzodiazepine withdrawal]] clinic at the [[Royal Victoria Infirmary]] in Newcastle.<ref name=\":1\" /> She was on the executive committee of the North East Council on Addictions.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neca.co.uk/|title=Home|website=Neca}}</ref> Ashton also helped set up the British organisation Victims of Tranquillisers (VOT).<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://benzo.org.uk/peart.htm|title=benzo.org.uk - Victims of Tranquillisers - Objectives & Activities|website=benzo.org.uk}}</ref> She also gave evidence to British government committees on tobacco smoking, cannabis and benzodiazepines.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://benzo.org.uk/manual/|title=benzo.org.uk : Benzodiazepines: How They Work & How to Withdraw, Prof C H Ashton DM, FRCP, 2002|website=benzo.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nAshton died on 15 September 2019 at her home in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], at age 90.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n== Research ==\nAshton's developed her expertise in the effects of [[Psychoactive drug|psychoactive drugs]] and the effects of substances such as [[nicotine]] and [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] on the [[brain]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nDuring the 1960s, [[Benzodiazepine|benzodiazepines]], like [[diazepam]] and [[temazepam]], had become popular and were seen as safe and effective treatment for anxiety or insomnia.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> One study found that the overdose death rate among patients taking both benzodiazepines and opioids was 10 times higher than among those who only took opioids.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nAshton's research on these drugs found that they could be used in the short term, but could lead to physical dependence over the long-term.<ref name=\":1\" /> She also recognised that this form of [[addiction]] was very different from those addicted to illegal drugs.<ref name=\":0\" /> This led to her writing an important manual to help those who were trying to quit their addiction, which is now recognised and used all over the world.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> This book, ''Benzodiazepines: How They Work and How to Withdraw,'' was first published in 1999<ref name=\":4\" />; it has become known as the Ashton Manual and has been translated into 11 languages.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Ashton's research was influential, leading to changes in prescribing practices and guidelines recommended for benzodiazepines in 2013.<ref name=\":1\" /> Her research on [[psychotropic]] drugs led to over 200 journal articles, chapters and books, including over 50 papers concerning benzodiazepines alone.<ref name=\":3\" />\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashton, Heather}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Newcastle University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Somerville College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British psychiatrists]]\n[[Category:Women scientists]]\n[[Category:People from Uttarakhand]]\n", "name_user": "Leela52452", "label": "safe", "comment": "alter: title. misc cosmetic changes.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heather_Ashton"}
{"title_page": "Hernando de Soto Polar", "text_new": "{{For|the Spanish explorer|Hernando de Soto}}\n{{Spanish name|De Soto|Polar}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2013}}\n{{peacock|date=January 2014}}\n}}\n{{Infobox economist\n | school_tradition= [[Austrian School]]<br />[[Chicago school of economics|Chicago School]]\n |alma_mater=[[International School of Geneva]]<br>[[Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies]]| color =\n | image = {{CSS image crop \n|Image         = WTTC Americas Summit - Opening Ceremony & Session 1, Hernando de Soto, President (ILD) (15016116417).jpg\n|bSize         = 1000 \n|cWidth        = 250\n|cHeight       = 350\n|oLeft = 420\n|oTop = 20\n|Location = center \n}}\n | caption =de Soto at the [[World Travel and Tourism Council|WTTC Americas Summit]] in 2014\n | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1941|06|03}}\n | birth_place = [[Arequipa]], [[Peru]]\n | death_date =\n | death_place =\n | nationality = [[Per\u00fa|Peruvian]]\n |institution=[[Institute for Liberty and Democracy]]| field = The economics of the [[informal sector]],<br>research in [[property rights]] theory\n | influences = [[Milton Friedman]]<br />[[Friedrich Hayek]]\n | influenced =\n | contributions = [[Dead capital]]\n}}\n'''Hernando de Soto Polar''' (or '''Hernando de Soto''' {{IPAc-en|d|\u0259|\u02c8|s|o\u028a|t|o\u028a}}; born 1941) is a Peruvian [[economist]] known for his work on the [[informal economy]] and on the importance of business and [[property rights]]. He is the president of the [[Institute for Liberty and Democracy]] (ILD), located in [[Lima]], Peru.<ref name=ild2>[http://ild.org.pe/hernando-de-soto/158-staff/staff/713-hernando-de-soto-detailed-bio Institute for Liberty and Democracy, \"Hernando de Soto \u2013 Detailed Bio\".] (accessed 16 March 2013)</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nDe Soto was born on 2 June 1941 in [[Arequipa]], Peru. His father was a Peruvian diplomat. After the [[Manuel A. Odr\u00eda|1948 military coup in Peru]], his parents chose exile in Europe, taking their two young sons with them. De Soto was educated in Switzerland, where he attended the [[International School of Geneva]] and then did post-graduate work at the [[Graduate Institute of International Studies]] in [[Geneva]]. He later worked as an economist, corporate executive and consultant. He returned to Peru at the age of 38.<ref>Source: ''Investors Business Daily'', Monday November 6, 2006. p. A4. Leaders & Success. Article by IBD Reinhardt Kraus.</ref> His younger brother \u00c1lvaro served in the Peruvian diplomatic corps in Lima, [[New York City]] and [[Geneva]] and was seconded to United Nations in 1982. He retired from the U.N. in 2007 with the title rank of Assistant Under-Secretary-General; his last position was as the UN Special Coordinator for the Middle East Peace Process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://image.guardian.co.uk/sys-files/Guardian/documents/2007/06/12/DeSotoReport.pdf|title=End of Mission Report|author=Alvaro de Soto|accessdate=31 August 2015}}</ref> He is well known as an international adviser.\n\n==Reforms in Peru and elsewhere==\nBetween 1988 and 1995, he and the [[Institute for Liberty and Democracy]] (ILD) were mainly responsible for some four hundred initiatives, laws, and regulations that led to significant changes in Peru's [[economic system]].<ref>[http://www.theglobalist.com/AuthorBiography.aspx?AuthorId=32 The Globalist | Biography of Hernando de Soto] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911100830/http://www.theglobalist.com/AuthorBiography.aspx?AuthorId=32 |date=2006-09-11 }}</ref>\n\nIn particular, ILD designed the administrative reform of Peru's property system which has given titles to an estimated 1.2 million families and helped some 380,000 firms, which previously operated in the [[black market]], to enter the formal [[economy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnstoncenter.unc.edu/index.php/media-events/jcue-fpg/122-2004-2005fpglecture.html|title=The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill - Website Maintenance|website=www.johnstoncenter.unc.edu|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> This latter task was accomplished through the elimination of bureaucratic \"[[red-tape]]\" and of restrictive registration, licensing and permit laws, which made the opening of new businesses very time-consuming and costly.\n\n[[University of Chicago]] political scientist [[Susan Stokes|Susan C. Stokes]] believes that de Soto's influence helped change the policies of [[Alberto Fujimori]] from a [[Keynesian]] to a [[neoliberal]] approach. De Soto convinced then-president Fujimori to travel to [[New York City]], where they met with [[Javier P\u00e9rez de Cu\u00e9llar]], [[Barber Conable]], [[Enrique V. Iglesias]] (the heads of the United Nations, the International Monetary Fund, and the [[Inter-American Development Bank]]), who convinced him to follow the guidelines for economic policy set by the international financial institutions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/07/01/world/new-peru-leader-in-accord-on-debt.html|title=NEW PERU LEADER IN ACCORD ON DEBT|first=Paul Lewis and Special To the New York|last=Times|accessdate=16 August 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 1990}}</ref> These policies led to a reduction in the rate of [[inflation]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stokes|first1=Susan|title=Are Parties What's Wrong with Democracy in Latin America?|citeseerx=10.1.1.569.1490}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Cato Institute]] and ''[[The Economist]]'' magazine have argued that de Soto's policy prescriptions brought him into conflict with and eventually helped to undermine the [[Shining Path]] (Sendero Luminoso) guerrilla movement. By granting titles to small [[coca]] farmers in the two main coca-growing areas, they argued that the Shining Path was deprived of safe havens, recruits and money, and the leadership was forced to cities where they were arrested.<ref name=\"cato.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cato.org/special/friedman/desoto/index.html|title=Hernando de Soto's Biography|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"economist\">{{cite news| url=https://www.economist.com/people/displayStory.cfm?story_id=1559905 | work=The Economist | title=The economist versus the terrorist | date=30 January 2003}}</ref> A large terrorist attack was launched against the ILD and de Soto in light of the statements by Shining Path leader [[Abimael Guzm\u00e1n]] who saw ILD as a serious threat.<ref>http://nsarchive.gwu.edu/NSAEBB/NSAEBB64/peru33.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ild.org.pe/publications/books/the-other-path|title=The Other Path|website=www.ild.org.pe|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the split with Fujimori, he and his institute designed similar programs in [[El Salvador]], [[Haiti]], [[Tanzania]], and [[Egypt]] and has gained favor with the [[World Bank]], the World Bank-allied international NGO [[Slum Dwellers International]] and the government of [[South Africa]].\n\nSince its work in Peru in the 1980s, his institute, the ILD, has worked in dozens of countries. Heads of state in over 35 countries have sought the ILD's services to discuss how ILD's theories on property rights could potentially improve their economies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ild.org.pe/about-us/impact/achievements|title=Achievements|website=www.ild.org.pe|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe impact of de Soto's institute in the field of development\u2014on political leaders, experts and multi-lateral organizations\u2014is widespread and acknowledged. For example:\n* The ILD's institutional reform program has attracted the interest of strategically key nations concerned with internal conflict and terrorism.\n* The ILD has designed successful reforms that have inspired major initiatives in former client countries such as Egypt, the Philippines, Honduras and Tanzania.\n* The ILD is recognized as the world authority in understanding extralegal economies, influencing the protocols of large multilateral organizations by helping them to understand the realities that the poor and the excluded face, day to day. These include institutions such as the Commission for Legal Empowerment of the Poor, the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB), USAID and the World Bank.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freetochoosemedia.org/broadcasts/power_poor/docs/hernando_de_soto_bio.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721055023/http://www.freetochoosemedia.org/broadcasts/power_poor/docs/hernando_de_soto_bio.pdf |archivedate=2015-07-21 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the ILD turned its attention back to Peru and the plight of the indigenous peoples of the Peruvian Amazon jungle. In response to Peru's President Garc\u00eda's call to all Peruvians to present their proposals toward solving the problems leading to the bloody incidents in Bagua, the ILD has assessed the situation and presented its preliminary findings. ILD has published a short videotaped documentary, ''The Mystery of Capital among the Indigenous Peoples of the Amazon'', summarizing its findings from indigenous communities in Alaska, Canada and the Peruvian jungle.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Enrique Escalante|first1=Edwar|title=Peru: The Mystery of Capital among the Indigenous People of the Amazon|url=http://www.hacer.org/latam/peru-the-mystery-of-capital-among-the-indigenous-people-of-the-amazon-by-edwar-enrique-escalante/|website=Hacer Latin America|accessdate=31 July 2015|date=2009-09-30}}</ref>\n\n==Main thesis==\nThe main message of de Soto's work and writings is that no nation can have a strong [[market economy]] without adequate participation in an information framework that records ownership of property and other economic information.<ref>\"The Destruction of Economic Facts\", by Hernando de Soto. April 28, 2010. Bloomberg ''[[BusinessWeek]]''. Accessed online May 2, 2011 [http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/11_19/b4227060634112.htm]</ref> [[Black market|Unreported, unrecorded economic activity]] results in many small entrepreneurs who lack legal ownership of their property, making it difficult for them to obtain credit, sell the business, or expand. They cannot seek legal remedies to business conflicts in court, since they do not have legal ownership. Lack of information on income prevents governments from collecting taxes and acting for the public welfare.\n\n<blockquote>The existence of such massive exclusion generates two parallel economies, legal and extra legal. An elite minority enjoys the economic benefits of the law and globalization, while the majority of entrepreneurs are stuck in poverty, where their assets\u2014adding up to more than US$10 trillion worldwide\u2014languish as [[dead capital]] in the shadows of the law.<ref name=\"Soto, Hernando 2000\">de Soto, Hernando. 2000. The Mystery of Capital. UK: Black Swan.</ref>\n\nTo survive, to protect their assets, and to do as much business as possible, the extralegals create their own rules. But because these local arrangements are full of shortcomings and are not easily enforceable, the extralegals also create their own social, political and economic problems that affect the society at large.\n\nSince the fall of the Berlin Wall, responsible nations around the developing world have worked hard to make the transition to a market economy, but have in general failed.<ref>de Soto 2000, 1</ref> Populist leaders have used this failure of the free market system to wipe out poverty in the developing world to beat their \"anti-globalization\" drums. But the ILD believes that the real enemy is within the flawed legal systems of developing nations that make it virtually impossible for the majority of their people\u2014and their assets\u2014to gain a stake in the market. The people of these countries have talent, enthusiasm, and an astonishing ability to wring a profit out of practically nothing`.<ref name=\"Soto, Hernando 2000\"/>\n\nWhat the poor majority in the developing world do not have is easy access to the legal system which, in the advanced nations of the world and for the elite in their countries, is the gateway to economic success, for it is in the legal system where property documents are created and standardized according to law. That documentation builds a public memory that permits society to engage in such crucial economic activities as identifying and gaining access to information about individuals, their assets, their titles, rights, charges and obligations; establishing the limits of liability for businesses; knowing an asset's previous economic situation; assuring protection of third parties; and quantifying and valuing assets and rights.<ref>[[Barry Smith (ontologist)|Barry Smith]], \"[http://ontology.buffalo.edu/document_ontology/Seale&deSoto.pdf \"Searle and De Soto: The New Ontology of the Social World]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\", in Barry Smith, David Mark and Isaac Ehrlich (eds.), ''[http://www.opencourtbooks.com/books_n/mystery.htm The Mystery of Capital and the Construction of Social Reality]'', Chicago: Open Court, 2008, 35\u201351.</ref> These public memory mechanisms in turn facilitate such opportunities as access to credit, the establishment of systems of identification, the creation of systems for credit and insurance information, the provision for housing and infrastructure, the issue of shares, the mortgage of property and a host of other economic activities that drive a modern market economy.<ref>Institute for Liberty and Democracy, ''The ILD's war against exclusion'', p. 19. 2009</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Work and research ==\n\nSince 2008, De Soto has been refining his thesis about the importance of property rights to development in response to his organization's findings that a number of new global threats have \"property rights distortions\" at their root. \nIn essays, that appeared from early 2009 into 2012 in media outlets in the U.S. and Europe, De Soto argued that the reason why the U.S. and European economies were mired in recession was the result of a \"knowledge crisis\" not a financial one.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sheridan|first1=Barrett|title=Economy: Slumdogs vs. Wall Street Millionaires|url=http://www.newsweek.com/economy-slumdogs-vs-wall-street-millionaires-82171|website=Newsweek|accessdate=16 August 2015|date=2009-02-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Destruction of Economic Facts|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/stories/2011-04-27/the-destruction-of-economic-facts|website=Bloomberg Business|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Toxic Assets Were Hidden Assets|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123793811398132049|website=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=What if you can't prove you had a house?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/20/opinion/20iht-edsoto.html?_r=1&|website=The New York Times|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Knowledge Crisis Strategy|url=http://www.ild.org.pe/our-work/property-paradigm/the-knowledge-crisis-strategy|website=ild.org.pe|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref>\n \n\"Capitalism lives in two worlds,\" De Soto wrote in the ''Financial Times'' in January 2012. \"There is the visible one of palm trees and Panamanian ships, but it is the other \u2013 made up of the property information cocooned in laws and records \u2013 that allows us to organize and understand fragments of reality and join them creatively.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Knowledge lies at the heart over western capitalism|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/4520ccda-4769-11e1-b847-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?siteedition=uk&_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F4520ccda-4769-11e1-b847-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Duk&_i_referer=&classification=conditional_standard&iab=barrier-app|website=Financial Times|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref> De Soto argued that the knowledge in those public memory systems, which \"helped Capitalism triumph,\" was distorted over the past 15 years or so. \"Until this knowledge system is repaired,\" he wrote, \"neither US nor European capitalism will recover.\" <ref>{{cite web|title=Knowledge lies at the heart of western capitalism|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/4520ccda-4769-11e1-b847-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?siteedition=uk&_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F4520ccda-4769-11e1-b847-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Duk&_i_referer=&classification=conditional_standard&iab=barrier-app#axzz3izOmPxfD|website=Financial Times|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn another series of articles that appeared in US and Europe in 2011, De Soto used the findings of ILD field research in Egypt, Tunisia and Libya to make his case for \"the economic roots of the [[Arab Spring]].\"<ref name=\"wsj.com\">{{cite web|title=The Secret to Reviving the Arab Spring's Promise: Property Rights|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324162304578302403519972088|website=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ft.com\">{{cite web|title=The free market secret of the Arab revolution |url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/653fab0e-0a00-11e1-85ca-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?siteedition=intl&_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F653fab0e-0a00-11e1-85ca-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Dintl&_i_referer=&classification=conditional_standard&iab=barrier-app#axzz3izOmPxfD |website=Financial Times|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"The real Mohamed Bouazizi\">{{cite web|title=The real Mohamed Bouazizi|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2011/12/16/the-real-mohamed-bouazizi/|website=Foreign Policy|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref> The ongoing Arab revolutions, he argued, were \"economic revolutions\" driven mainly by the frustrations of 200 million ordinary Arabs who depended on the informal economy for their livelihoods.<ref name=\"ft.com\"/><ref name=\"The real Mohamed Bouazizi\"/> He pointed to the ILD's earlier 2004 findings in Egypt, which revealed the nation's largest employer with 92% of the property in the informal economy \u2013 assets worth almost $247 billion.<ref name=\"wsj.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=The Economic Roots of the Arab Spring|url=http://www.cfr.org/world/economic-roots-arab-spring/p35234|website=Council of foreign relations|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref>\nAlso, as proof of the extent of desperation among [[MENA]]\u2019s entrepreneurs, he elaborated ILD's exclusive research on [[Mohamed Bouazizi]], the Tunisian street vendor whose public self-immolation in protest of the expropriation of his goods and scale literally sparked the Jasmine Revolution in Tunisia, which spread unrest through the Arab world.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Real Mohamed Bouazizi|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2011/12/16/the-real-mohamed-bouazizi/|website=Foreign Policy|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Economic Inclusion, Democracy, and the Arab Spring|url=http://www.cipe.org/blog/2013/02/11/economic-inclusion-democracy-and-the-arab-spring/#.VdClW3g-Dsl|website=CIPE Development|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Arab Spring unrest was ignited by entrepreneurs facing constraints: Economist|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/06/08/arab-spring-unrest-was-ignited-by-entrepreneurs-facing-constraints-economist/|website=Daily News Egypt|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing core funding from USAID, ILD laid off the majority of their employees from their San Isidro office. In 2014-2015, De Soto and a small team working out of his house began to attempt to guide the political process in Peru, as Presidential elections were due to take place in 2016, by finding solutions to the ongoing national mining crisis. De Soto has been a strong advocate for the formalisation of the informal miners that are scattered throughout Peru.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diariocorreo.pe/ciudad/juliaca-hernando-de-soto-propondra-formalizacion-a-mineros-572009/|title=Juliaca: Hernando de Soto propondr\u00e1 formalizaci\u00f3n a mineros|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gestion.pe/politica/hernando-soto-propone-hacer-comunidades-accionistas-mineras-2136954|title=Hernando de Soto propone hacer a las comunidades accionistas de las mineras|first=Redacci\u00f3n|last=Gesti\u00f3n|date=11 July 2015|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> Since 2014, several large national investment projects, including Las Bambas, and Tia Maria have been disrupted by violent protests by informal miners against government regulation and formal extractive industries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diariocorreo.pe/opinion/conga-tia-maria-y-las-bambas-621747/|title=Conga, T\u00eda Mar\u00eda y Las Bambas|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> In July 2015, the ILD discovered that former Shining Path militants who have taken up the ecological cause were paralyzing some $70 billion in mining investment in Peru.<ref name=\"elcomercio.pe\">{{cite web|url=http://elcomercio.pe/politica/actualidad/soto-hay-us70-mil-mlls-inversion-minera-paralizada-noticia-1823604|title=De Soto: \"Hay US$70 mil mlls. de inversi\u00f3n minera paralizada\"|first=Mariella|last=Balbi|date=5 July 2015|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, recorded video debates between the former extremists and De Soto were published on ILD's YouTube channel and revealed that the Shining Path militants agree that property rights could be an important part of the solution to social conflicts in Peru.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Gpfp1PRJ-c|title=Hernando de Soto Y Anti-Mineros (Segmento #1)|last=Institute for Liberty and Democracy|date=8 July 2015|accessdate=16 August 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> De Soto's stated goal is to determine the roots of informal hostility against multinationals and identify what is needed to build a national social contract on extractive industries that could harmonize their property interests with those of [[Multinational corporation|multinationals]] as opposed to creating conflict.<ref name=\"elcomercio.pe\"/>\n\n=== De Soto applies thesis to terrorism ===\n\nIn October 2014, De Soto published an article in the Wall Street Journal, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-capitalist-cure-for-terrorism-1412973796 The Capitalist Cure for Terrorism], that stated an aggressive agenda for economic empowerment was needed in the Middle East in order to defeat terrorist groups like [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]]. He argued that the U.S. should promote an agenda similar to what was successfully used in Peru to defeat the [[Shining Path]] in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-capitalist-cure-for-terrorism-1412973796|title=The Capitalist Cure for Terrorism|first=Hernando de|last=Soto|date=10 October 2014|accessdate=16 August 2018|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref> He also mentions in the article that local policymakers in the Middle East are missing the fact that if ordinary people cannot play the game legally, they will be far less able to resist a terrorist offensive. The article received praise among high-level global politicians such as US Presidential candidates Rand Paul and Jeb Bush.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/twentysixteen/2015/02/04/exclusive-education-jeb-bush |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-11-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125051438/http://www.nationaljournal.com/twentysixteen/2015/02/04/exclusive-education-jeb-bush |archivedate=2015-11-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/rand-paul-isis-benghazi-and-bringing-us-troops-home-290947|title=Rand Paul on ISIS, Benghazi and Bringing U.S. Troops Home|date=11 December 2014|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOnce again In January 2016, De Soto released his second article, How to Win the War on Terror, which focused on defeating terrorism through promoting strong property rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economia.icaew.com/opinion/global-review-2015-winter/how-to-win-the-war-on-terror|title=How to win the war on terror|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> The article was distributed by Project Syndicate and published in dozens of countries and languages, including in Switzerland by the World Economic Forum in advance of their 2016 forum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2016/01/this-is-how-we-can-win-the-war-on-terror|title=This is how we can win the war on terror|website=World Economic Forum|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/mundo/ee-uu-y-canada/como-ganarle-la-guerra-al-terrorismo-analisis/16490102|title=C\u00f3mo ganarle la guerra al terrorismo / An\u00e1lisis|first=Casa Editorial El|last=Tiempo|website=El Tiempo|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== De Soto challenges Thomas Piketty and approaches Pope Francis ===\n\nIn 2014, De Soto started to refute French economist [[Thomas Piketty]]\u2019s thesis by arguing that his recent attacks against capital in his worldwide best seller book \"[[Capital in the 21st Century]]\" were unjustified.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hernando de Soto refuted the theories of Thomas Piketty|url=http://elcomercio.pe/economia/opinion/hernando-soto-refuto-teorias-thomas-piketty-noticia-1808487|website=El Comercio Portfolio|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> His op-ed article challenging Piketty, \u2018The Poor Against Piketty\u2019 (French - Les pauvres contre Piketty) was first published in France's news magazine ''Le Point'' in April 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/editos-du-point/sebastien-le-fol/les-pauvres-contre-piketty-16-04-2015-1922011_1913.php|title=Les pauvres contre Piketty|last=magazine|first=Le Point|date=2015-04-16|newspaper=Le Point|language=fr-FR|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref>\n\nDe Soto argued that Piketty's statistics ignore the 90 per cent of the world population that lives in developing countries and former Soviet states, whose inhabitants produce and hold their capital in the [[informal sector]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Why Thomas Piketty is wrong about capital in the 21st century|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/comment/why-thomas-piketty-is-wrong-about-capital-in-the-21st-century-10251801.htm|website=The Independent|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> Furthermore, he states that his institute's global research proves that most people actually want more rather than less capital. Finally, he argues that the wars against capital, which Piketty claims are coming, have already begun under Europe's nose in the form of the [[Arab Spring]] in the Middle East and North Africa.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Canoy|first1=Marcel|title=Why De Soto owns Piketty|url=http://www.ild.org.pe/ild-in-the-news/174-2015/971-why-de-soto-owns-piketty|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> \nThe article in English was published in ''[[The Independent]]'' under the title, \u2018[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/comment/why-thomas-piketty-is-wrong-about-capital-in-the-21st-century-10251801.html Why Thomas Piketty is wrong about capital in the 21st century]\u2019, in May 2015 and has since been published in over twenty countries, including in Germany's ''Die Welt'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Die Armen der Welt sind viel reicher als gedacht|url=https://www.welt.de/debatte/kommentare/article142052977/Die-Armen-der-Welt-sind-viel-reicher-als-gedacht.html|website=Die Welt|accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref> Nigeria's ''Ventures Africa'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The Poor Against Piketty|url=http://venturesafrica.com/features/the-poor-against-piketty/|website=Venture Africa|accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref> Spain's ''El Pais'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Los pobres frente a Piketty |url=http://economia.elpais.com/economia/2015/04/29/actualidad/1430325144_581940.html|website=El Pais|accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref> Egypt's ''Youm 7'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youm7.com/story/2015/5/3/90-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%B3%D9%83%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%8A%D8%AD%D8%AA%D9%81%D8%B8%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A8%D8%A3%D9%85%D9%88%D9%84%D9%87%D9%85-%D8%A8%D8%B9%D9%8A%D8%AF%D8%A7-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D8%AD%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%A6%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%8A/2165688#.Vb6QdpNVikq|website=Youm 7|accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref> and Brazil's ''Folha de S.Paulo'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The poor against Piketty|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/ilustrissima/2015/06/1638385-os-pobres-contra-piketty.shtml|website=Folha|accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref> Canada's ''Vancouver Sun'' <ref name=\"tvs1\">{{Cite news|url=https://vancouversun.com/Opinion+poor+against+Piketty/11273987/story.html|title=Opinion: The poor against Piketty|last=Soto|first=Hernando de|newspaper=www.vancouversun.com|language=en-ca|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref> and the ''Miami Herald''.<ref name=\"mh1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/opinion/issues-ideas/article29774506.html|title=Hernando De Soto dissects Thomas Piketty's apocalyptic political thesis|newspaper=miamiherald|language=en|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, De Soto took a break from countering Piketty's work and wrote an article addressing [[Pope Francis]]\u2019s trip to Mexico titled, A Mexican Impasse for the Pope.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/pope-francis-property-rights-by-hernando-de-soto-2016-02?barrier=true|title=A Mexican Impasse for the Pope - by Hernando de Soto|first=Hernando de|last=Soto|date=11 February 2016|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> The article encourages the Pope and the Vatican to address the lack of property rights among the poor in countries like Mexico as a solution to global refugee crises.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neurope.eu/article/the-pope-and-property-rights/|title=The Pope and property rights|date=15 February 2016|accessdate=16 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216092601/http://neurope.eu/article/the-pope-and-property-rights/|archive-date=2016-02-16|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/viewpoints/analysis/helping-those-without-rights-to-step-out-of-the-shadows-381405.html|title=Helping those without rights to step out of the shadows|date=12 February 2016|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nA week later, De Soto published a second article in Fortune Magazine addressing the Pope's and US Republican Presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]]\u2019s public spat over [[Trump's border wall|building a wall]] on the Mexican-USA border. The article titled, What Pope Francis Should Really Say to Donald Trump, conveys five property rights related thoughts that the Pope should use to respond to Trump.<ref name=\"fortune.com\">{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/02/25/pope-francis-donald-trump-immigration/|title=What Pope Francis Should Really Say to Donald Trump|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> The article was well received in the US and led to many different opinion articles featured in Breitbart, Investors Business Daily and Stream.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.investors.com/politics/capital-hill/pope-francis-keeps-listening-to-the-wrong-peruvian/|title=Pope Francis Keeps Listening To The Wrong Peruvian|last=Daily|first=Investor's Business|date=2016-02-19|newspaper=Investor's Business Daily|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://stream.org/pope-francis-hernando-de-soto-poor-property-rights/|title=Pope Francis and Economist Hernando de Soto Agree on One Thing: Free the Poor by Protecting Their Property Rights {{!}} The Stream|date=2016-02-17|newspaper=The Stream|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref>\n\n==Blockchain work==\nIn May 2015, De Soto attended the 1st Annual Block Chain Summit hosted by British billionaire [[Richard Branson]] at his private Caribbean residence, [[Necker Island (British Virgin Islands)|Necker Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blockchainsummit.io/|title=Block Chain Summit|last=Bitfury|website=www.blockchainsummit.io|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virgin.com/richard-branson/shaping-serendipity|title=Shaping serendipity|last=admin|date=16 June 2015|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> De Soto was one of three moderators, along with Michael J. Casey, former ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]'' senior columnist and Matthew Bishop, editor at ''[[The Economist]]''. Advocates of [[blockchain (database)|blockchain]] technology argue that it is well-suited to acting as a public ledger to help achieve De Soto's objective of formalising the informally-held property rights of groups like the indigenous peoples of Peru.<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2015/07/01/venture-capitalist-bill-tai-my-summer-reading-list-commentary.html.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2015/06/02/bitbeat-grand-plans-for-bitcoin-from-necker-island/|title=BitBeat: Grand Plans for Bitcoin From Necker Island|last=Casey|first=Michael J.|newspaper=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortaleciendocapacidades.lamula.pe/2015/05/28/culmina-cumbre-que-reune-a-las-mentes-mas-brillantes-del-mundo/habilidadesdiferentes/|title=CULMINA CUMBRE QUE RE\u00daNE A LAS MENTES M\u00c1S BRILLANTES DEL MUNDO|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ifoldsflip.com/i/598242-techonomy-magazine-2015|title=Techonomy Report - Techonomy Magazine 2015|website=www.ifoldsflip.com|language=en|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2016/03/could-blockchain-technology-help-the-worlds-poor|title=Could blockchain technology help the world's poor?|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref>\n\nDe Soto presented a property application of Bitcoin to [[Sheikh Nahyan bin Mubarak Al Nahyan]] of the [[United Arab Emirates]] and financial authorities of [[Abu Dhabi]] at a second Blockchain summit held in Abu Dhabi in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ild.org.pe/ild-in-the-news/174-2015/1018-de-soto-a-main-speaker-at-block-chain-sumit-in-abu-dhabi|title=De Soto Speaks at a Block Chain Summit in Abu Dhabi|last=Brad|first=Kamloops|website=ild.org.pe|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-01-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055211/http://ild.org.pe/ild-in-the-news/174-2015/1018-de-soto-a-main-speaker-at-block-chain-sumit-in-abu-dhabi|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Praise for work==\nSince the publication of ''The Mystery of Capital'' in 2000 and subsequent translations, his ideas have become increasingly influential in the field of development economics.\n\n[[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine]] chose De Soto as one of the five leading [[Latin American]] innovators of the century in its special May 1999 issue \"Leaders of the New Millennium\", and included him among the 100 most influential people in the world in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.comhttp//content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1970858_1970888_1971022,00.html?xid=fblike|title=The 2004 TIME 100 - TIME|website=TIME.com|accessdate=16 August 2018}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> De Soto was also listed as one of the 15 innovators \"who will reinvent your future\" according to ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine's 85th anniversary edition. In January 2000, ''Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit'', the German development magazine, described De Soto as one of the most important development theoreticians.<ref>[http://www.inwent.org/E+Z/zeitschr/ez100-6.htm Hans-Heinrich Bass und Markus Wauschkuhn: Hernando de Soto \u2013 die Legalisierung des Faktischen, in: E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, 2000, Nr. 1, S. 15\u201318.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730235128/http://www.inwent.org/E+Z/zeitschr/ez100-6.htm |date=2013-07-30 }}</ref> In October 2005, over 20,000 readers of [[Prospect (magazine)|''Prospect'' magazine]] of the UK and ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' magazine of the U.S. ranked him as number 13 on the joint survey of the world's ''[[Top 100 Public Intellectuals Poll]]''.\n\nU.S. presidents from both major parties have praised De Soto's work. [[Bill Clinton]], for example, called him \"The world's greatest living economist\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unc.edu/news/archives/oct04/fpg_desoto101904.html|title=UNC News release -- Noted economist de Soto to discuss property rights|website=www.unc.edu|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> [[George H. W. Bush]] declared that \"De Soto's prescription offers a clear and promising alternative to economic stagnation\u2026\"<ref>Source for President George H. W. Bush's remarks: ''Text of Remarks by the President to the World Bank/International Monetary Fund Annual Meeting'', 27 September 1989, announcing NAFTA. Press release.</ref> Bush's predecessor, [[Ronald Reagan]] said, \"De Soto and his colleagues have examined the only ladder for [[upward mobility]]. The [[free market]] is the other path to development and the one true path. It is the people's path\u2026 it leads somewhere. It works.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cato.org/special/friedman/desoto/praise.html|title=Praise for de Soto and Institute for Liberty and Democracy|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> His work has also received praise from two [[United Nations]] secretaries general [[Kofi Annan]] \u2013 \"Hernando de Soto is absolutely right, that we need to rethink how we capture economic growth and development\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2001/sgsm7892.doc.htm|title=TRANSCRIPT OF PRESS CONFERENCE BY SECRETARY-GENERAL KOFI ANNAN AT INTERNATIONAL LABOUR ORGANIZATION, GENEVA, 16 JULY 2001 - Meetings Coverage and Press Releases|website=www.un.org|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> \u2013 and [[Javier P\u00e9rez de Cu\u00e9llar]] \u2013 \"A crucial contribution. A new proposal for change that is valid for the whole world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booksattransworld.co.uk/catalog/book.htm?command=Search&db=twmain.txt&eqisbndata=0552999237|title=Penguin Books|website=www.booksattransworld.co.uk|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, de Soto was honored with the [[Brigham-Kanner Property Rights Prize]], awarded by the [[William & Mary Law School]] during the 13th Annual [[Brigham-Kanner Property Rights Conference]], in recognition of his tireless advocacy of property rights reform as a tool to alleviate global poverty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://law.wm.edu/news/stories/2016/internationally-renowned-peruvian-economist-de-soto-honored-at-13th-property-rights-conference.php|title=William & Mary Law School - Internationally Renowned Peruvian Economist de Soto Honored at 13th Property Rights Conference|website=law.wm.edu|access-date=2016-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==Prizes==\nAmong the prizes he has received are:\n* The Freedom Prize (Switzerland)\n* The Fisher Prize (United Kingdom)\n* 2002\n** the Goldwater Award (USA)\n** [[Adam Smith Award]] from the [[Association of Private Enterprise Education]] (USA)\n** The CARE Canada Award for Outstanding Development Thinking ([[Canada]])\n* 2003\n** received the Downey Fellowship at [[Yale University]]\n** the Democracy Hall of Fame International Award from the National Graduate University (USA)\n* 2004\n** the Templeton Freedom Prize (USA)\n** the [[Milton Friedman Prize for Advancing Liberty]] (USA)<ref name=\"cato.org\"/>\n** the Royal Decoration of the Most Admirable [[Order of the Direkgunabhorn]], 5th Class, ([[Thailand]])\n* 2005\n** an honorary Doctor of Letters from the [[University of Buckingham]] ([[United Kingdom]]),\n** The Americas Award (USA)\n** named the Most Outstanding of 2004 for Economic Development at Home and Abroad by the Peruvian National Assembly of Rectors\n** received the Prize of Deutsche Stiftung Eigentum for exceptional contributions to the theory of property rights\n** the 2004 IPAE Award by the Peruvian Institute of Business Administration\n** the [[Academy of Achievement|Academy of Achievement's]] [[Golden Plate Award]] 2005 (USA) in tribute to his outstanding accomplishments\n** the [[BearingPoint]], ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'' magazine's seventh Compass Award for Strategic Direction\n** was named as a \"Fellow of the Class of 1930\" by [[Dartmouth College]].\n* 2006\n** the 2006 [[Bradley Prize]] for outstanding achievement by the [[Bradley Foundation]].<ref>[http://www.bradleyfdn.org/cm-prizes.asp?ID=2006BradleyPrizeWinners Bradley Foundation \u2013 Prizes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100713064747/http://www.bradleyfdn.org/cm-prizes.asp?ID=2006BradleyPrizeWinners |date=2010-07-13 }}</ref>\n** the 2006 Innovation Award (Social and Economic Innovation) from ''[[The Economist]]'' magazine (December 2, 2006) for the promotion of property rights and economic development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/search/displaystory.cfm?story_id=E1_RTVSSVR|title=Search|website=The Economist|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n* 2007\n** The Poder BCG Business Awards 2007, granted by ''Poder'' Magazine and the [[Boston Consulting Group]], for the \"Best Anti-Poverty Initiative\"\n** the anthology ''Die Zw\u00f6lf Wichtigsten \u00d6konomen der Welt'' (The World's Twelve Most Influential Economists, 2007), included a profile of de Soto among a list that begins with Adam Smith and includes such recent winners of the Nobel Prize in Economics as [[Joseph Stiglitz]] and [[Amartya Sen]].\n** the 2007 Humanitarian Award in recognition of his work to help poor people participate in the market economy.\n* 2009\n** Honorary patron of the [[University Philosophical Society]] of [[Trinity College, Dublin]] for having excelled in public life and made a worthy contribution to society.\n** the inaugural Hernando de Soto Award for Democracy awarded by the [[Center for International Private Enterprise]] (CIPE) in recognition of his extraordinary achievements in furthering economic freedom in Peru and throughout the developing world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cipe.advomation.com/25th/|title=CIPE @ 25|website=cipe.advomation.com|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n* 2010\n** the Hayek Medal for his theories on liberal development policy (\"market economy from below\") and for the appropriate implementation of his concepts by two Peruvian presidents.\n** the [[Medal of the Presidency of the Italian Republic]] (Council of Ministers) in recognition of his contribution toward the betterment of humankind and having worked for the future of the earth through his commitment.\n* 2016\n** received the 2016 [[Brigham\u2013Kanner Property Rights Prize]] from William & Mary Law School during a ceremony in The Hague, Netherlands, in October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2016/hernando-de-soto-to-receive-2016-brigham-kanner-property-rights-prize.php|title=William & Mary -\u00a0Hernando de Soto to receive 2016 Brigham-Kanner Property Rights Prize|website=www.wm.edu|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===World Justice Project===\nHernando de Soto serves as an honorary co-chair for the [[World Justice Project]]. The [[World Justice Project]] works to lead a global, multidisciplinary effort to strengthen the [[rule of law]] for the development of communities of opportunity and equity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldjusticeproject.com/about/|title=About|accessdate=2010-02-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203064233/http://www.worldjusticeproject.com/about/|archivedate=2010-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and responses==\nDe Soto's works on [[Right to property|property rights]] has voiced diverse views on the effect of the [[Titling|titling of land]].<ref>Bruce, J., Migot-Adholla, S. (Eds.), 1994. Searching for Land Tenure Security in Africa. Kendall Hunt, Dubuque.</ref><ref>Pinckney, T.C. and P.K. Kimuyu. 1994. \"Land Tenure Reform in East Africa: Good, Bad or Unimportant?\" Journal of African Economies 3 (1): 1\u201328.</ref> De Soto has been criticized for methodological and analytical reasons, while some activists have accused him of just wanting to be a representative figure of the prioritizing property rights movement.<ref>Sjaastada, Espen and Ben Cousins. 2008. \"Formalisation of Land Rights In the South: An Overview.\" Land Use Policy 26: 1\u20139</ref> Some state that his theory does not offer anything new compared to traditional land reform. \"De Soto\u2019s proposal is not wealth transfer, but wealth legalization.<ref>Gilbert, Alan. 2002. On the mystery of capital and the myths of Hernando de Soto. What difference does legal title make? International Development Planning Review 24 (1) 1\u201319.</ref><ref>Deininger, Klaus. 2003. Land Policies for Growth and Poverty Reduction. Washington, DC: World Bank.</ref> The poor of the world already possess trillions in assets now. De Soto is not distributing capital to anyone. By making them liquid, everyone\u2019s capital pool grows dramatically\".<ref name=\"Biswas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.floorgroup.raumplanung.tu-dortmund.de/FLOOR_Working_papers/FLOOR_WP018_Dey_Biswas_Land_rights_formalization_India.pdf|title=Dey Biswas, Sattwick. 2014. Land Rights Formalization in India; Examining de Soto through the lens of Rawls theory of justice. FLOOR Working paper 18|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> While analysing Schaefer's arguments, Roy writes, \"de Soto\u2019s ideas are seductive precisely because they only guarantee the latter, but in doing so promise the former\".<ref>Roy, Dayabati. 2013. Rural Politics in India: Political Stratification and Governance in West Bengal. Cambridge University Press, pp 152</ref><ref>Platteau, J.-P. 1996. \"The Evolutionary Theory of Land Rights as Applied To Sub-Saharan Africa: A Critical Assessment.\" Development and Change 27 (1): 29\u201385.</ref>\n\nWhat differentiates de Soto from his predecessor is his attempt to include non-agricultural land in the scheme of reform and emphasizing in formalization of existing informal possession.<ref name=\"Sjaastada 2008\">Sjaastada, Espen and Ben Cousins. 2008. \"Formalisation of Land Rights In the South: An Overview.\" Land Use Policy 26: 1\u20139.</ref> His emphasis on title formalization as the only reason behind economic growth in the United States has been subject to criticism.<ref>Madrick, Jeff. 2001. [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2001/may/31/the-charms-of-property/ The Charms of Property]. ''The New York Review of Books''</ref> Property formalization in America may have happened as a result of different reasons including establishment of law and order, increased state control, greater institutional integration, increased economic efficiency, increased tax revenue, and greater equality.(<ref name=\"Sjaastada 2008\"/>) The argument for private and often individualist property regime comes under the question of societal legitimacy, may not be justified even if de Soto eyes bringing an unified system in a state or unification with the global economy.<ref name=\"Biswas\" />\n\nIn his ''Planet of Slums'',<ref>Mike Davis, ''Planet of Slums'', Verso, 2006 pp. 79\u201382</ref> [[Mike Davis (scholar)|Mike Davis]] argues that de Soto, who Davis calls 'the global guru of neo-liberal populism', is essentially promoting what the statist left in South America and India has always promoted\u2014individual [[land titling]]. Davis argues that titling is the incorporation into the formal economy of cities, which benefits more wealthy squatters but is disastrous for poorer squatters, and especially tenants who simply cannot afford incorporation into the fully commodified formal economy.\n\nGrassroots controlled and directed shack dwellers movements like [[Abahlali baseMjondolo]] in [[South Africa]] and the [[Homeless Workers' Movement]] (Movimento dos Trabalhadores Sem Teto \u2013 MTST) in Brazil<ref>[http://www.mtst.info MTST \u2013 Movimento dos Trabalhadores Sem Teto] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706135612/http://www.mtst.info/ |date=2008-07-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mstbrazil.org/|title=Home - Friends of the MST|website=www.mstbrazil.org|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> have strenuously argued against individual titling and for communal and democratic systems of collective land tenure because this offers protection to the poorest and prevents 'downward raiding' in which richer people displace squatters once their neighborhoods are formalized.\n\nAn article by [[Madeleine Bunting]] for ''[[The Guardian]]'' (UK) claimed that de Soto's suggestions would in some circumstances cause more harm than benefit, and referred to The Mystery of Capital as \"an elaborate smokescreen\" used to obscure the issue of the power of the globalized elite. She cited de Soto's employment history as evidence of his bias in favor of the powerful.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2000/sep/11/imf.comment|last=Bunting|first=Madeleine|title=Fine words, flawed ideas|work=The Guardian|date=11 September 2000}}</ref> Reporter [[John Gravois]] also criticized de Soto for his ties to power circles, exemplified by his attendance at the [[Davos]] [[World Economic Forum]]. In response, de Soto told Gravois that this proximity to power would help de Soto educate the elites about poverty. [[Ivan Osorio]] of the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]] has refuted Gravois's allegations pointing out how Gravois has misinterpreted many of de Soto's recommendations.<ref name=\"Osorio\">{{Cite web |url=http://cei.org/gencon/019,04389.cfm |title=Osorio, Ivan. Will the Real Hernando de Soto Please Stand Up?, originally published as Osorio Op-ed in Tech Central Station, February 2, 2005 |access-date=January 6, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202005655/http://www.cei.org/gencon/019%2C04389.cfm |archive-date=December 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Robert J. Samuelson]] has argued against what he sees as de Soto's \"single bullet\" approach and has argued for a greater emphasis on culture and how local conditions affect people's perceptions of their opportunities.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20010101fareviewessay2001010112/robert-j-samuelson/the-spirit-of-capitalism.html|last=Samuelson|first=Robert J|title=The Spirit of Capitalism|journal=Foreign Affairs|date=January\u2013February 2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080312222150/http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20010101fareviewessay2001010112/robert-j-samuelson/the-spirit-of-capitalism.html|archivedate=12 March 2008}}</ref> UN Special Rapporteur on the right to food, [[Olivier De Schutter]], has questioned the insistence on titling as a means to protect security of tenure based on the risk that titling will undermine customary forms of tenure and insufficiently protect the rights of land users that depend on the commons, as well as the fear that titling schemes may lead to further reconcentration of land ownership, unless strong support is provided to smallholders.\n\nIn the [[World Development]] journal, a 1990 article by R. G. Rossini and J. J. Thomas of the [[London School of Economics]] questioned the statistical basis of de Soto's claims about the size of the informal economy in his first book ''The Other Path''.<ref>[http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/B6VC6-45CWV65-32/2/0eeb1e04e92415f8fb6c2e3efaae1ee7 Rossini, R. G. and J. J. Thomas. \"The size of the informal sector in Peru: A critical comment on Hernando de Soto's El Otro Sendero\", in World Development, Volume 18, Issue 1, January 1990, pp. 125\u201335.]</ref> However, the ILD pointed out, in the same journal, that Rossini and Thomas\u2019 observations \"neither [addressed] the central theme of the book, nor [did it address] the main body of quantitative evidence displayed to substantiate the importance of economic and legal barriers that give rise to informal activities. Instead, [they focused] exclusively on four empirical estimates that the book [mentioned] only in passing\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=A reply|date=1 January 1990|journal=World Development|volume=18|issue=1|pages=137\u2013145|doi=10.1016/0305-750X(90)90108-A}}</ref>\n\nIn the ''[[Journal of Economic Literature]]'', [[Christopher Woodruff]] of the [[University of California, San Diego]] criticized de Soto for overestimating the amount of wealth that land titling now informally owned property could unlock, and argues that \"de Soto's own experience in Peru suggests that land titling by itself is not likely to have much effect. Titling must be followed by a series of politically challenging steps. Improving the efficiency of judicial systems, rewriting bankruptcy codes, restructuring financial market regulations, and similar reforms will involve much more difficult choices by policymakers.\"<ref>[http://epserv.unila.ac.id/jurnal/BAhan/Jurnal%20Of%20Economic%20lietratur/Content/2001/dec/articles/woodruff.pdf Woodruff, Christopher. Review: Review of de Soto's \"The Mystery of Capital\", Journal of Economic Literature, Vol. 39, No. 4 (Dec., 2001), pp. 1215\u201323]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=imf1>{{cite web|url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/fandd/2003/12/pdf/people.pdf|title=Clift, Jeremy. \"People in Economics: Hernando de Soto\" \u2013 Finance & Development \u2013 December 2003.|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nEmpirical studies by Argentine economists [[Sebastian Galiani]] and [[Ernesto Schargrodsky]] have taken issue with de Soto's link between titling and the increase in credit to the poor, but have also pointed out that families with titles \"substantially increased housing investment, reduced household size, and improved the education of their children relative to the control group\".<ref>[http://coase.org/workingpapers/wp-7.pdf Galiani, Sebastian and Ernesto Schargrodsky. ''Property Rights for the Poor: Effects of Land Titling'' \u2013 Ronald Coase Institute, Working Paper Series, revised January 2009, ]</ref> In a 2012 book by Yale University political science methodologist Thad Dunning, he argues that Galiani and Schargrodsky's studies provide \"highly credible\" claims because the studies rely on true randomization, whereas De Soto's study did not (and is thus vulnerable to confounding variables).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/natural-experiments-in-the-social-sciences/introduction/CFD585F55CEF077D132706D2D7820548|title=Introduction|last=Dunning|first=Thad|date=2012|website=Natural Experiments in the Social Sciences: A Design-Based Approach|pages=5-12|language=en|doi=10.1017/cbo9781139084444.002|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> A study commissioned by [[DFID]], an agency of the [[U.K. government]], further summarized many of the complications arising from implementing de Soto's policy recommendations when insufficient attention is paid to the local social context.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oxfam.org.uk/resources/learning/landrights/downloads/land_changing_contexts_relationships_rights.rtf |title=Daley, Elizabeth and Mary Hobley. ''Land: Changing Contexts, Changing Relationships, Changing Rights'' (for DFID's Urban-Rural Change Team) September 2005 |access-date=2010-01-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608083557/http://www.oxfam.org.uk/resources/learning/landrights/downloads/land_changing_contexts_relationships_rights.rtf |archive-date=2011-06-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDe Soto himself has often pointed out that his critics mistakenly claim that he advocates land titling by itself as sufficient for effective development: For example, in the ILD's new brochure he is quoted as saying, \"The ILD is not just about titling. What we do is help Governments build a system of public memory that legally identifies all their people, their assets, their business records and their transactions in such a way that they can unleash their economic potential. No economy can develop and prosper without the benefits that clearly registered public documents bestow.\"<ref>Institute for Liberty and Democracy, ''The ILD's war against exclusion'', p. 21. 2009</ref>\n\nOn January 31, 2012, de Soto and his publisher were fined by the Peruvian intellectual property rights organization INDECOPI for excluding the names of co-authors, [[Enrique Ghersi]] and [[Mario Ghibellini]], on newer editions of his 1986 book ''The Other Path''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Per\u00fa: Condenan por infracci\u00f3n a derecho moral de paternidad a economista Hernando de Soto|url=http://iptango.blogspot.ca/2012/02/peru-condenan-por-infraccion-derecho.html|website=IP Tango: weblog for intellectual property law and practice for Latin America|accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref><ref>http://elcomercio.pe/economia/peru/sancionan-hernando-soto-violacion-propiedad-intelectual-noticia-1368239</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sistemas.indecopi.gob.pe/SPI_Jurisprudencia/documentos/1-45/2012/0040-2012.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721151832/http://sistemas.indecopi.gob.pe/SPI_Jurisprudencia/documentos/1-45/2012/0040-2012.pdf |archivedate=2015-07-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indecopi.gob.pe/0/modulos/NOT/NOT_DetallarNoticia.aspx?PFL=0&NOT=382 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-07-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924034223/http://www.indecopi.gob.pe/0/modulos/NOT/NOT_DetallarNoticia.aspx?PFL=0&NOT=382 |archivedate=2015-09-24 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books===\nDe Soto has published two books about economic development: ''The Other Path: The Invisible Revolution in the Third World'' in 1986 in Spanish (with a new edition in 2002 titled ''The Other Path, The Economic Answer to Terrorism'') and in 2000, ''The Mystery of Capital: Why Capitalism Triumphs in the West and Fails Everywhere Else'' ({{ISBN|978-0465016150}}). Both books have been international bestsellers, translated into some 30 languages.\n\nThe original [[Spanish language|Spanish-language]] title of ''The Other Path'' is ''El Otro Sendero'', an allusion to de Soto's alternative proposals for development in Peru, countering the attempts of the \"[[Shining Path]]\" (''\"Sendero Luminoso\"'') to win the support of Peru's poor. Based on five years worth of ILD research into the causes of massive informality and legal exclusion in Peru, the book was also a direct intellectual challenge to the Shining Path, offering to the poor of Peru not the violent overthrow of the system but \"the other path\" out of poverty, through legal reform. In response, the Senderistas added de Soto to their assassination list. In July 1992, the terrorists sent a second car bomb into ILD headquarters in Lima, killing 3 and wounding 19.\n\nIn addition, he has written, with Francis Cheneval, ''Swiss Human Rights Book Volume 1: Realizing Property Rights'', published in 2006 \u2013 a collection of papers presented at an international symposium in Switzerland in 2006 on the urgency of property rights in impoverished countries for small business owners, women, and other vulnerable groups, such as the poor and political refugees. The book includes a paper on the ILD's work in Tanzania delivered by Hernando de Soto.<ref>[http://www.swisshumanrightsbook.com/SHRB/home.html De Soto, Hernando and Francis Cheneval. Swiss Human Rights Book Volume 1: Realizing Property Rights, 2006.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121043723/http://www.swisshumanrightsbook.com/SHRB/home.html |date=2008-11-21 }}</ref>\n* De Soto, Hernando. ''The Other Path: The Invisible Revolution in the Third World''. Harpercollins, 1989. {{ISBN|0-06-016020-9}}\n* De Soto, Hernando. ''The Mystery of Capital: Why Capitalism Triumphs in the West and Fails Everywhere Else''. Basic Books, 2000. {{ISBN|0-465-01614-6}}\n* De Soto, Hernando. ''[[The Other Path]]: The Economic Answer to Terrorism''. Basic Books, 2002. {{ISBN|0-465-01610-3}}\n* De Soto, Hernando and Francis Cheneval. ''Swiss Human Rights Book Volume 1: Realizing Property Rights'', 2006. {{ISBN|978-3-907625-25-5}}\n* Smith, Barry et al. (eds.). ''The Mystery of Capital and the Construction of Social Reality'', Chicago: Open Court, 2008. {{ISBN|0-8126-9615-8}}\n\n===Articles===\nDe Soto has also published a number of articles on the importance of inclusive property and business rights, legally empowering the poor, and the causes of the global financial crisis of 2008\u201309 in leading newspapers and magazines around the world. In 2001, ''Time'' magazine published \"The Secret of Non-Success,\"<ref name=\"time1\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0QOQ6_I6NqwC&lpg=PA49&dq=%22The+Secret+of+Non-Success%E2%80%9D+Time+magazine&pg=PA49#v=onepage&q=%22The+Secret+of+Non-Success%E2%80%9D+Time+magazine&f=false|title=New Horizons for Foreign Direct Investment|first=Global Forum on International|last=Investment|date=1 January 2002|publisher=Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|accessdate=16 August 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9789264197282}}</ref> the New York Times ran his post-September 11 op-ed essay \"The Constituency of Terror,\"<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/15/opinion/15DESO.html|title=The Constituency of Terror|first=Hernando De|last=Soto|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> and the IMF's Finance & Development magazine published \"The Mystery of Capital\", a condensed version of the third chapter of his eponymous book.<ref name=\"imf2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/fandd/2001/03/desoto.htm|title=Finance and Development|website=Finance and Development - F&D|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> In 2007, ''Time'' magazine published \"Giving the Poor their Rights\", an article written with former Secretary of State, Madeleine Albright, on the legal empowerment of the poor. In 2009, Newsweek International published his essay on the financial crisis, \"Toxic Paper\"<ref name=\"nw1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/185814|title=Hernando de Soto on the Toxic-Paper Problem|date=20 February 2009|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> \u2013 along with an on-line interview with him, \"Slumdogs and Millionaires.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/185656|title=Economy: Slumdogs vs. Wall Street Millionaires|date=19 February 2009|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> That was soon followed by two more articles on the crisis, in the Wall Street Journal (\"Toxic Assets Were Hidden Assets\")<ref name=\"wsj1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123793811398132049|title=Toxic Assets Were Hidden Assets|first=Hernando de|last=Soto|date=25 March 2009|accessdate=16 August 2018|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref> and The Los Angeles Times (\"Global Meltdown Rule #1: Do the Math\").<ref name=\"lat1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/la-oe-desoto12-2009apr12-story.html|title=Global Meltdown Rule No. 1: Do the math|first=By Hernando de|last=Soto|website=latimes.com|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> Versions of these articles also appeared in newspapers in France, Switzerland, Germany and Latin America. In 2011, Bloomberg published \"The Destruction of Economic Facts\",<ref name=\"bb1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/11_19/b4227060634112.htm|title=De Soto, Hernando. \"The Destruction of Economic Facts\", Bloomberg Businessweek, 28 April 2011|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> and The Washington Post recently ran \"The cost of financial ignorance\".<ref name=\"wp3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/the-cost-of-financial-ignorance/2011/10/03/gIQAEU3yTL_story.html|title=The cost of financial ignorance|website=Washington Post|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> When protests began in Cairo at the beginning of 2011, The Wall Street Journal published De Soto's \"Egypt's Economic Apartheid\",<ref name=\"wsj2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704358704576118683913032882|title=Egypt's Economic Apartheid|first=Hernando de|last=Soto|date=3 February 2011|accessdate=16 August 2018|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref> and Financial Times later published \"The free-market secret of the Arab Revolution\".<ref name=\"ft1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/653fab0e-0a00-11e1-85ca-00144feabdc0.html|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Other Path: The Economic Answer to Terrorism]]''\n* [[Liberalism]]\n* [[Contributions to liberal theory]]\n* [[Dependency theory]]\n* [[Documentality]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ild.org.pe Institute for Liberty and Democracy] official website.\n* [http://www.newsweek.com/id/185656 \"Slumdogs vs. Millionaires\"], Newsweek's Barrett Sheridan interviews Hernando de Soto\n* [http://www.greatissuesforum.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=68&Itemid=76 The Great Issues Forum], video of [[Naomi Klein]], [[Joseph Stiglitz]], and Hernando de Soto discussing the financial crisis\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100206205134/http://ild.org.pe/news/esri \"Mapping the Invisible\"], speech by Hernando de Soto at the 2009 [http://www.esri.com/events/uc/ ESRI] International User Conference\n* [http://www.munkdebates.com/index.cfm?debate=1 The Munk Debate on Foreign Aid, 2009.]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Stephen Lewis and Paul Collier against Peruvian economist Hernando de Soto and Dambisa Moyo, a Zambian-born critic of foreign aid.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110118083151/http://www.aifestival.org/audio-video-library.php?menu=3&title=535&action=full_info Afternoon of Conversation: Andrea Mitchell, Madeleine Albright, Hernando De Soto], video of conversation\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090802211731/http://www.literalmagazine.com/es/archive-L13.php?section=archive&lang=es ''The Rule of Law''] \u2013 an interview with Hernando de Soto By Gustavo Wensjoe 2008\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/commandingheights/shared/minitextlo/int_hernandodesoto.html Transcript] of an interview for the PBS documentary [[Commanding Heights]].\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/Archive/Article/0,4273,4061838,00.html A highly critical review] in the British newspaper [[The Guardian]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080312222150/http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20010101fareviewessay2001010112/robert-j-samuelson/the-spirit-of-capitalism.html An essay by Robert Samuelson] in [[Foreign Affairs]], arguing that de Soto underestimates the importance of culture\n* [http://www.thepowerofthepoor.com/ The Power of the Poor] \u2013 Documentary about de Soto's work by Free to Choose Media\n* {{C-SPAN|hernandodesoto}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soto Polar, Hernando De}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies alumni]]\n[[Category:Development economists]]\n[[Category:Peruvian economists]]\n[[Category:People from Arequipa]]\n[[Category:Peruvian male writers]]\n[[Category:Winners of The Economist innovation awards]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Spanish explorer|Hernando de Soto}}\n{{Spanish name|De Soto|Polar}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2013}}\n{{peacock|date=January 2014}}\n}}\n{{Infobox economist\n | school_tradition= [[Austrian School]]<br />[[Chicago school of economics|Chicago School]]\n |alma_mater=[[International School of Geneva]]<br>[[Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies]]| color =\n | image = {{CSS image crop \n|Image         = WTTC Americas Summit - Opening Ceremony & Session 1, Hernando de Soto, President (ILD) (15016116417).jpg\n|bSize         = 1000 \n|cWidth        = 250\n|cHeight       = 350\n|oLeft = 420\n|oTop = 20\n|Location = center \n}}\n | caption =de Soto at the [[World Travel and Tourism Council|WTTC Americas Summit]] in 2014\n | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1941|06|03}}\n | birth_place = [[Arequipa]], [[Peru]]\n | death_date =\n | death_place =\n | nationality = [[Per\u00fa|Peruvian]]\n |institution=[[Institute for Liberty and Democracy]]| field = The economics of the [[informal sector]],<br>research in [[property rights]] theory\n | influences = [[Milton Friedman]]<br />[[Friedrich Hayek]]\n | influenced =\n | contributions = [[Dead capital]]\n}}\n'''Hernando de Soto Polar''' (or '''Hernando de Soto''' {{IPAc-en|d|\u0259|\u02c8|s|o\u028a|t|o\u028a}}; born 1941) is a Peruvian [[economist]] known for his work on the [[informal economy]] and on the importance of business and [[property rights]]. He is the president of the [[Institute for Liberty and Democracy]] (ILD), located in [[Lima]], Peru.<ref name=ild2>[http://ild.org.pe/hernando-de-soto/158-staff/staff/713-hernando-de-soto-detailed-bio Institute for Liberty and Democracy, \"Hernando de Soto \u2013 Detailed Bio\".] (accessed 16 March 2013)</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nDe Soto was born on 2 June 1941 in [[Arequipa]], Peru. His father was a Peruvian diplomat. After the [[Manuel A. Odr\u00eda|1948 military coup in Peru]], his parents chose exile in Europe, taking their two young sons with them. De Soto was educated in Switzerland, where he attended the [[International School of Geneva]] and then did post-graduate work at the [[Graduate Institute of International Studies]] in [[Geneva]]. He later worked as an economist, corporate executive and consultant. He returned to Peru at the age of 38.<ref>Source: ''Investors Business Daily'', Monday November 6, 2006. p. A4. Leaders & Success. Article by IBD Reinhardt Kraus.</ref> His younger brother \u00c1lvaro served in the Peruvian diplomatic corps in Lima, [[New York City]] and [[Geneva]] and was seconded to United Nations in 1982. He retired from the U.N. in 2007 with the title rank of Assistant Under-Secretary-General; his last position was as the UN Special Coordinator for the Middle East Peace Process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://image.guardian.co.uk/sys-files/Guardian/documents/2007/06/12/DeSotoReport.pdf|accessdate=31 August 2015}}</ref> He is well known as an international adviser.\n\n==Reforms in Peru and elsewhere==\nBetween 1988 and 1995, he and the [[Institute for Liberty and Democracy]] (ILD) were mainly responsible for some four hundred initiatives, laws, and regulations that led to significant changes in Peru's [[economic system]].<ref>[http://www.theglobalist.com/AuthorBiography.aspx?AuthorId=32 The Globalist | Biography of Hernando de Soto] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911100830/http://www.theglobalist.com/AuthorBiography.aspx?AuthorId=32 |date=2006-09-11 }}</ref>\n\nIn particular, ILD designed the administrative reform of Peru's property system which has given titles to an estimated 1.2 million families and helped some 380,000 firms, which previously operated in the [[black market]], to enter the formal [[economy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnstoncenter.unc.edu/index.php/media-events/jcue-fpg/122-2004-2005fpglecture.html|title=The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill - Website Maintenance|website=www.johnstoncenter.unc.edu|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> This latter task was accomplished through the elimination of bureaucratic \"[[red-tape]]\" and of restrictive registration, licensing and permit laws, which made the opening of new businesses very time-consuming and costly.\n\n[[University of Chicago]] political scientist [[Susan Stokes|Susan C. Stokes]] believes that de Soto's influence helped change the policies of [[Alberto Fujimori]] from a [[Keynesian]] to a [[neoliberal]] approach. De Soto convinced then-president Fujimori to travel to [[New York City]], where they met with [[Javier P\u00e9rez de Cu\u00e9llar]], [[Barber Conable]], [[Enrique V. Iglesias]] (the heads of the United Nations, the International Monetary Fund, and the [[Inter-American Development Bank]]), who convinced him to follow the guidelines for economic policy set by the international financial institutions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/07/01/world/new-peru-leader-in-accord-on-debt.html|title=NEW PERU LEADER IN ACCORD ON DEBT|first=Paul Lewis and Special To the New York|last=Times|accessdate=16 August 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 1990}}</ref> These policies led to a reduction in the rate of [[inflation]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stokes|first1=Susan|title=Are Parties What's Wrong with Democracy in Latin America?|citeseerx=10.1.1.569.1490}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Cato Institute]] and ''[[The Economist]]'' magazine have argued that de Soto's policy prescriptions brought him into conflict with and eventually helped to undermine the [[Shining Path]] (Sendero Luminoso) guerrilla movement. By granting titles to small [[coca]] farmers in the two main coca-growing areas, they argued that the Shining Path was deprived of safe havens, recruits and money, and the leadership was forced to cities where they were arrested.<ref name=\"cato.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cato.org/special/friedman/desoto/index.html|title=Hernando de Soto's Biography|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"economist\">{{cite news| url=https://www.economist.com/people/displayStory.cfm?story_id=1559905 | work=The Economist | title=The economist versus the terrorist | date=30 January 2003}}</ref> A large terrorist attack was launched against the ILD and de Soto in light of the statements by Shining Path leader [[Abimael Guzm\u00e1n]] who saw ILD as a serious threat.<ref>http://nsarchive.gwu.edu/NSAEBB/NSAEBB64/peru33.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ild.org.pe/publications/books/the-other-path|title=The Other Path|website=www.ild.org.pe|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the split with Fujimori, he and his institute designed similar programs in [[El Salvador]], [[Haiti]], [[Tanzania]], and [[Egypt]] and has gained favor with the [[World Bank]], the World Bank-allied international NGO [[Slum Dwellers International]] and the government of [[South Africa]].\n\nSince its work in Peru in the 1980s, his institute, the ILD, has worked in dozens of countries. Heads of state in over 35 countries have sought the ILD's services to discuss how ILD's theories on property rights could potentially improve their economies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ild.org.pe/about-us/impact/achievements|title=Achievements|website=www.ild.org.pe|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe impact of de Soto's institute in the field of development\u2014on political leaders, experts and multi-lateral organizations\u2014is widespread and acknowledged. For example:\n* The ILD's institutional reform program has attracted the interest of strategically key nations concerned with internal conflict and terrorism.\n* The ILD has designed successful reforms that have inspired major initiatives in former client countries such as Egypt, the Philippines, Honduras and Tanzania.\n* The ILD is recognized as the world authority in understanding extralegal economies, influencing the protocols of large multilateral organizations by helping them to understand the realities that the poor and the excluded face, day to day. These include institutions such as the Commission for Legal Empowerment of the Poor, the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB), USAID and the World Bank.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freetochoosemedia.org/broadcasts/power_poor/docs/hernando_de_soto_bio.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721055023/http://www.freetochoosemedia.org/broadcasts/power_poor/docs/hernando_de_soto_bio.pdf |archivedate=2015-07-21 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the ILD turned its attention back to Peru and the plight of the indigenous peoples of the Peruvian Amazon jungle. In response to Peru's President Garc\u00eda's call to all Peruvians to present their proposals toward solving the problems leading to the bloody incidents in Bagua, the ILD has assessed the situation and presented its preliminary findings. ILD has published a short videotaped documentary, ''The Mystery of Capital among the Indigenous Peoples of the Amazon'', summarizing its findings from indigenous communities in Alaska, Canada and the Peruvian jungle.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Enrique Escalante|first1=Edwar|title=Peru: The Mystery of Capital among the Indigenous People of the Amazon|url=http://www.hacer.org/latam/peru-the-mystery-of-capital-among-the-indigenous-people-of-the-amazon-by-edwar-enrique-escalante/|website=Hacer Latin America|accessdate=31 July 2015|date=2009-09-30}}</ref>\n\n==Main thesis==\nThe main message of de Soto's work and writings is that no nation can have a strong [[market economy]] without adequate participation in an information framework that records ownership of property and other economic information.<ref>\"The Destruction of Economic Facts\", by Hernando de Soto. April 28, 2010. Bloomberg ''[[BusinessWeek]]''. Accessed online May 2, 2011 [http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/11_19/b4227060634112.htm]</ref> [[Black market|Unreported, unrecorded economic activity]] results in many small entrepreneurs who lack legal ownership of their property, making it difficult for them to obtain credit, sell the business, or expand. They cannot seek legal remedies to business conflicts in court, since they do not have legal ownership. Lack of information on income prevents governments from collecting taxes and acting for the public welfare.\n\n<blockquote>The existence of such massive exclusion generates two parallel economies, legal and extra legal. An elite minority enjoys the economic benefits of the law and globalization, while the majority of entrepreneurs are stuck in poverty, where their assets\u2014adding up to more than US$10 trillion worldwide\u2014languish as [[dead capital]] in the shadows of the law.<ref name=\"Soto, Hernando 2000\">de Soto, Hernando. 2000. The Mystery of Capital. UK: Black Swan.</ref>\n\nTo survive, to protect their assets, and to do as much business as possible, the extralegals create their own rules. But because these local arrangements are full of shortcomings and are not easily enforceable, the extralegals also create their own social, political and economic problems that affect the society at large.\n\nSince the fall of the Berlin Wall, responsible nations around the developing world have worked hard to make the transition to a market economy, but have in general failed.<ref>de Soto 2000, 1</ref> Populist leaders have used this failure of the free market system to wipe out poverty in the developing world to beat their \"anti-globalization\" drums. But the ILD believes that the real enemy is within the flawed legal systems of developing nations that make it virtually impossible for the majority of their people\u2014and their assets\u2014to gain a stake in the market. The people of these countries have talent, enthusiasm, and an astonishing ability to wring a profit out of practically nothing`.<ref name=\"Soto, Hernando 2000\"/>\n\nWhat the poor majority in the developing world do not have is easy access to the legal system which, in the advanced nations of the world and for the elite in their countries, is the gateway to economic success, for it is in the legal system where property documents are created and standardized according to law. That documentation builds a public memory that permits society to engage in such crucial economic activities as identifying and gaining access to information about individuals, their assets, their titles, rights, charges and obligations; establishing the limits of liability for businesses; knowing an asset's previous economic situation; assuring protection of third parties; and quantifying and valuing assets and rights.<ref>[[Barry Smith (ontologist)|Barry Smith]], \"[http://ontology.buffalo.edu/document_ontology/Seale&deSoto.pdf \"Searle and De Soto: The New Ontology of the Social World]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\", in Barry Smith, David Mark and Isaac Ehrlich (eds.), ''[http://www.opencourtbooks.com/books_n/mystery.htm The Mystery of Capital and the Construction of Social Reality]'', Chicago: Open Court, 2008, 35\u201351.</ref> These public memory mechanisms in turn facilitate such opportunities as access to credit, the establishment of systems of identification, the creation of systems for credit and insurance information, the provision for housing and infrastructure, the issue of shares, the mortgage of property and a host of other economic activities that drive a modern market economy.<ref>Institute for Liberty and Democracy, ''The ILD's war against exclusion'', p. 19. 2009</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Work and research ==\n\nSince 2008, De Soto has been refining his thesis about the importance of property rights to development in response to his organization's findings that a number of new global threats have \"property rights distortions\" at their root. \nIn essays, that appeared from early 2009 into 2012 in media outlets in the U.S. and Europe, De Soto argued that the reason why the U.S. and European economies were mired in recession was the result of a \"knowledge crisis\" not a financial one.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sheridan|first1=Barrett|title=Economy: Slumdogs vs. Wall Street Millionaires|url=http://www.newsweek.com/economy-slumdogs-vs-wall-street-millionaires-82171|website=Newsweek|accessdate=16 August 2015|date=2009-02-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Destruction of Economic Facts|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/stories/2011-04-27/the-destruction-of-economic-facts|website=Bloomberg Business|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Toxic Assets Were Hidden Assets|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123793811398132049|website=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=What if you can't prove you had a house?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/20/opinion/20iht-edsoto.html?_r=1&|website=The New York Times|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Knowledge Crisis Strategy|url=http://www.ild.org.pe/our-work/property-paradigm/the-knowledge-crisis-strategy|website=ild.org.pe|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref>\n \n\"Capitalism lives in two worlds,\" De Soto wrote in the ''Financial Times'' in January 2012. \"There is the visible one of palm trees and Panamanian ships, but it is the other \u2013 made up of the property information cocooned in laws and records \u2013 that allows us to organize and understand fragments of reality and join them creatively.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Knowledge lies at the heart over western capitalism|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/4520ccda-4769-11e1-b847-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?siteedition=uk&_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F4520ccda-4769-11e1-b847-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Duk&_i_referer=&classification=conditional_standard&iab=barrier-app|website=Financial Times|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref> De Soto argued that the knowledge in those public memory systems, which \"helped Capitalism triumph,\" was distorted over the past 15 years or so. \"Until this knowledge system is repaired,\" he wrote, \"neither US nor European capitalism will recover.\" <ref>{{cite web|title=Knowledge lies at the heart of western capitalism|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/4520ccda-4769-11e1-b847-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?siteedition=uk&_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F4520ccda-4769-11e1-b847-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Duk&_i_referer=&classification=conditional_standard&iab=barrier-app#axzz3izOmPxfD|website=Financial Times|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn another series of articles that appeared in US and Europe in 2011, De Soto used the findings of ILD field research in Egypt, Tunisia and Libya to make his case for \"the economic roots of the [[Arab Spring]].\"<ref name=\"wsj.com\">{{cite web|title=The Secret to Reviving the Arab Spring's Promise: Property Rights|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324162304578302403519972088|website=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ft.com\">{{cite web|title=The free market secret of the Arab revolution |url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/653fab0e-0a00-11e1-85ca-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?siteedition=intl&_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F653fab0e-0a00-11e1-85ca-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Dintl&_i_referer=&classification=conditional_standard&iab=barrier-app#axzz3izOmPxfD |website=Financial Times|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"The real Mohamed Bouazizi\">{{cite web|title=The real Mohamed Bouazizi|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2011/12/16/the-real-mohamed-bouazizi/|website=Foreign Policy|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref> The ongoing Arab revolutions, he argued, were \"economic revolutions\" driven mainly by the frustrations of 200 million ordinary Arabs who depended on the informal economy for their livelihoods.<ref name=\"ft.com\"/><ref name=\"The real Mohamed Bouazizi\"/> He pointed to the ILD's earlier 2004 findings in Egypt, which revealed the nation's largest employer with 92% of the property in the informal economy \u2013 assets worth almost $247 billion.<ref name=\"wsj.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=The Economic Roots of the Arab Spring|url=http://www.cfr.org/world/economic-roots-arab-spring/p35234|website=Council of foreign relations|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref>\nAlso, as proof of the extent of desperation among [[MENA]]\u2019s entrepreneurs, he elaborated ILD's exclusive research on [[Mohamed Bouazizi]], the Tunisian street vendor whose public self-immolation in protest of the expropriation of his goods and scale literally sparked the Jasmine Revolution in Tunisia, which spread unrest through the Arab world.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Real Mohamed Bouazizi|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2011/12/16/the-real-mohamed-bouazizi/|website=Foreign Policy|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Economic Inclusion, Democracy, and the Arab Spring|url=http://www.cipe.org/blog/2013/02/11/economic-inclusion-democracy-and-the-arab-spring/#.VdClW3g-Dsl|website=CIPE Development|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Arab Spring unrest was ignited by entrepreneurs facing constraints: Economist|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/06/08/arab-spring-unrest-was-ignited-by-entrepreneurs-facing-constraints-economist/|website=Daily News Egypt|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing core funding from USAID, ILD laid off the majority of their employees from their San Isidro office. In 2014-2015, De Soto and a small team working out of his house began to attempt to guide the political process in Peru, as Presidential elections were due to take place in 2016, by finding solutions to the ongoing national mining crisis. De Soto has been a strong advocate for the formalisation of the informal miners that are scattered throughout Peru.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diariocorreo.pe/ciudad/juliaca-hernando-de-soto-propondra-formalizacion-a-mineros-572009/|title=Juliaca: Hernando de Soto propondr\u00e1 formalizaci\u00f3n a mineros|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gestion.pe/politica/hernando-soto-propone-hacer-comunidades-accionistas-mineras-2136954|title=Hernando de Soto propone hacer a las comunidades accionistas de las mineras|first=Redacci\u00f3n|last=Gesti\u00f3n|date=11 July 2015|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> Since 2014, several large national investment projects, including Las Bambas, and Tia Maria have been disrupted by violent protests by informal miners against government regulation and formal extractive industries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diariocorreo.pe/opinion/conga-tia-maria-y-las-bambas-621747/|title=Conga, T\u00eda Mar\u00eda y Las Bambas|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> In July 2015, the ILD discovered that former Shining Path militants who have taken up the ecological cause were paralyzing some $70 billion in mining investment in Peru.<ref name=\"elcomercio.pe\">{{cite web|url=http://elcomercio.pe/politica/actualidad/soto-hay-us70-mil-mlls-inversion-minera-paralizada-noticia-1823604|title=De Soto: \"Hay US$70 mil mlls. de inversi\u00f3n minera paralizada\"|first=Mariella|last=Balbi|date=5 July 2015|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, recorded video debates between the former extremists and De Soto were published on ILD's YouTube channel and revealed that the Shining Path militants agree that property rights could be an important part of the solution to social conflicts in Peru.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Gpfp1PRJ-c|title=Hernando de Soto Y Anti-Mineros (Segmento #1)|last=Institute for Liberty and Democracy|date=8 July 2015|accessdate=16 August 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> De Soto's stated goal is to determine the roots of informal hostility against multinationals and identify what is needed to build a national social contract on extractive industries that could harmonize their property interests with those of [[Multinational corporation|multinationals]] as opposed to creating conflict.<ref name=\"elcomercio.pe\"/>\n\n=== De Soto applies thesis to terrorism ===\n\nIn October 2014, De Soto published an article in the Wall Street Journal, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-capitalist-cure-for-terrorism-1412973796 The Capitalist Cure for Terrorism], that stated an aggressive agenda for economic empowerment was needed in the Middle East in order to defeat terrorist groups like [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]]. He argued that the U.S. should promote an agenda similar to what was successfully used in Peru to defeat the [[Shining Path]] in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-capitalist-cure-for-terrorism-1412973796|title=The Capitalist Cure for Terrorism|first=Hernando de|last=Soto|date=10 October 2014|accessdate=16 August 2018|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref> He also mentions in the article that local policymakers in the Middle East are missing the fact that if ordinary people cannot play the game legally, they will be far less able to resist a terrorist offensive. The article received praise among high-level global politicians such as US Presidential candidates Rand Paul and Jeb Bush.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/twentysixteen/2015/02/04/exclusive-education-jeb-bush |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-11-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125051438/http://www.nationaljournal.com/twentysixteen/2015/02/04/exclusive-education-jeb-bush |archivedate=2015-11-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/rand-paul-isis-benghazi-and-bringing-us-troops-home-290947|title=Rand Paul on ISIS, Benghazi and Bringing U.S. Troops Home|date=11 December 2014|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOnce again In January 2016, De Soto released his second article, How to Win the War on Terror, which focused on defeating terrorism through promoting strong property rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economia.icaew.com/opinion/global-review-2015-winter/how-to-win-the-war-on-terror|title=How to win the war on terror|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> The article was distributed by Project Syndicate and published in dozens of countries and languages, including in Switzerland by the World Economic Forum in advance of their 2016 forum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2016/01/this-is-how-we-can-win-the-war-on-terror|title=This is how we can win the war on terror|website=World Economic Forum|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/mundo/ee-uu-y-canada/como-ganarle-la-guerra-al-terrorismo-analisis/16490102|title=C\u00f3mo ganarle la guerra al terrorismo / An\u00e1lisis|first=Casa Editorial El|last=Tiempo|website=El Tiempo|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== De Soto challenges Thomas Piketty and approaches Pope Francis ===\n\nIn 2014, De Soto started to refute French economist [[Thomas Piketty]]\u2019s thesis by arguing that his recent attacks against capital in his worldwide best seller book \"[[Capital in the 21st Century]]\" were unjustified.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hernando de Soto refuted the theories of Thomas Piketty|url=http://elcomercio.pe/economia/opinion/hernando-soto-refuto-teorias-thomas-piketty-noticia-1808487|website=El Comercio Portfolio|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> His op-ed article challenging Piketty, \u2018The Poor Against Piketty\u2019 (French - Les pauvres contre Piketty) was first published in France's news magazine ''Le Point'' in April 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/editos-du-point/sebastien-le-fol/les-pauvres-contre-piketty-16-04-2015-1922011_1913.php|title=Les pauvres contre Piketty|last=magazine|first=Le Point|date=2015-04-16|newspaper=Le Point|language=fr-FR|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref>\n\nDe Soto argued that Piketty's statistics ignore the 90 per cent of the world population that lives in developing countries and former Soviet states, whose inhabitants produce and hold their capital in the [[informal sector]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Why Thomas Piketty is wrong about capital in the 21st century|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/comment/why-thomas-piketty-is-wrong-about-capital-in-the-21st-century-10251801.htm|website=The Independent|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> Furthermore, he states that his institute's global research proves that most people actually want more rather than less capital. Finally, he argues that the wars against capital, which Piketty claims are coming, have already begun under Europe's nose in the form of the [[Arab Spring]] in the Middle East and North Africa.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Canoy|first1=Marcel|title=Why De Soto owns Piketty|url=http://www.ild.org.pe/ild-in-the-news/174-2015/971-why-de-soto-owns-piketty|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> \nThe article in English was published in ''[[The Independent]]'' under the title, \u2018[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/comment/why-thomas-piketty-is-wrong-about-capital-in-the-21st-century-10251801.html Why Thomas Piketty is wrong about capital in the 21st century]\u2019, in May 2015 and has since been published in over twenty countries, including in Germany's ''Die Welt'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Die Armen der Welt sind viel reicher als gedacht|url=https://www.welt.de/debatte/kommentare/article142052977/Die-Armen-der-Welt-sind-viel-reicher-als-gedacht.html|website=Die Welt|accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref> Nigeria's ''Ventures Africa'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The Poor Against Piketty|url=http://venturesafrica.com/features/the-poor-against-piketty/|website=Venture Africa|accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref> Spain's ''El Pais'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Los pobres frente a Piketty |url=http://economia.elpais.com/economia/2015/04/29/actualidad/1430325144_581940.html|website=El Pais|accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref> Egypt's ''Youm 7'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youm7.com/story/2015/5/3/90-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%B3%D9%83%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%8A%D8%AD%D8%AA%D9%81%D8%B8%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A8%D8%A3%D9%85%D9%88%D9%84%D9%87%D9%85-%D8%A8%D8%B9%D9%8A%D8%AF%D8%A7-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D8%AD%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%A6%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%8A/2165688#.Vb6QdpNVikq|website=Youm 7|accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref> and Brazil's ''Folha de S.Paulo'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The poor against Piketty|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/ilustrissima/2015/06/1638385-os-pobres-contra-piketty.shtml|website=Folha|accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref> Canada's ''Vancouver Sun'' <ref name=\"tvs1\">{{Cite news|url=https://vancouversun.com/Opinion+poor+against+Piketty/11273987/story.html|title=Opinion: The poor against Piketty|last=Soto|first=Hernando de|newspaper=www.vancouversun.com|language=en-ca|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref> and the ''Miami Herald''.<ref name=\"mh1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/opinion/issues-ideas/article29774506.html|title=Hernando De Soto dissects Thomas Piketty's apocalyptic political thesis|newspaper=miamiherald|language=en|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, De Soto took a break from countering Piketty's work and wrote an article addressing [[Pope Francis]]\u2019s trip to Mexico titled, A Mexican Impasse for the Pope.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/pope-francis-property-rights-by-hernando-de-soto-2016-02?barrier=true|title=A Mexican Impasse for the Pope - by Hernando de Soto|first=Hernando de|last=Soto|date=11 February 2016|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> The article encourages the Pope and the Vatican to address the lack of property rights among the poor in countries like Mexico as a solution to global refugee crises.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neurope.eu/article/the-pope-and-property-rights/|title=The Pope and property rights|date=15 February 2016|accessdate=16 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216092601/http://neurope.eu/article/the-pope-and-property-rights/|archive-date=2016-02-16|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/viewpoints/analysis/helping-those-without-rights-to-step-out-of-the-shadows-381405.html|title=Helping those without rights to step out of the shadows|date=12 February 2016|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nA week later, De Soto published a second article in Fortune Magazine addressing the Pope's and US Republican Presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]]\u2019s public spat over [[Trump's border wall|building a wall]] on the Mexican-USA border. The article titled, What Pope Francis Should Really Say to Donald Trump, conveys five property rights related thoughts that the Pope should use to respond to Trump.<ref name=\"fortune.com\">{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/02/25/pope-francis-donald-trump-immigration/|title=What Pope Francis Should Really Say to Donald Trump|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> The article was well received in the US and led to many different opinion articles featured in Breitbart, Investors Business Daily and Stream.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.investors.com/politics/capital-hill/pope-francis-keeps-listening-to-the-wrong-peruvian/|title=Pope Francis Keeps Listening To The Wrong Peruvian|last=Daily|first=Investor's Business|date=2016-02-19|newspaper=Investor's Business Daily|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://stream.org/pope-francis-hernando-de-soto-poor-property-rights/|title=Pope Francis and Economist Hernando de Soto Agree on One Thing: Free the Poor by Protecting Their Property Rights {{!}} The Stream|date=2016-02-17|newspaper=The Stream|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref>\n\n==Blockchain work==\nIn May 2015, De Soto attended the 1st Annual Block Chain Summit hosted by British billionaire [[Richard Branson]] at his private Caribbean residence, [[Necker Island (British Virgin Islands)|Necker Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blockchainsummit.io/|title=Block Chain Summit|last=Bitfury|website=www.blockchainsummit.io|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virgin.com/richard-branson/shaping-serendipity|title=Shaping serendipity|last=admin|date=16 June 2015|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> De Soto was one of three moderators, along with Michael J. Casey, former ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]'' senior columnist and Matthew Bishop, editor at ''[[The Economist]]''. Advocates of [[blockchain (database)|blockchain]] technology argue that it is well-suited to acting as a public ledger to help achieve De Soto's objective of formalising the informally-held property rights of groups like the indigenous peoples of Peru.<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2015/07/01/venture-capitalist-bill-tai-my-summer-reading-list-commentary.html.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2015/06/02/bitbeat-grand-plans-for-bitcoin-from-necker-island/|title=BitBeat: Grand Plans for Bitcoin From Necker Island|last=Casey|first=Michael J.|newspaper=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortaleciendocapacidades.lamula.pe/2015/05/28/culmina-cumbre-que-reune-a-las-mentes-mas-brillantes-del-mundo/habilidadesdiferentes/|title=CULMINA CUMBRE QUE RE\u00daNE A LAS MENTES M\u00c1S BRILLANTES DEL MUNDO|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ifoldsflip.com/i/598242-techonomy-magazine-2015|title=Techonomy Report - Techonomy Magazine 2015|website=www.ifoldsflip.com|language=en|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2016/03/could-blockchain-technology-help-the-worlds-poor|title=Could blockchain technology help the world's poor?|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=2017-01-28}}</ref>\n\nDe Soto presented a property application of Bitcoin to [[Sheikh Nahyan bin Mubarak Al Nahyan]] of the [[United Arab Emirates]] and financial authorities of [[Abu Dhabi]] at a second Blockchain summit held in Abu Dhabi in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ild.org.pe/ild-in-the-news/174-2015/1018-de-soto-a-main-speaker-at-block-chain-sumit-in-abu-dhabi|title=De Soto Speaks at a Block Chain Summit in Abu Dhabi|last=Brad|first=Kamloops|website=ild.org.pe|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-01-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055211/http://ild.org.pe/ild-in-the-news/174-2015/1018-de-soto-a-main-speaker-at-block-chain-sumit-in-abu-dhabi|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Praise for work==\nSince the publication of ''The Mystery of Capital'' in 2000 and subsequent translations, his ideas have become increasingly influential in the field of development economics.\n\n[[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine]] chose De Soto as one of the five leading [[Latin American]] innovators of the century in its special May 1999 issue \"Leaders of the New Millennium\", and included him among the 100 most influential people in the world in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.comhttp//content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1970858_1970888_1971022,00.html?xid=fblike|title=The 2004 TIME 100 - TIME|website=TIME.com|accessdate=16 August 2018}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> De Soto was also listed as one of the 15 innovators \"who will reinvent your future\" according to ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine's 85th anniversary edition. In January 2000, ''Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit'', the German development magazine, described De Soto as one of the most important development theoreticians.<ref>[http://www.inwent.org/E+Z/zeitschr/ez100-6.htm Hans-Heinrich Bass und Markus Wauschkuhn: Hernando de Soto \u2013 die Legalisierung des Faktischen, in: E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, 2000, Nr. 1, S. 15\u201318.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730235128/http://www.inwent.org/E+Z/zeitschr/ez100-6.htm |date=2013-07-30 }}</ref> In October 2005, over 20,000 readers of [[Prospect (magazine)|''Prospect'' magazine]] of the UK and ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' magazine of the U.S. ranked him as number 13 on the joint survey of the world's ''[[Top 100 Public Intellectuals Poll]]''.\n\nU.S. presidents from both major parties have praised De Soto's work. [[Bill Clinton]], for example, called him \"The world's greatest living economist\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unc.edu/news/archives/oct04/fpg_desoto101904.html|title=UNC News release -- Noted economist de Soto to discuss property rights|website=www.unc.edu|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> [[George H. W. Bush]] declared that \"De Soto's prescription offers a clear and promising alternative to economic stagnation\u2026\"<ref>Source for President George H. W. Bush's remarks: ''Text of Remarks by the President to the World Bank/International Monetary Fund Annual Meeting'', 27 September 1989, announcing NAFTA. Press release.</ref> Bush's predecessor, [[Ronald Reagan]] said, \"De Soto and his colleagues have examined the only ladder for [[upward mobility]]. The [[free market]] is the other path to development and the one true path. It is the people's path\u2026 it leads somewhere. It works.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cato.org/special/friedman/desoto/praise.html|title=Praise for de Soto and Institute for Liberty and Democracy|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> His work has also received praise from two [[United Nations]] secretaries general [[Kofi Annan]] \u2013 \"Hernando de Soto is absolutely right, that we need to rethink how we capture economic growth and development\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2001/sgsm7892.doc.htm|title=TRANSCRIPT OF PRESS CONFERENCE BY SECRETARY-GENERAL KOFI ANNAN AT INTERNATIONAL LABOUR ORGANIZATION, GENEVA, 16 JULY 2001 - Meetings Coverage and Press Releases|website=www.un.org|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> \u2013 and [[Javier P\u00e9rez de Cu\u00e9llar]] \u2013 \"A crucial contribution. A new proposal for change that is valid for the whole world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booksattransworld.co.uk/catalog/book.htm?command=Search&db=twmain.txt&eqisbndata=0552999237|title=Penguin Books|website=www.booksattransworld.co.uk|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, de Soto was honored with the [[Brigham-Kanner Property Rights Prize]], awarded by the [[William & Mary Law School]] during the 13th Annual [[Brigham-Kanner Property Rights Conference]], in recognition of his tireless advocacy of property rights reform as a tool to alleviate global poverty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://law.wm.edu/news/stories/2016/internationally-renowned-peruvian-economist-de-soto-honored-at-13th-property-rights-conference.php|title=William & Mary Law School - Internationally Renowned Peruvian Economist de Soto Honored at 13th Property Rights Conference|website=law.wm.edu|access-date=2016-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==Prizes==\nAmong the prizes he has received are:\n* The Freedom Prize (Switzerland)\n* The Fisher Prize (United Kingdom)\n* 2002\n** the Goldwater Award (USA)\n** [[Adam Smith Award]] from the [[Association of Private Enterprise Education]] (USA)\n** The CARE Canada Award for Outstanding Development Thinking ([[Canada]])\n* 2003\n** received the Downey Fellowship at [[Yale University]]\n** the Democracy Hall of Fame International Award from the National Graduate University (USA)\n* 2004\n** the Templeton Freedom Prize (USA)\n** the [[Milton Friedman Prize for Advancing Liberty]] (USA)<ref name=\"cato.org\"/>\n** the Royal Decoration of the Most Admirable [[Order of the Direkgunabhorn]], 5th Class, ([[Thailand]])\n* 2005\n** an honorary Doctor of Letters from the [[University of Buckingham]] ([[United Kingdom]]),\n** The Americas Award (USA)\n** named the Most Outstanding of 2004 for Economic Development at Home and Abroad by the Peruvian National Assembly of Rectors\n** received the Prize of Deutsche Stiftung Eigentum for exceptional contributions to the theory of property rights\n** the 2004 IPAE Award by the Peruvian Institute of Business Administration\n** the [[Academy of Achievement|Academy of Achievement's]] [[Golden Plate Award]] 2005 (USA) in tribute to his outstanding accomplishments\n** the [[BearingPoint]], ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'' magazine's seventh Compass Award for Strategic Direction\n** was named as a \"Fellow of the Class of 1930\" by [[Dartmouth College]].\n* 2006\n** the 2006 [[Bradley Prize]] for outstanding achievement by the [[Bradley Foundation]].<ref>[http://www.bradleyfdn.org/cm-prizes.asp?ID=2006BradleyPrizeWinners Bradley Foundation \u2013 Prizes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100713064747/http://www.bradleyfdn.org/cm-prizes.asp?ID=2006BradleyPrizeWinners |date=2010-07-13 }}</ref>\n** the 2006 Innovation Award (Social and Economic Innovation) from ''[[The Economist]]'' magazine (December 2, 2006) for the promotion of property rights and economic development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/search/displaystory.cfm?story_id=E1_RTVSSVR|title=Search|website=The Economist|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n* 2007\n** The Poder BCG Business Awards 2007, granted by ''Poder'' Magazine and the [[Boston Consulting Group]], for the \"Best Anti-Poverty Initiative\"\n** the anthology ''Die Zw\u00f6lf Wichtigsten \u00d6konomen der Welt'' (The World's Twelve Most Influential Economists, 2007), included a profile of de Soto among a list that begins with Adam Smith and includes such recent winners of the Nobel Prize in Economics as [[Joseph Stiglitz]] and [[Amartya Sen]].\n** the 2007 Humanitarian Award in recognition of his work to help poor people participate in the market economy.\n* 2009\n** Honorary patron of the [[University Philosophical Society]] of [[Trinity College, Dublin]] for having excelled in public life and made a worthy contribution to society.\n** the inaugural Hernando de Soto Award for Democracy awarded by the [[Center for International Private Enterprise]] (CIPE) in recognition of his extraordinary achievements in furthering economic freedom in Peru and throughout the developing world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cipe.advomation.com/25th/|title=CIPE @ 25|website=cipe.advomation.com|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n* 2010\n** the Hayek Medal for his theories on liberal development policy (\"market economy from below\") and for the appropriate implementation of his concepts by two Peruvian presidents.\n** the [[Medal of the Presidency of the Italian Republic]] (Council of Ministers) in recognition of his contribution toward the betterment of humankind and having worked for the future of the earth through his commitment.\n* 2016\n** received the 2016 [[Brigham\u2013Kanner Property Rights Prize]] from William & Mary Law School during a ceremony in The Hague, Netherlands, in October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2016/hernando-de-soto-to-receive-2016-brigham-kanner-property-rights-prize.php|title=William & Mary -\u00a0Hernando de Soto to receive 2016 Brigham-Kanner Property Rights Prize|website=www.wm.edu|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===World Justice Project===\nHernando de Soto serves as an honorary co-chair for the [[World Justice Project]]. The [[World Justice Project]] works to lead a global, multidisciplinary effort to strengthen the [[rule of law]] for the development of communities of opportunity and equity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldjusticeproject.com/about/|title=About|accessdate=2010-02-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203064233/http://www.worldjusticeproject.com/about/|archivedate=2010-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and responses==\nDe Soto's works on [[Right to property|property rights]] has voiced diverse views on the effect of the [[Titling|titling of land]].<ref>Bruce, J., Migot-Adholla, S. (Eds.), 1994. Searching for Land Tenure Security in Africa. Kendall Hunt, Dubuque.</ref><ref>Pinckney, T.C. and P.K. Kimuyu. 1994. \"Land Tenure Reform in East Africa: Good, Bad or Unimportant?\" Journal of African Economies 3 (1): 1\u201328.</ref> De Soto has been criticized for methodological and analytical reasons, while some activists have accused him of just wanting to be a representative figure of the prioritizing property rights movement.<ref>Sjaastada, Espen and Ben Cousins. 2008. \"Formalisation of Land Rights In the South: An Overview.\" Land Use Policy 26: 1\u20139</ref> Some state that his theory does not offer anything new compared to traditional land reform. \"De Soto\u2019s proposal is not wealth transfer, but wealth legalization.<ref>Gilbert, Alan. 2002. On the mystery of capital and the myths of Hernando de Soto. What difference does legal title make? International Development Planning Review 24 (1) 1\u201319.</ref><ref>Deininger, Klaus. 2003. Land Policies for Growth and Poverty Reduction. Washington, DC: World Bank.</ref> The poor of the world already possess trillions in assets now. De Soto is not distributing capital to anyone. By making them liquid, everyone\u2019s capital pool grows dramatically\".<ref name=\"Biswas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.floorgroup.raumplanung.tu-dortmund.de/FLOOR_Working_papers/FLOOR_WP018_Dey_Biswas_Land_rights_formalization_India.pdf|title=Dey Biswas, Sattwick. 2014. Land Rights Formalization in India; Examining de Soto through the lens of Rawls theory of justice. FLOOR Working paper 18|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> While analysing Schaefer's arguments, Roy writes, \"de Soto\u2019s ideas are seductive precisely because they only guarantee the latter, but in doing so promise the former\".<ref>Roy, Dayabati. 2013. Rural Politics in India: Political Stratification and Governance in West Bengal. Cambridge University Press, pp 152</ref><ref>Platteau, J.-P. 1996. \"The Evolutionary Theory of Land Rights as Applied To Sub-Saharan Africa: A Critical Assessment.\" Development and Change 27 (1): 29\u201385.</ref>\n\nWhat differentiates de Soto from his predecessor is his attempt to include non-agricultural land in the scheme of reform and emphasizing in formalization of existing informal possession.<ref name=\"Sjaastada 2008\">Sjaastada, Espen and Ben Cousins. 2008. \"Formalisation of Land Rights In the South: An Overview.\" Land Use Policy 26: 1\u20139.</ref> His emphasis on title formalization as the only reason behind economic growth in the United States has been subject to criticism.<ref>Madrick, Jeff. 2001. [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2001/may/31/the-charms-of-property/ The Charms of Property]. ''The New York Review of Books''</ref> Property formalization in America may have happened as a result of different reasons including establishment of law and order, increased state control, greater institutional integration, increased economic efficiency, increased tax revenue, and greater equality.(<ref name=\"Sjaastada 2008\"/>) The argument for private and often individualist property regime comes under the question of societal legitimacy, may not be justified even if de Soto eyes bringing an unified system in a state or unification with the global economy.<ref name=\"Biswas\" />\n\nIn his ''Planet of Slums'',<ref>Mike Davis, ''Planet of Slums'', Verso, 2006 pp. 79\u201382</ref> [[Mike Davis (scholar)|Mike Davis]] argues that de Soto, who Davis calls 'the global guru of neo-liberal populism', is essentially promoting what the statist left in South America and India has always promoted\u2014individual [[land titling]]. Davis argues that titling is the incorporation into the formal economy of cities, which benefits more wealthy squatters but is disastrous for poorer squatters, and especially tenants who simply cannot afford incorporation into the fully commodified formal economy.\n\nGrassroots controlled and directed shack dwellers movements like [[Abahlali baseMjondolo]] in [[South Africa]] and the [[Homeless Workers' Movement]] (Movimento dos Trabalhadores Sem Teto \u2013 MTST) in Brazil<ref>[http://www.mtst.info MTST \u2013 Movimento dos Trabalhadores Sem Teto] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706135612/http://www.mtst.info/ |date=2008-07-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mstbrazil.org/|title=Home - Friends of the MST|website=www.mstbrazil.org|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> have strenuously argued against individual titling and for communal and democratic systems of collective land tenure because this offers protection to the poorest and prevents 'downward raiding' in which richer people displace squatters once their neighborhoods are formalized.\n\nAn article by [[Madeleine Bunting]] for ''[[The Guardian]]'' (UK) claimed that de Soto's suggestions would in some circumstances cause more harm than benefit, and referred to The Mystery of Capital as \"an elaborate smokescreen\" used to obscure the issue of the power of the globalized elite. She cited de Soto's employment history as evidence of his bias in favor of the powerful.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2000/sep/11/imf.comment|last=Bunting|first=Madeleine|title=Fine words, flawed ideas|work=The Guardian|date=11 September 2000}}</ref> Reporter [[John Gravois]] also criticized de Soto for his ties to power circles, exemplified by his attendance at the [[Davos]] [[World Economic Forum]]. In response, de Soto told Gravois that this proximity to power would help de Soto educate the elites about poverty. [[Ivan Osorio]] of the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]] has refuted Gravois's allegations pointing out how Gravois has misinterpreted many of de Soto's recommendations.<ref name=\"Osorio\">{{Cite web |url=http://cei.org/gencon/019,04389.cfm |title=Osorio, Ivan. Will the Real Hernando de Soto Please Stand Up?, originally published as Osorio Op-ed in Tech Central Station, February 2, 2005 |access-date=January 6, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202005655/http://www.cei.org/gencon/019%2C04389.cfm |archive-date=December 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Robert J. Samuelson]] has argued against what he sees as de Soto's \"single bullet\" approach and has argued for a greater emphasis on culture and how local conditions affect people's perceptions of their opportunities.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20010101fareviewessay2001010112/robert-j-samuelson/the-spirit-of-capitalism.html|last=Samuelson|first=Robert J|title=The Spirit of Capitalism|journal=Foreign Affairs|date=January\u2013February 2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080312222150/http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20010101fareviewessay2001010112/robert-j-samuelson/the-spirit-of-capitalism.html|archivedate=12 March 2008}}</ref> UN Special Rapporteur on the right to food, [[Olivier De Schutter]], has questioned the insistence on titling as a means to protect security of tenure based on the risk that titling will undermine customary forms of tenure and insufficiently protect the rights of land users that depend on the commons, as well as the fear that titling schemes may lead to further reconcentration of land ownership, unless strong support is provided to smallholders.\n\nIn the [[World Development]] journal, a 1990 article by R. G. Rossini and J. J. Thomas of the [[London School of Economics]] questioned the statistical basis of de Soto's claims about the size of the informal economy in his first book ''The Other Path''.<ref>[http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/B6VC6-45CWV65-32/2/0eeb1e04e92415f8fb6c2e3efaae1ee7 Rossini, R. G. and J. J. Thomas. \"The size of the informal sector in Peru: A critical comment on Hernando de Soto's El Otro Sendero\", in World Development, Volume 18, Issue 1, January 1990, pp. 125\u201335.]</ref> However, the ILD pointed out, in the same journal, that Rossini and Thomas\u2019 observations \"neither [addressed] the central theme of the book, nor [did it address] the main body of quantitative evidence displayed to substantiate the importance of economic and legal barriers that give rise to informal activities. Instead, [they focused] exclusively on four empirical estimates that the book [mentioned] only in passing\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=A reply|date=1 January 1990|journal=World Development|volume=18|issue=1|pages=137\u2013145|doi=10.1016/0305-750X(90)90108-A}}</ref>\n\nIn the ''[[Journal of Economic Literature]]'', [[Christopher Woodruff]] of the [[University of California, San Diego]] criticized de Soto for overestimating the amount of wealth that land titling now informally owned property could unlock, and argues that \"de Soto's own experience in Peru suggests that land titling by itself is not likely to have much effect. Titling must be followed by a series of politically challenging steps. Improving the efficiency of judicial systems, rewriting bankruptcy codes, restructuring financial market regulations, and similar reforms will involve much more difficult choices by policymakers.\"<ref>[http://epserv.unila.ac.id/jurnal/BAhan/Jurnal%20Of%20Economic%20lietratur/Content/2001/dec/articles/woodruff.pdf Woodruff, Christopher. Review: Review of de Soto's \"The Mystery of Capital\", Journal of Economic Literature, Vol. 39, No. 4 (Dec., 2001), pp. 1215\u201323]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=imf1>{{cite web|url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/fandd/2003/12/pdf/people.pdf|title=Clift, Jeremy. \"People in Economics: Hernando de Soto\" \u2013 Finance & Development \u2013 December 2003.|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nEmpirical studies by Argentine economists [[Sebastian Galiani]] and [[Ernesto Schargrodsky]] have taken issue with de Soto's link between titling and the increase in credit to the poor, but have also pointed out that families with titles \"substantially increased housing investment, reduced household size, and improved the education of their children relative to the control group\".<ref>[http://coase.org/workingpapers/wp-7.pdf Galiani, Sebastian and Ernesto Schargrodsky. ''Property Rights for the Poor: Effects of Land Titling'' \u2013 Ronald Coase Institute, Working Paper Series, revised January 2009, ]</ref> In a 2012 book by Yale University political science methodologist Thad Dunning, he argues that Galiani and Schargrodsky's studies provide \"highly credible\" claims because the studies rely on true randomization, whereas De Soto's study did not (and is thus vulnerable to confounding variables).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/natural-experiments-in-the-social-sciences/introduction/CFD585F55CEF077D132706D2D7820548|title=Introduction|last=Dunning|first=Thad|date=2012|website=Natural Experiments in the Social Sciences: A Design-Based Approach|pages=5-12|language=en|doi=10.1017/cbo9781139084444.002|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> A study commissioned by [[DFID]], an agency of the [[U.K. government]], further summarized many of the complications arising from implementing de Soto's policy recommendations when insufficient attention is paid to the local social context.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oxfam.org.uk/resources/learning/landrights/downloads/land_changing_contexts_relationships_rights.rtf |title=Daley, Elizabeth and Mary Hobley. ''Land: Changing Contexts, Changing Relationships, Changing Rights'' (for DFID's Urban-Rural Change Team) September 2005 |access-date=2010-01-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608083557/http://www.oxfam.org.uk/resources/learning/landrights/downloads/land_changing_contexts_relationships_rights.rtf |archive-date=2011-06-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDe Soto himself has often pointed out that his critics mistakenly claim that he advocates land titling by itself as sufficient for effective development: For example, in the ILD's new brochure he is quoted as saying, \"The ILD is not just about titling. What we do is help Governments build a system of public memory that legally identifies all their people, their assets, their business records and their transactions in such a way that they can unleash their economic potential. No economy can develop and prosper without the benefits that clearly registered public documents bestow.\"<ref>Institute for Liberty and Democracy, ''The ILD's war against exclusion'', p. 21. 2009</ref>\n\nOn January 31, 2012, de Soto and his publisher were fined by the Peruvian intellectual property rights organization INDECOPI for excluding the names of co-authors, [[Enrique Ghersi]] and [[Mario Ghibellini]], on newer editions of his 1986 book ''The Other Path''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Per\u00fa: Condenan por infracci\u00f3n a derecho moral de paternidad a economista Hernando de Soto|url=http://iptango.blogspot.ca/2012/02/peru-condenan-por-infraccion-derecho.html|website=IP Tango: weblog for intellectual property law and practice for Latin America|accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref><ref>http://elcomercio.pe/economia/peru/sancionan-hernando-soto-violacion-propiedad-intelectual-noticia-1368239</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sistemas.indecopi.gob.pe/SPI_Jurisprudencia/documentos/1-45/2012/0040-2012.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721151832/http://sistemas.indecopi.gob.pe/SPI_Jurisprudencia/documentos/1-45/2012/0040-2012.pdf |archivedate=2015-07-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indecopi.gob.pe/0/modulos/NOT/NOT_DetallarNoticia.aspx?PFL=0&NOT=382 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-07-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924034223/http://www.indecopi.gob.pe/0/modulos/NOT/NOT_DetallarNoticia.aspx?PFL=0&NOT=382 |archivedate=2015-09-24 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books===\nDe Soto has published two books about economic development: ''The Other Path: The Invisible Revolution in the Third World'' in 1986 in Spanish (with a new edition in 2002 titled ''The Other Path, The Economic Answer to Terrorism'') and in 2000, ''The Mystery of Capital: Why Capitalism Triumphs in the West and Fails Everywhere Else'' ({{ISBN|978-0465016150}}). Both books have been international bestsellers, translated into some 30 languages.\n\nThe original [[Spanish language|Spanish-language]] title of ''The Other Path'' is ''El Otro Sendero'', an allusion to de Soto's alternative proposals for development in Peru, countering the attempts of the \"[[Shining Path]]\" (''\"Sendero Luminoso\"'') to win the support of Peru's poor. Based on five years worth of ILD research into the causes of massive informality and legal exclusion in Peru, the book was also a direct intellectual challenge to the Shining Path, offering to the poor of Peru not the violent overthrow of the system but \"the other path\" out of poverty, through legal reform. In response, the Senderistas added de Soto to their assassination list. In July 1992, the terrorists sent a second car bomb into ILD headquarters in Lima, killing 3 and wounding 19.\n\nIn addition, he has written, with Francis Cheneval, ''Swiss Human Rights Book Volume 1: Realizing Property Rights'', published in 2006 \u2013 a collection of papers presented at an international symposium in Switzerland in 2006 on the urgency of property rights in impoverished countries for small business owners, women, and other vulnerable groups, such as the poor and political refugees. The book includes a paper on the ILD's work in Tanzania delivered by Hernando de Soto.<ref>[http://www.swisshumanrightsbook.com/SHRB/home.html De Soto, Hernando and Francis Cheneval. Swiss Human Rights Book Volume 1: Realizing Property Rights, 2006.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121043723/http://www.swisshumanrightsbook.com/SHRB/home.html |date=2008-11-21 }}</ref>\n* De Soto, Hernando. ''The Other Path: The Invisible Revolution in the Third World''. Harpercollins, 1989. {{ISBN|0-06-016020-9}}\n* De Soto, Hernando. ''The Mystery of Capital: Why Capitalism Triumphs in the West and Fails Everywhere Else''. Basic Books, 2000. {{ISBN|0-465-01614-6}}\n* De Soto, Hernando. ''[[The Other Path]]: The Economic Answer to Terrorism''. Basic Books, 2002. {{ISBN|0-465-01610-3}}\n* De Soto, Hernando and Francis Cheneval. ''Swiss Human Rights Book Volume 1: Realizing Property Rights'', 2006. {{ISBN|978-3-907625-25-5}}\n* Smith, Barry et al. (eds.). ''The Mystery of Capital and the Construction of Social Reality'', Chicago: Open Court, 2008. {{ISBN|0-8126-9615-8}}\n\n===Articles===\nDe Soto has also published a number of articles on the importance of inclusive property and business rights, legally empowering the poor, and the causes of the global financial crisis of 2008\u201309 in leading newspapers and magazines around the world. In 2001, ''Time'' magazine published \"The Secret of Non-Success,\"<ref name=\"time1\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0QOQ6_I6NqwC&lpg=PA49&dq=%22The+Secret+of+Non-Success%E2%80%9D+Time+magazine&pg=PA49#v=onepage&q=%22The+Secret+of+Non-Success%E2%80%9D+Time+magazine&f=false|title=New Horizons for Foreign Direct Investment|first=Global Forum on International|last=Investment|date=1 January 2002|publisher=Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|accessdate=16 August 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9789264197282}}</ref> the New York Times ran his post-September 11 op-ed essay \"The Constituency of Terror,\"<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/15/opinion/15DESO.html|title=The Constituency of Terror|first=Hernando De|last=Soto|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> and the IMF's Finance & Development magazine published \"The Mystery of Capital\", a condensed version of the third chapter of his eponymous book.<ref name=\"imf2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/fandd/2001/03/desoto.htm|title=Finance and Development|website=Finance and Development - F&D|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> In 2007, ''Time'' magazine published \"Giving the Poor their Rights\", an article written with former Secretary of State, Madeleine Albright, on the legal empowerment of the poor. In 2009, Newsweek International published his essay on the financial crisis, \"Toxic Paper\"<ref name=\"nw1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/185814|title=Hernando de Soto on the Toxic-Paper Problem|date=20 February 2009|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> \u2013 along with an on-line interview with him, \"Slumdogs and Millionaires.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/185656|title=Economy: Slumdogs vs. Wall Street Millionaires|date=19 February 2009|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> That was soon followed by two more articles on the crisis, in the Wall Street Journal (\"Toxic Assets Were Hidden Assets\")<ref name=\"wsj1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123793811398132049|title=Toxic Assets Were Hidden Assets|first=Hernando de|last=Soto|date=25 March 2009|accessdate=16 August 2018|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref> and The Los Angeles Times (\"Global Meltdown Rule #1: Do the Math\").<ref name=\"lat1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/la-oe-desoto12-2009apr12-story.html|title=Global Meltdown Rule No. 1: Do the math|first=By Hernando de|last=Soto|website=latimes.com|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> Versions of these articles also appeared in newspapers in France, Switzerland, Germany and Latin America. In 2011, Bloomberg published \"The Destruction of Economic Facts\",<ref name=\"bb1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/11_19/b4227060634112.htm|title=De Soto, Hernando. \"The Destruction of Economic Facts\", Bloomberg Businessweek, 28 April 2011|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> and The Washington Post recently ran \"The cost of financial ignorance\".<ref name=\"wp3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/the-cost-of-financial-ignorance/2011/10/03/gIQAEU3yTL_story.html|title=The cost of financial ignorance|website=Washington Post|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> When protests began in Cairo at the beginning of 2011, The Wall Street Journal published De Soto's \"Egypt's Economic Apartheid\",<ref name=\"wsj2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704358704576118683913032882|title=Egypt's Economic Apartheid|first=Hernando de|last=Soto|date=3 February 2011|accessdate=16 August 2018|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref> and Financial Times later published \"The free-market secret of the Arab Revolution\".<ref name=\"ft1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/653fab0e-0a00-11e1-85ca-00144feabdc0.html|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Other Path: The Economic Answer to Terrorism]]''\n* [[Liberalism]]\n* [[Contributions to liberal theory]]\n* [[Dependency theory]]\n* [[Documentality]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ild.org.pe Institute for Liberty and Democracy] official website.\n* [http://www.newsweek.com/id/185656 \"Slumdogs vs. Millionaires\"], Newsweek's Barrett Sheridan interviews Hernando de Soto\n* [http://www.greatissuesforum.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=68&Itemid=76 The Great Issues Forum], video of [[Naomi Klein]], [[Joseph Stiglitz]], and Hernando de Soto discussing the financial crisis\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100206205134/http://ild.org.pe/news/esri \"Mapping the Invisible\"], speech by Hernando de Soto at the 2009 [http://www.esri.com/events/uc/ ESRI] International User Conference\n* [http://www.munkdebates.com/index.cfm?debate=1 The Munk Debate on Foreign Aid, 2009.]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Stephen Lewis and Paul Collier against Peruvian economist Hernando de Soto and Dambisa Moyo, a Zambian-born critic of foreign aid.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110118083151/http://www.aifestival.org/audio-video-library.php?menu=3&title=535&action=full_info Afternoon of Conversation: Andrea Mitchell, Madeleine Albright, Hernando De Soto], video of conversation\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090802211731/http://www.literalmagazine.com/es/archive-L13.php?section=archive&lang=es ''The Rule of Law''] \u2013 an interview with Hernando de Soto By Gustavo Wensjoe 2008\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/commandingheights/shared/minitextlo/int_hernandodesoto.html Transcript] of an interview for the PBS documentary [[Commanding Heights]].\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/Archive/Article/0,4273,4061838,00.html A highly critical review] in the British newspaper [[The Guardian]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080312222150/http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20010101fareviewessay2001010112/robert-j-samuelson/the-spirit-of-capitalism.html An essay by Robert Samuelson] in [[Foreign Affairs]], arguing that de Soto underestimates the importance of culture\n* [http://www.thepowerofthepoor.com/ The Power of the Poor] \u2013 Documentary about de Soto's work by Free to Choose Media\n* {{C-SPAN|hernandodesoto}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soto Polar, Hernando De}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies alumni]]\n[[Category:Development economists]]\n[[Category:Peruvian economists]]\n[[Category:People from Arequipa]]\n[[Category:Peruvian male writers]]\n[[Category:Winners of The Economist innovation awards]]\n", "name_user": "2x2leax", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hernando_de_Soto_Polar"}
{"title_page": "Sadhana Shivdasani", "text_new": "{{other uses2|Sadhana}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sadhana Shivdasani\n| image              = Nanda Waheeda Helen Sadhana.jpg\n| caption            = Sadhana (furthest right) alongside Nanda (left), Waheeda Rehman and Helen (middle)\n| birth_name         = Sadhana Shivdasani\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1941|09|02|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Karachi]], [[Sind Province (1936\u201355)|Sind]], [[British Raj|British India]] (present-day [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]])\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2015|12|25|1941|09|02|df=yes}}\n| death_place        = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| resting_place      = [[Oshiwara]], Mumbai, Maharashtra, India\n| residence          = [[Santacruz, Mumbai|Santacruz]], Mumbai, Mahrashtra, India\n| nationality        = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Jai Hind College]], Mumbai\n| occupation         = * [[Actress]]\n* [[film producer]]\n* [[film director]]\n| other_names        = Sadhana<br>''The Mystery Girl''\n| known_for          = [[Bollywood]] films and songs\n| style              = Sadhana cut\n| spouse             = {{marriage|R.K. Nayyar|1966|1995|end=died}}\n| relatives          = See [[List of Hindi film clans#Shivdasani family|Shivdasani family]]\n| awards             = [[IIFA Lifetime Achievement Award]] (2002)\n| years_active       = 1958\u20131981\n}}\n\n'''Sadhana Shivdasani''' (2 September 1941<ref name=HT/> \u2013 25 December 2015), popularly known by the mononym '''Sadhana''', was an Indian film actress, who appeared in many successful films of 1960s and 70s. Regarded as one of the finest and iconic film actresses in the history of [[Hindi cinema]], Sadhana was the highest-paid actress of her time from early 1960s to late 1970s. Popularly known as ''The Mystery Girl'', Sadhana was one of the most beautiful and the top actresses in the 1960s, a period regarded as [[Bollywood]]'s \"golden era\". She was active from 1960-1981.<ref name=hindu>{{cite news|title=Bollywood, kin, bid adieu to Sadhana|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/news/bollywood-kin-bid-adieu-to-sadhana/article8033705.ece|work=The Hindu|date=27 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sadhana Shivdasani Cremated, Waheeda Rehman, Asha Parekh Bid Farewell|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/sadhana-shivdasani-cremated-waheeda-rehman-asha-parekh-bid-farewell-1259238|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn a career spanning over four decades, Sadhana starred in over 30 successful films such as ''Hum Dono'', ''Woh Kaun Thi'', Rajkumar, Waqt, Mere Mehboob, Mera Saaya, Anita, Sachaai and Ek Phool do mali. Shivdasani appeared in the [[Sindhi language]] film ''Abaana'' and entered the [[Bollywood|Hindi film industry]] through the 1960s romantic film ''[[Love in Simla]]''. Her [[fringe (hair)|fringe haircut]] became popular during the 1960s and came to be known as the \"Sadhana cut\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Sadhana: The actor with the timeless elegance, the fringe and that outfit|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/in-the-60s-there-was-nothing-as-influential-as-the-sadhana-cut|newspaper=The Indian Express|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sadhana will always be remembered for her trendsetting 'Sadhana cut' hairstyle, say fans|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/lifestyle-2/sadhana-will-always-be-remembered-as-a-trendsetter-say-fans-1181792.html|publisher=IBNLive|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe became famous with her three suspense thriller films; ''[[Woh Kaun Thi?]]'' (1964), ''[[Mera Saaya]]'' (1966) and ''[[Anita (1967 film)|Anita]]'' (1967), all directed by [[Raj Khosla]]. Sadhana was given a double role in her two commercial successful films ''Woh Kaun Thi?'' and ''Mera Saaya''. She was nominated for the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress]] for films such as ''[[Woh Kaun Thi?]]'' and ''[[Waqt (1965 film)|Waqt]]'' in 1965 and 1966 respectively. She took retirement from the film industry in the mid-1970s before which she also directed and co-produced a few films. She received the [[IIFA Lifetime Achievement Award]] for her contributions to hit and evergreen classic films of [[Bollywood]].\n\nSadhana married her ''Love in Shimla'' director R.K. Nayyar in 1966. Their marriage lasted for 30 years and ended when R.K. Nayyar died in 1995. Sadhana never married after his death and lived alone for most of her life. Sadhana was diagnosed with [[cancer]] in her old age that led her to her death on 25 December 2015.\n\n==Early life==\nSadhana was born Sadhana Shivdasani in a [[Sindhi Hindus|Sindhi Hindu]] family<ref name=Interview1991>{{cite magazine|url=https://docs.google.com/document/pub?id=13wK4lve5tli4rLyLAGXDjBkgiHD7MPh9kaw63qlRJmc|title=The Sadhana Mystique|magazine=Filmfare|date=July 1991|author=Punita Bhatt|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> in [[Karachi]], [[British Raj|British India]] on 2 September 1941. She was an only child. Sadhana was named after her father's favorite actress-dancer [[Sadhana Bose]]. Her father was the elder brother of actor [[Hari Shivdasani]], father of actress [[Babita]].\n\nThe family migrated from [[Karachi]] during the post-[[Partition of India|Partition]] riots and settled in [[Mumbai]]. Her mother home-schooled her until she was 8 years old, after which she studied at Auxilium Convent, Wadala and [[Jai Hind College]]. Although they encountered difficult times, Sadhana was allowed to watch as many as two films. Sadhana was inspired to become a [[film actress]] and actress [[Nutan]] was said to have been her inspiration.<ref name=Interview1990>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/pub?id=1d0vDKTadIBf_bIVfEbUgtk1MZsZnQ2THX2_AHnObVoM|title= Interview in Movie Magazine|author=Chandrika Bhattacharya |accessdate=3 February 2012|publisher=Movie Magazine|year=1990}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nSadhana aspired to be an actress since childhood. Her father helped her enter films. In 1955 she played a chorus girl in the song \"Mur mur ke na dekh mur mur ke\" in [[Raj Kapoor]]'s ''[[Shree 420]]''.<ref name=\"Song\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/feb/11dinesh.htm|title=Sadhana's Song|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Rediff.com|access-date=|accessdate=2 February 2012|author=[[Dinesh Raheja]]}}</ref><ref name=Upperstall>{{cite web|url=http://www.upperstall.com/people/sadhana |title=Sadhana|publisher=Upperstall|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> When she was 15 years old, she was approached by some producers who had seen her act in a college play. They cast her in India's first Sindhi film titled ''Abaana'' (1958), where she played the role of [[Sheila Ramani]]'s younger sister.<ref name=Song/>\n\nA photograph of her publicizing ''Shree 420'' appeared in the movie magazine ''[[Screen (magazine)|Screen]]''. It was then that [[Sashadhar Mukherjee]], one of Hindi cinema's leading producers at that time, noticed her. She joined Mukherjee's acting school along with her debutant co-star [[Joy Mukherjee]]. Sashadhar's son R.K. Nayyar, who had previously worked as assistant director on a few films, directed this film. He also created her trademark look, called the ''Sadhana cut'', inspired by British actress [[Audrey Hepburn]].<ref name=Song/><ref name=Iconic>{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/that-iconic-touch/757393/0|title=That Iconic Touch|newspaper=[[Indian Express]]|accessdate=2 February 2012|author=Rajiv Vijayakar|location= Mumbai|date=4 March 2011}}</ref> The Filmalaya Production banner thus introduced Joy, Sadhana and her iconic hairstyle in their 1960 romantic film ''[[Love in Simla]]''. The film was declared a hit at the box office and was listed in the top 10 films of 1960.<ref name=Boxoffice1960>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=166&catName=MTk2MA==|title=Box Office 1960|website=Boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=3 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014060830/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=166&catName=MTk2MA==|archivedate=14 October 2013}}</ref> During this period she would again work under the same banner opposite Joy in ''[[Ek Musafir Ek Haseena]]''.<ref name=\"Love\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/mar/08dinesh.htm|title=Love in Simla: Grin fairytale|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Rediff.com|access-date=|accessdate=6 February 2012|author=[[Dinesh Raheja]]}}</ref>\n\n===Stardom===\nBesides ''[[Love in Simla]]'', Sadhana was signed by acclaimed director [[Bimal Roy]] for his satirical film on Indian democracy, ''[[Parakh (1960 film)|Parakh]]''. She portrayed a simple village girl in this multi-award-winning film. The film was a semi hit at box office and is known for the song \"O Sajna Barkha Bahar Aai\" sung by Lata Mangeshkar.\n\n====Major breakthrough====\n* 1961: ''[[Hum Dono (1961 film)|Hum Dono]]'' - In this 1961's hit film,<ref name=Boxoffice1961>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=167&catName=MTk2MQ==|title=Box Office 1961|website=Boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> ''[[Hum Dono (1961 film)|Hum Dono]]'', she played the love interest of [[Dev Anand]]. This black-and-white film was [[Film colourization|colourized]] and re-released in 2011. ''[[Rediff.com]]'' in the film's review writes about Sadhana: \"Her eyes, expressive and captivating, do most of the work, while she balances out her submissiveness with a firm tongue.\"<ref name=HumDono>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/hum-dono-review/20110204.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|title=Hum Dono review: absolute must-watch|date=4 February 2011|author=Raja Sen|location=Mumbai|accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref> The duet \"Abhi na jaao chhodkar\" from the film ''Hum Dono'' is regarded as \"the most romantic song\" by actor [[Shah Rukh Khan]]<ref>{{cite news|title='Abhi na jao chhod kar...\u2019|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/nation/-abhi-na-jao-chhod-kar/175554.html|newspaper=The Tribune|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> and director [[Sanjay Leela Bhansali]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/veteran-actor-sadhana-takes-her-last-breath/article8028929.ece|title=Sadhana, Hindi film style icon of 1960s, is no more|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=26 December 2015|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Author [[Amit Chaudhuri]] in an essay comparing cultures, says that Sadhana's curious expressions in the song denote listener's peculiar ecstasy while in other cinemas it would mean sex or love.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bh9iAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT196|title=Telling Tales: Selected Writing, 1993-2013|publisher=Penguin UK|author=Chaudhuri, Amit|authorlink=Amit Chaudhuri|year=2014|location=UK|isbn=9789351185963}}</ref>\n* 1962: ''Asli-Naqli'' - In 1962, she was again paired with [[Dev Anand]] in ''[[Asli-Naqli]]'' by director [[Hrishikesh Mukherjee]]. The film has two hit songs \"Tujhe Jeevan Ki Dor Se\", sung by both [[Mohammed Rafi]] and [[Lata Mangeshkar]] and \"Tera Mera Pyar Amar\", sung by Lata Mangeshkar. The same year saw director-screenwriter [[Raj Khosla]] cast her opposite Joy Mukherjee in ''[[Ek Musafir Ek Hasina]]''. She had debuted with Joy Mukherjee with the film ''Love in Shimla'' in 1960. Khosla would again work with Sadhana to make a suspense thriller trilogy.<ref name=\"ndtvbio\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/sadhana-shivdasani-bollywoods-mystery-girl-and-hasina-1258999|title=Sadhana Shivdasani, Bollywood's Mystery Girl and Hasina|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n* 1963: ''Mere Mehboob'' - This film was the highest grossing Indian film of 1963. The film stars Sadhana, [[Rajendra Kumar]], [[Ashok Kumar]], [[Nimmi]], Pran, [[Johnny Walker (actor)|Johnny Walker]] and [[Ameeta]]. In this film, Sadhana played her first role in the [[technicolour]] film. The film ''[[Mere Mehboob]]'' was directed by [[H. S. Rawail]]. The song \"Mere Mehboob Tujhe\" was shot in the University Hall and in a couple of places, one gets to see the University. The song became very popular upon release. The opening scene of the film shows the famous residential hall and the associated hall \"Victoria Gate\". The film was the blockbuster of 1963, and ranked in the top 5 films of the 1960s.\n* 1964: ''Woh Kaun Thi'' - In 1964, she played a double role in the first of the suspense-thriller trilogy; ''[[Woh Kaun Thi?]]''. This white-sari-clad performance opposite [[Manoj Kumar]] earned her first [[Filmfare]] nomination as Best Actress. Through this role she got to be part of [[Lata Mangeshkar]] \u2013 [[Madan Mohan]]\u2019s songs \"Naina barse\" and \"[[Lag jaa gale]]\". ''Rediff.com'' called her a show-stopper \"with an intriguing [[Mona Lisa]]-like smile\". The film was a box office hit. Raj Khosla cast her in two more successful mystery films; ''[[Mera Saaya]]'' (1966) and ''[[Anita (1967 film)|Anita]]'' (1967) thus making her famous as the \"Mystery girl\".\n*1965 : Arzoo- Arzoo was a box office success, with Sadhana, Rajendra Kumar and Feroz Khan in lead roles. The film had songs like \"Ae Phoolon ki Rani\" sung by Mohammad Rafi and \" Aji rooth kar ab\" , sung by Lata Mangeshkar.\n* 1966: ''Mera Saaya'' - ''Mera Saaya'' was a box office success, a courtroom drama film, again saw her playing a double role, now opposite [[Sunil Dutt]]. The film was the third film directed by Raj Khosla with Sadhana. The song \"Jhumka gira re\" sung by [[Asha Bhosle]] and composed by [[Madan Mohan]] saw Sadhana perform dance steps choreographed by [[Saroj Khan]]. Khan was then an assistant to dance director [[B. Sohanlal]]. The song became so popular that excited audience in cinema halls used to throw coins at the screen, and is one of the most requested songs on the radio. The film also had the classic songs \"Mera Saaya Saath Hoga\" and \"Nainon Mein Badra Chhaye\", both voiced by [[Lata Mangeshkar]].\n* 1965: ''Waqt''- In this 1965 drama film, Sadhana appeared alongside Sunil Dutt. For her performance in this hit film, Sadhana got her second Filmfare nomination as Best Actress for the role of Meena, in Yash Chopra's directorial saga ''Waqt'' (1965). She stood out in Bollywood's first ever ensemble cast by bringing out the fashion of tight ''churidar-kurtas''. The song has hit Hindi songs such as \"Aye Meri Zohra Zabeen\", sung by Manna Dey, \"Hum Jab Simat Ke\", sung by Mahendra Kapoor and Asha Bhosle, \"Waqt Se Din Aur Raat\", sung by Mohammed Rafi and \"Aage Bhi Jaane Na Tu\", sung by Asha Bhosle. The film proved to be 1965's \"blockbuster hit\".\n* 1967: ''Anita'' - In this 1967 suspense film, Sadhana appeared alongside Manoj Kumar with whom she had starred in lead role in the blockbuster film ''Woh Kaun Thi''. This was the last film of the suspense-thriller trilogy of Khosla-Sadhana partnership.\n*1969: ''Inteqam'' - This film was directed by R.K. Nayyar, and stars Sadhana and Sanjay Khan in lead roles and supported by Ashok Kumar, Jeevan, Rajendra Nath, Rehman, Helen and Anju Mahendru. The film features the first cabaret number song \"Aa Jaane Jaan\", also a rarity through her career. The film was a success at box office and marked the return of Sadhana after her brief illness, and her husband directed the film.\n\nHer other notable works in the 1960s include performances in [[Gaban (1966 film)|''Gaban'']] (1966) and ''[[Budtameez]]'' (1966). Sadhana and Shammi Kapoor worked together in 4 films Rajkumar, Budtameez, Sachaai and Chhote Sarkar of which the first 3 were box office hits and the pair got good audience acceptance''.''\n\n* 1964: ''Rajkumar'' - ''Rajkumar'' stars Sadhana, [[Shammi Kapoor]], Pran, [[Prithviraj Kapoor]], [[Om Prakash]] and [[Rajindernath]]. The film was a box office success and has the hit songs \"Aaja Aai Bahar\", sung by Lata Mangeshkar, \"Tumne Pukara Aur Hum Chale Aaye\", sung by Mohammed Rafi and [[Suman Kalyanpur]], \"Tumne Kisi Ki Jaan Ko\" and \"Is Rang Badalti Duniya Mein\", both sung by Mohammed Rafi. \n*1969: Sachaai - Sachaai stars Sadhana, Shammi Kapoor , Sanjeev Kumar, Helen, Johnny Walker and Pran. This film was a box office hit with songs like \" Sau baras ki zindagi\", sung by Mohammed Rafi and Asha Bhosle \" Ae dost mere maine duniya dekhi hai\" , sung by Mohammed Rafi and Manna Dey and \" Mere gunaah maaf kar\" sung by Mohammed Rafi.\n* 1969: ''Ek Phool Do Mali'' - This Indian Hindi film of 1969 stars Sadhana and Sanjay Khan in lead roles and has hit songs such as \"Ye Parda Hata Do\", sung by Asha Bhosle and Mohammed Rafi, \"Aulad Walo\", sung by Asha Bhosle and Mohammed Rafi, \"O Nanhe Se Farishte\" sung by Mohammed Rafi, \"Saiyan Le Gayi Jiya\", sung by Asha Bhosle and \"Tujhe Suraj Kahoon Ya Chanda\" sung by [[Manna Dey]].\n\n===End of acting career===\n[[File:Nanda-Waheeda-Helen-Sadhana.jpg|thumb|right|Sadhana (first from right) with [[Helen (actress)|Helen]], [[Waheeda Rehman]] and [[Nanda (actress)|Nanda]] in 2010]]\nSadhana had health issues due to her thyroid, which she got treated in [[Boston]]. After returning from the US, she starred in the successful movies Intaquam (1969), Ek phool do mali (1969), Sachaai (1969), Dil Daulat Duniya (1972) and Geeta Mera Naam (1974).\n\nIn ''[[Intaquam]]'' she played the role of a woman who revengefully lures the son of her own boss who cheated her, to be put behind the bars for a crime he did not commit. In 1974, her directorial venture ''[[Geeta Mera Naam]]'' was released. Produced by her husband, the film had herself playing the lead actress along with [[Sunil Dutt]] and [[Feroz Khan (actor, born 1939)|Feroz Khan]]. It was also [[Saroj Khan]]'s first film as an independent dance director..\n\nAfter that, she retired from acting, as she did not want to be cast as a side-actress or do character roles.<ref name=Song/> Later, she and her husband formed a production company. She also produced the movie ''Pati Parmeshwar'', starring [[Dimple Kapadia]] in 1989.<ref name=Hindu>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|author=Das Gupta, Ranjan|title=Sadhna worked wonders|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2008/09/05/stories/2008090550840400.htm|date=5 September 2008|accessdate=3 February 2012|location=Chennai, India}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSadhana married her ''Love in Simla'' director Ram Krishna Nayyar on 7 March 1966.<ref name=\"MeraSaaya\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/jun/20dinesh.htm|title=Mera Saaya: A Compelling Conundrum|last=|author=[[Dinesh Raheja]]|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Rediff.com|access-date=|accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref> Their love blossomed on the film set. But as she was very young then, her parents opposed it. They were married for nearly thirty years, until his death in 1995 from asthma. The couple had no children. In 2013, she stated that doesn't keep in touch with her cousin [[Babita]] but does keep in touch with actresses such as [[Asha Parekh]], [[Waheeda Rehman]], [[Nanda (actress)|Nanda]] and [[Helen Jairag Richardson]].<ref>http://timesofIndia.Indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-dont-acknowledge-Babita-Sadhana/articleshow/26720515.cms</ref>\n\nShe suffered from eye problems due to [[hyperthyroidism]]. After her retirement from acting, she refused to be photographed.<ref name=Iconic/> Living in [[Santacruz, Mumbai]], she rented an apartment building owned by singer [[Asha Bhosle]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-08-13/news-interviews/28298083_1_sangeeta-bungalow-sadhana-yusuf-lakdawala|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|title=Builder threatened to kill me: Sadhana|date=13 August 2012|author=Deeptiman Tiwary|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-dont-acknowledge-Babita-Sadhana/articleshow/26720515.cms|title=I don't acknowledge Babita: Sadhana|work=The Times of India|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Fashion icon==\nSadhana introduced the [[Bangs (hair)|fringe]] hairstyle in the Indian film industry in her first film ''[[Love in Simla]]''. R.K. Nayyar, director of the film and her future husband, suggested the fringe style in order to make her forehead look narrower. Sadhana says: \"They tried to stick a strip near the hair-line, but it didn\u2019t work out.\"<ref name=Interview1990/> Nayyar then suggested she go for the fringe style as was then sported by the Hollywood actress [[Audrey Hepburn]].<ref name=Song/><ref name=Iconic/><ref name=Hindu/> The fringe soon became popular and a fashion fad in the 1960s.<ref name=HT>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Fashion/Sadhana-s-fringe-benefits-from-Audrey-Hepburn/Article1-738866.aspx|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|title=Sadhana's fringe benefits from Audrey Hepburn|location=Mumbai|date=28 August 2011|author=Roshmila Bhattacharya|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=Fashion>{{cite book|title=Fashion cultures: Theories, explorations, and analysis|author1=[[Stella Bruzzi]] |author2=Pamela Church Gibson |year=2000|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-20685-5|page=188|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xmjv-IJymZsC&pg=PA188 }}</ref>\n\nThe style was copied by girls in India and is still known by the same name.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Rachel Dwyer |author2=Divia Patel |title=Cinema India: the visual culture of Hindi film |publisher=Reaktion Books|year=2002|page=97|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ebsaAQAAIAAJ&q=sadhana+cut&dq=sadhana+cut }}</ref> The look suited the role of naughty, pretty, glamorous Sonia that she played. But when Sadhana went on the shoot for [[Bimal Roy]]'s ''[[Parakh (1960 film)|Parakh]]'', Roy was disappointed to see her modern look. She had to stick her fringe back in order to match the simple village girl she played here.<ref name=Interview1990/> In 1963, when she signed to play a role of a simple Muslim girl from Aligarh in ''[[Mere Mehboob]]'', Sadhana undid her famous \"Sadhana cut\" to fit the bill. She had centre-parted her hair and wore it in a plait, which was immediately discarded by the director H.S. Rawail. He said that the audience wanted to see her signature \"Sadhana cut\" and demanded it.<ref name=Interview1991/> Recently, the Bollywood actress [[Deepika Padukone]] sported the same fringe in her films ''[[Om Shanti Om]]'' (2007) and ''[[Chandni Chowk To China]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110404/jsp/entertainment/story_13805378.jsp|title=Mirror Mirror|newspaper=The Telegraph India|date=4 April 2011|author=Priscilla Corner|accessdate=5 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nSadhana is also credited with bringing into fashion the tight ''churidar-kurta''.<ref name=Interview1991/><ref name=Fashion/> She went with this concept of gracefully changing the traditional loose [[salwar kameez]] to her director [[Yash Chopra]] for the 1965 film ''[[Waqt (1965 film)|Waqt]]''. Chopra felt insecure and thought that it would not be accepted. But Sadhana, with the help of her fashion designer [[Bhanu Athaiya]] showed him a sample, which he liked.<ref name=Interview1990/> The trend lasted well into the 1970s and can be seen, adopted by many actresses.<ref name=Encyclo>{{cite book|title=Encyclopaedia of Hindi Cinema|author=[[Gulzar]], [[Govind Nihalani]], Saibal Chatterjee|publisher=Popular Prakashan|page=523|isbn=81-7991-066-0|year=2003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8y8vN9A14nkC&pg=PT547 }}</ref>\n\nIn a song sequence of \"[[Phir Milenge Chalte Chalte]]\" for ''[[Rab Ne Bana Di Jodi]]'' (2008), actress [[Bipasha Basu]] dressed herself in a white ''churidar-kurta'' and also frolicked with the famous fringe as a tribute to Sadhana.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/DressCircle/I-m-not-going-to-risk-my-life-for-any-film/Article1-367020.aspx|title=I'm not going to risk my life for any film|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=15 January 2009|author=Subhash K. Jha|location=Mumbai|accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Sadhana made a rare public appearance walking the ramp in a pink sari at a fashion show to support the cause for cancer and AIDS patients. She was escorted by her relative, actor [[Ranbir Kapoor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/veteran-actress-sadhana-walks-the-ramp-with-ranbir-kapoor/#sadhana-ranbir-gs|title=Veteran actress Sadhana walks the ramp with Ranbir Kapoor|work=[[Indian Express]]|date=11 May 2014|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nDespite the fact that many of Shivdasani's films fared very well at the [[box office]], she did not receive any of the leading awards of the film industry. She was nominated for the [[Filmfare Award]] in [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress|Best Actress category]] for her roles in ''[[Woh Kaun Thi?]]'' and ''[[Waqt (1965 film)|Waqt]].\n\nFor her contribution to film, she was awarded the [[IIFA Lifetime Achievement Award|Lifetime Achievement Award]] by the [[International Indian Film Academy Awards|IIFA]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iifa.com/web07/showcase/2002-winnerslist.htm|title=Showcase: IIFA 2002 Malaysia|publisher=IIFA|accessdate=14 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070329033936/http://www.iifa.com/web07/showcase/2002-winnerslist.htm|archivedate=29 March 2007|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000361/2002|publisher=IMDB|title=Awards of the International Indian Film Academy (2002)|accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nDuring her later years, Sadhana was involved in court cases<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/3-court-cases-were-wearing-her-out-says-sadhanas-lawyer/|title=3 court cases were wearing her out, says Sadhana\u2019s lawyer|date=2015-12-26|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-02-12|language=en-US}}</ref> and suffered from illness.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ailing Sadhana pleaded for help but no one from the film industry came forward: Tabassum|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/ailing-sadhana-pleaded-for-help-but-no-one-from-the-film-industry-came-forward-tabassum|last=Sahadevan|first=Sonup|work=The Indian Express|date=26 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> She had undergone an emergency surgery due to a bleeding oral lesion in December 2014 at the [[K J Somaiya Medical College]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Veteran actress Sadhana on the mend after emergency surgery|last=Pandit|first=Sadaguru|url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/veteran-actress-sadhana-on-the-mend-after-emergency-surgery/15839157|work=Mid Day|date=13 December 2014|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Yesteryear actress Sadhana undergoes a major surgery|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141212/entertainment-bollywood/article/yestyear-actress-sadhana-undergoes-major-surgery|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=12 December 2014|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nSadhana died on 25 December 2015 in [[P.D. Hinduja National Hospital and Medical Research Centre|Hinduja Hospital]], Mumbai after being hospitalised with high fever.<ref name=hindu/> Although the illness she briefly suffered from was officially undisclosed,<ref>{{cite news|title=Sadhana, Hindi film style icon of 1960s, is no more|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/veteran-actor-sadhana-takes-her-last-breathe/article8028929.ece|work=The Hindu|date=26 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> Sadhana was cremated at Oshiwara crematorium in [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]. Bollywood stars such [[Anushka Sharma]], [[Karan Johar]], [[Madhur Bhandarkar]], [[Lata Mangeshkar]] and several others expressed their sorrow at the loss.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bollywood mourns veteran actor Sadhana\u2019s death|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/bollywood-mourns-veteran-actor-sadhana-s-death/story-OGkdVEKGvR91ZUhtICcizJ.html|work=Hindustan Times|date=25 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=RIP Sadhana: Lag Jaa Gale to Jhumka Gira Re, remembering the actor through her songs|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/rip-sadhana-laj-jaa-gale-to-jhumka-gira-re-remembering-the-actor-through-her-songs/1/555187.html|last=Nijhara|first=Apoorva|work=India Today|date=25 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Movie !! Role !! Note \n|-\n| 1955 || '''''[[Shree 420]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Chorus girl || Cameo role in the song \"Mud Mud Ke Na Dekh\"\n|-\n| 1958 || '''''[[Abana (film)|Abana]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || || First [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]] film \n|-\n| 1958  ||Sahara ||\n|-\n| 1960 || '''''[[Love in Simla]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Sonia || Sadhana debut film as a lead actress \n|-\n| 1960 || '''''[[Parakh (1960 film)|Parakh]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Seema ||Hit Song \"O Sajna Barkha Bahar\" \n|-\n| 1961 || '''''[[Hum Dono (1961 film)|Hum Dono]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Mita ||Hit Song \"Abhi Na Jao Chodkar\", a duet by [[Asha Bhosle]] and [[Mohammed Rafi]] \n|-\n| 1962 || '''''[[Prem Patra]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Kavita Kapoor ||\n|-\n| 1962 || '''''Man Mauji'''''<ref name=\"Evergreen\">{{cite web | url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/519618/part-several-evergreen-films-sadhana.html | title=Part of several evergreen films, Sadhana no more | work=[[Deccan Herald]] | date=26 December 2015 | accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> || Rani || \n|-\n| 1962 || '''''[[Ek Musafir Ek Hasina]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Asha || \n|-\n| 1962 || '''''[[Asli-Naqli]]'''''<ref name=\"Evergreen\"/> || Renu ||Hit songs from the film are \"Tere Mera Pyar Amar\", sung by Lata Mangeshkar, and \"Tujhe Jeevan Ki Durse\", a duet by Lata Mangeshkar and Mohammed Rafi \n|-\n| 1963 || '''''[[Mere Mehboob]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Husna Banu Changezi || Hit Song \"Mere Mehboob Tujhe Meri\" \n|-\n| 1964 || '''''[[Woh Kaun Thi?]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Sandhya / Seema (Double Role) || {{Nom}}: [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress]]<br>Hit Song \"[[Lag Jaa Gale|Lag Ja Gale Ke Phir]]\", \"Aap Kyon Royen\", <br> \"Naina Barse Rim Jhim\" and \"Chhod Kar Tere Pyaar Ka Daman\" \n|-\n| 1964 || '''''[[Rajkumar (1964 film)|Rajkumar]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Princess Sangeeta ||Hit Song \"Aaja Aai Bahar\", \"Iss Rang Badalti Duniya Mein\", \"Tumne Pukara Aur Hum Chale Aaye\" and \"Tumne Kisi Ki Jaan ko\" \n|-\n| 1964 || '''''Picnic''''' || || Not released<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JVD7dajMt3YC&pg=PA201 | title=Ten Years with Guru Dutt: Abrar Alvi's Journey | publisher=Penguin Books India |author1=Sathya Saran |author2=Abrar Alvi | year=2008 | pages=201 | isbn=9780670082216}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1964 || '''''[[Dulha Dulhan]]'''''<ref name=\"Evergreen\"/> || Rekha / Chanda || \n|-\n| 1965 || '''[[Waqt (1965 film)|''Waqt'']]'''<ref name=Song/> || Meena Mittal || {{Nom}}: [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress]] Hit songs are \"Ae Meri Zohra Zabeen\", sung by Manna Dey and \"Hum Jab Simat Ke Aapki\" by Asha Bhosle and Mahendra Kapoor \n|-\n| 1965 || '''[[Arzoo (1965 film)|''Arzoo'']]''' <ref name=Song/> || Usha ||Hit Song \"Bedardi Balma Tujhko\" sung by Lata Mangeshkar, \"Aji Rooth Kar Ab\", sung by Lata Mangeshkar and \"Ae Phoolon Ki Rani Baharon Ki Malika\", sung by [[Mohammed Rafi]] \n|-\n| 1966 || '''''[[Mera Saaya]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Geeta / Nisha (Raina) (Double Role) ||Hit Song \"Jhoomka Gira Re\", sung by Asha Bhosle, \"Mera Saaya Saath Hoga\", sung by Lata Mangeshkar and \"Nainon Mein Badea Chhaye\", sung by Lata Mangeshkar \n|-\n| 1966 || '''[[Gaban (1966 film)|''Gaban'']]'''<ref name=\"Evergreen\"/> || Jalpa ||Hit Song \"tum bin sajan\"\n|-\n| 1966 || '''''[[Budtameez]]'''''<ref name=\"Evergreen\"/> || Shanta ||Hit songs 'Hassen ho tum khuda nahi ho' , 'Apni baahon se koi kaam toh lo', Budtameez kaho ya kaho janwar'