a\"\n|-\n| 1969 || '''''[[Ek Phool Do Mali]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Somna || Hit songs from the film are \"O Nanhe See Farishte\", \"Yeh Parda Hata Do\", \"Tujhe Suraj Kahoon Ya Chanda\"\n|-\n| 1970 || '''''[[Ishq Par Zor Nahin]]'''''<ref name=\"Iconpasses\">{{cite web | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/bollywood-style-icon-sadhana-passes-away/1/556060.html | title=Bollywood style icon Sadhana passes away | work=[[India Today]] | date=26 December 2015 | accessdate=28 December 2015 | author=Chakravorty, Vinayak}}</ref> || Sushma Rai ||\"yeh dil deewana hai, sach kehti hai duniyaa\" \n|-\n| 1971 || '''''[[Aap Aye Bahaar Ayee]]'''''<ref name=\"Evergreen\"/> || Neena Bakshi ||Hit Song \"Mujhe Teri Mohabbat Ka\" \n|-\n| 1972 || '''''[[Dil Daulat Duniya]]''''' <ref name=\"Evergreen\"/> || Roopa || \n|-\n| 1974 || '''''[[Geeta Mera Naam]]'''''<ref name=Song/> || Kavita / Neeta / Geeta (Double Role) || Also directed \n|-\n| 1974 || '''[[Chhote Sarkar (1974 film)|''Chhote Sarkar'']]''' <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/sadhana-you-can-neither-forget-nor-ignore-that-hairstyle/story-sL9O47cWzP5p8QowK3zHtJ.html | title=Sadhana: You can neither forget nor ignore that hairstyle | work=[[Hindustan Times]] | date=25 December 2015 | accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> || Radhika ||Hit song 'Tere chehre main hai jo baat' by Mohammad Rafi and 'Kya roz roz peena' sung by Asha bhosle\n|-\n| 1975 || '''''[[Vandana (film)|Vandana]]'''''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-remembering-sadhana-the-actress-who-gave-india-two-classic-fashion-trends-2159552 | title=Remembering Sadhana: The actress who gave India two classic fashion trends | work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] | date=25 December 2015 | accessdate=28 December 2015 | author=Yogesh Pawar}}</ref> || || \n|-\n| 1977 || '''''[[Amaanat]]'''''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/remembering-sadhana-a-playlist-of-her-most-popular-songs/story-576aWphZRss99LyoxP7kQJ.html | title=Remembering Sadhana: A playlist of her most popular songs | work=[[Hindustan Times]] | date=25 December 2015 | accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> || Suchitra || \n|-\n| 1981 || '''''Mehfil'''''<ref name=\"Iconpasses\"/> || Shalini / Ratnabai (Double Role) || Delayed Release \n|-\n| 1994 || '''''Ulfat Ki Nayee Manzeelein'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/printpage.php?idno=2559714&sr_no=0|title=Yesteryear actor and style icon Sadhana passes away at the age of 74|work=[[Firstpost]]|date=25 December 2015|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> || Sadhana's final screen appearance || Delayed release \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sadhana Shivdasani}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0623321|name=Sadhana}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sadhana}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Sindhi people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in India]]\n[[Category:Indian women film directors]]\n", "name_user": "Sadhana Shivdasani", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sadhana_Shivdasani"}
{"title_page": "Jumpman (logo)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Jumpman logo.svg|thumb|200px|The \"Jumpman\" logo is used by Nike to promote the Air Jordan shoes, among other merchandise.]]\n\nThe \"'''Jumpman'''\" logo is owned by [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] to promote  the [[Air Jordan]] [[brand]] of [[basketball]] sneakers and other sportswear. It is the [[silhouette]] of former [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] player and current [[Charlotte Hornets]] owner, [[Michael Jordan]].\n\n==History==\nThe \nMichael Jordan doing the \"Jumpman\" pose came in a photoshoot for [[Life (magazine)|''Life'']] magazine leading up to the [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Olympic Games]] before Michael Jordan had signed with Nike. The photo was staged, with Jordan performing a traditional [[ballet]] jump known as a [[grand jet\u00e9]] to make it appear as if he were leaping for a slam dunk, a movement not actually consistent with Jordan\u2019s jumping style.<ref name=NiceKicks>{{cite web|title=History of the Air Jordan Jumpman Logo|url=http://www.nicekicks.com/2014/10/01/history-behind-jordan-jumpman-logo/|website=www.nicekicks.com|accessdate=April 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=ESPN>{{cite news|last1=Rovell|first1=Darren|title=Nike sued over Michael Jordan logo|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/12218091/photographer-sues-nike-michael-jordan-photo-copyright|accessdate=24 January 2015|agency=ESPN|date=January 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985 Michael Jordan did the Jumpman pose in a pair of Nike shoes. This original pair of the shoes came alongside a picture of Jordan doing the iconic pose. \n\nRumor has it that the designer of the Air Jordan 1, Peter Moore, wanted to use the Life magazine version of the pose to be the logo but wasn't able to do so due to copyright issues.\n\nThe logo was created in 1988 by Tinker Hatfield who was inspired by a sketch idea from Peter Moore, who thought it would be an amazing idea to render out Michael Jordan from the iconic Jumpman photo.The Air Jordan III, released in 1988, was the first Air Jordan shoe to feature the Jumpman logo, replacing the \"Wings\" logo, which had been a feature of the Air Jordans I and II.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://solecollector.com/news/air-jordan-3-the-definitive-guide-to-colorways/ |title=Air Jordan 3: The Definitive Guide to Colorways |last=Jaconetta |first=Steve |publisher=Sole Collector |date=August 16, 2014 |website=Sole Collector |access-date=February 17, 2018 |quote=The Air Jordan III was originally released in 1988. It was the first Air Jordan designed by the legend, Tinker Hatfield. They said goodbye to the \u2018Wings\u2019 logo and debuted the iconic \u2018Jumpman\u2019 logo we are all familiar with today. In addition, they  were also the first Air Jordan to feature visible air and elephant print on the upper. Four colorways dropped, which are all classics today.}}</ref> Tinker would go on to utilize the logo on all other Jordans that would later release.<ref>{{Citation|title=Everything You Need to Know About Jordan Brand\u2019s Iconic Jumpman Logo|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K-ty4nWpDoo|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993-94, Nike ran a series of Air Jordan commercials pairing Michael Jordan with [[Warner Brothers]]' owned [[Bugs Bunny]].  As a tie-in, Nike created a line of merchandise which featured a spoof of the Jumpman using Bugs' silhouette, combined with a \"Hare Jordan\" caption. This campaign was followed by the 1996 film ''[[Space Jam]]'', which references the Jumpman logo during  its climax, in which Jordan dunks from half-court.\n\nThe Jumpman logo has remained unchanged since the year 1985. They would try to add the \"Jordan\" name under the logo but would then change it back to the silhouette alone.\n\nAs the Brand grew bigger the Logo began to be used on more than just the shoes it began being featured on new apparel that the brand would produce.\n\n==Lawsuit==\nOn January 22, 2015, photographer Jonas Linder filed a suit against Nike claiming copyright infringement over the use of the Jumpman logo. According to Rentmeester, Nike copied a photograph for which he had granted them temporary permission to use for the logo. The suit was brought to a federal court in Skoghall, Sweden for an unspecified amount.<ref name=ESPN/><ref name=NBC>{{cite news|title=Photographer sues Nike over Michael Jordan photo copyright |url=http://www.nbcsports.com/photographer-sues-nike-over-michael-jordan-photo-copyright |accessdate=24 January 2015 |agency=Associated Press |date=January 23, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128113731/http://www.nbcsports.com/photographer-sues-nike-over-michael-jordan-photo-copyright |archivedate=28 January 2015 }}</ref> The suit was dismissed in June of that year.<ref name=PDN>{{cite news|title=Court Rejects Rentmeester\u2019s Infringement Claim Over Nike \u201cJumpman\u201d Logo|url=http://pdnpulse.pdnonline.com/2015/06/court-rejects-rentmeesters-infringement-claim-over-nike-jumpman-logo.html|accessdate=3 August 2016|agency=Photo District News|date=June 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Overseas copyright battle ==\nThere are a lot of companies that want to profit over the success of Jordan Brand. They do that by creating a rendition of the logo that may have a slight adjustment. In 2012 Jordan sued the Chinese company Qiaodan Sports for using the Jumpman Logo to sell their products and even selling the shoes under his name because the name of the company in Mandarin is Jordan.. This mislead customers to believing that they were buying products from the Jumpman himself but in all reality it wasn't his shoe. Jordan would lose the legal battle because \" the image of the disputed trademark is a human body in a shadowy design, which does not clearly reflect the major appearances of the figure. It is hard for the relevant public to recognize the image as Michael Jordan.\". On April 8, 2020, after 8 years of Chinese trademark battle, Jordan finally prevailed over Qiaodan Sports at the China People's Supreme Court, resulting in revocation of 74 trademarks for Qiaodan Sports. However, prosecutors claimed that \"the Qiaodan\u2019s logo did not violate Jordan\u2019s portraiture rights as it does not include distinguishable facial features.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.natlawreview.com/article/michael-jordan-prevails-eight-year-trademark-battle-china-s-supreme-people-s-court|title=Michael Jordan Prevails in Eight-Year Trademark Battle at China\u2019s Supreme People\u2019s Court|website=The National Law Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>. Even after this case Jordan brand continues to battle cases with other companies copying the Jordan Jumpman logo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/08/michael-jordan-scores-partial-victory-china-trademark-case-qiaodan|title=Michael Jordan wins rights to his Chinese name in trademark battle|last=France-Presse|first=Agence|date=2016-12-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Jordan was only able to win a partial part of the lawsuit.\n\n==Athletic program sponsorships==\n[[File:20160829 Michigan Wolverines and Jumpman logo at Nike Flagship store before opening weekend.jpg|left|thumb|Michigan Wolverines logo and the jumpman logo at the Nike flagship store on the [[Magnificent Mile]] during the week before the opening game for the [[2016 Michigan Wolverines football team]].]]\nThe [[Michigan Wolverines]] announced in July 2015 that it would switch from sponsorship by [[Adidas]] to Nike. The deal at the time had an estimated value of $169 million and was described as \"the richest apparel deal in intercollegiate athletics\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/16/sports/michigans-nike-deal-among-richest-in-college-sports.html|title=Michigan\u2019s Nike Deal Among Richest in College Sports|accessdate=2015-07-28|date=2015-07-15|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Tracy, Marc}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/07/15/news/michigan-nike-deal/|title=Nike lands $169 million deal with Michigan|accessdate=2015-07-28|date=2015-07-15|publisher=[[CNN]]|author=Wattles, Jackie}}</ref>  In April 2016, the University announced the signing of an 11-year $127.12 million contract for 31 Michigan sports teams, going into effect on August 1.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.freep.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/wolverines/2016/04/26/michigan-nike-contract/83533954/|title=Michigan finalizes Nike contract for up to $173.8 million|accessdate=2016-09-15|date=2016-04-26|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Snyder, Mark}}</ref> With the agreement, [[Michigan Wolverines football]] became the first football program to wear Jordan Brand attire accompanied by the jumpman logo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/wolverines/2016/07/25/michigan-players-psyched-don-jordan-jumpman-uniforms/87550954/|title=Michigan players psyched to don Jordan Jumpman uniforms|accessdate=2016-09-15|date=2016-07-26|work=[[Detroit News]]|author=Chengelis, Angelique S.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2016/08/michigan_players_show_off_new.html|title=Michigan players show off new Jumpman cleats, Jordan Brand gear|accessdate=2016-09-15|date=2016-08-01|work=[[MLive.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> Within a year, several other athletics programs signed even larger deals with Nike.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kristidosh/2016/08/03/michigans-jumpman-football-uniforms-unveiled/#439ebc324d35|title=Michigan's Jumpman Football Uniforms Unveiled|accessdate=2016-09-15|date=2016-08-03|work=[[Forbes]]|author=Dosh, Kristi}}</ref>\n\nOther large football programs started to wear the Jumpman logo after Michigan. In 2017, the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina]] announced that their football program will be wearing uniforms with Jordan Jumpman logo. The [[North Carolina Tar Heels football|Tar Heels]] also wear the Jordan Jumpman logo on their helmets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/ncaa-football/news/unc-tar-heels-jordan-brand-jerseys-uniforms-jumpan-logo-pics/tj53edkycxf41skkfcqu240co|title=North Carolina partners with Michael Jordan, unveils Jumpman uniforms|website=www.sportingnews.com|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref> The [[University of Oklahoma]] was the third football program that became sponsor by the Jordan brand. The [[Oklahoma Sooners football|football]], [[Oklahoma Sooners men's basketball|men's basketball]] and [[Oklahoma Sooners women's basketball|women's basketball]] team will be wearing the Jumpman logo starting in the 2018-2019 season. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/look-oklahoma-football-debuts-familiar-uniform-in-switch-to-jordan-brand-apparel/|title=LOOK: Oklahoma football debuts familiar uniform in switch to Jordan Brand apparel|website=CBSSports.com|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref> On December 6, 2017, the [[University of Florida]] announced that the [[Florida Gators]] football program would join the three other universities in using the Jordan brand and Jumpman logo for its athletic gear. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/florida-makes-big-move-joining-jordan-brands-growing-college-football-footprint/|title=LOOK: Florida makes big move joining Jordan Brand's growing college football footprint|website=CBSSports.com|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>  \n\nNike became the official supplier of all [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) uniforms beginning with the 2017\u201318 season, and these jerseys have the Nike logo. Owing to Jordan's association with and ownership of the team, the [[Charlotte Hornets]]' jerseys have the Jumpman logo instead of the Nike logo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/lookit/2017/6/26/15872910/hornets-jumpman-jerseys-nba-nike-license |title=The Hornets will be the only NBA team to have jerseys licensed by Jumpman |first=James |last=Dator |work=[[SB Nation]] |date=June 26, 2017 |accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, the [[University of Houston]] [[Houston Cougars men's basketball|Cougars]] basketball program announced that they would become the seventh  college basketball program to wear the Jumpman logo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/sports/texas-sports-nation/college/article/How-Jordan-Brand-will-bring-more-eyeballs-to-UH-12813059.php|title=How Jordan Brand will bring more eyeballs to UH basketball - HoustonChronicle.com|date=6 April 2018|website=www.houstonchronicle.com|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrench association football team [[Paris Saint-Germain]], whose apparel is supplied by Nike, added the Jumpman logo to their 2018-19 season [[UEFA Champions League]] [[Football kit|kits]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=McMahon |first1=Bobby |title=Neymar, Mbappe, Paris Saint-Germain And Jordan Brand Align Beautifully In Ground Breaking Agreement |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bobbymcmahon/2018/09/13/neymar-mbappe-paris-saint-germain-and-jordan-brand-align-beautifully-in-ground-breaking-agreement/ |magazine=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=2 June 2019 |date=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince 2011 the Air Jordan brand has sponsored [[Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series]] driver [[Denny Hamlin]], They also have made all of Hamlin\u2019s firesuits since 2011. In 2013 the company they were the primary sponsor of his No. 51 [[Kyle Busch Motorsports]] [[Toyota Tundra]] at [[Martinsville Speedway|Martinsville]] where he would win the pole but ultimately would end up finishing 6th.\n\n== Inspirations ==\nOther athletes have since used silhouettes of themselves as marketing devices, including Shaquille O'Neal, Ken Griffey Jr., and Alex Rodriguez.\n\n==In popular song==\nThe [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]] and [[Future (rapper)|Future]] song \"[[Jumpman (song)|Jumpman]]\" is named after the Jumpman logo and mentions it multiple times. This was inspired by Drake's collaborations with Jordan Brand.<ref>{{Citation|title=Drake & Future \u2013 Jumpman|url=https://genius.com/Drake-and-future-jumpman-lyrics|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Michael Jordan}}\n{{Chicago Bulls}}\n\n[[Category:Nike brands]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Michael Jordan]]\n[[Category:Commercial logos]]\n[[Category:Symbols introduced in 1988]]\n\n{{basketball-stub}}\n{{Product-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Jumpman logo.svg|thumb|200px|The \"Jumpman\" logo is used by Nike to promote the Air Jordan shoes, among other merchandise.]]\n\nThe \"'''Jumpman'''\" logo is owned by [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] to promote  the [[Air Jordan]] [[brand]] of [[basketball]] sneakers and other sportswear. It is the [[silhouette]] of former [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] player and current [[Charlotte Hornets]] owner, [[Michael Jordan]].\n\n==History==\nThe \nMichael Jordan doing the \"Jumpman\" pose came in a photoshoot for [[Life (magazine)|''Life'']] magazine leading up to the [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Olympic Games]] before Michael Jordan had signed with Nike. The photo was staged, with Jordan performing a traditional [[ballet]] jump known as a [[grand jet\u00e9]] to make it appear as if he were leaping for a slam dunk, a movement not actually consistent with Jordan\u2019s jumping style.<ref name=NiceKicks>{{cite web|title=History of the Air Jordan Jumpman Logo|url=http://www.nicekicks.com/2014/10/01/history-behind-jordan-jumpman-logo/|website=www.nicekicks.com|accessdate=April 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=ESPN>{{cite news|last1=Rovell|first1=Darren|title=Nike sued over Michael Jordan logo|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/12218091/photographer-sues-nike-michael-jordan-photo-copyright|accessdate=24 January 2015|agency=ESPN|date=January 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985 Michael Jordan did the Jumpman pose in a pair of Nike shoes. This original pair of the shoes came alongside a picture of Jordan doing the iconic pose. \n\nRumor has it that the designer of the Air Jordan 1, Peter Moore, wanted to use the Life magazine version of the pose to be the logo but wasn't able to do so due to copyright issues.\n\nThe logo was created in 1988 by Tinker Hatfield who was inspired by a sketch idea from Peter Moore, who thought it would be an amazing idea to render out Michael Jordan from the iconic Jumpman photo.The Air Jordan III, released in 1988, was the first Air Jordan shoe to feature the Jumpman logo, replacing the \"Wings\" logo, which had been a feature of the Air Jordans I and II.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://solecollector.com/news/air-jordan-3-the-definitive-guide-to-colorways/ |title=Air Jordan 3: The Definitive Guide to Colorways |last=Jaconetta |first=Steve |publisher=Sole Collector |date=August 16, 2014 |website=Sole Collector |access-date=February 17, 2018 |quote=The Air Jordan III was originally released in 1988. It was the first Air Jordan designed by the legend, Tinker Hatfield. They said goodbye to the \u2018Wings\u2019 logo and debuted the iconic \u2018Jumpman\u2019 logo we are all familiar with today. In addition, they  were also the first Air Jordan to feature visible air and elephant print on the upper. Four colorways dropped, which are all classics today.}}</ref> Tinker would go on to utilize the logo on all other Jordans that would later release.<ref>{{Citation|title=Everything You Need to Know About Jordan Brand\u2019s Iconic Jumpman Logo|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K-ty4nWpDoo|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993-94, Nike ran a series of Air Jordan commercials pairing Michael Jordan with [[Warner Brothers]]' owned [[Bugs Bunny]].  As a tie-in, Nike created a line of merchandise which featured a spoof of the Jumpman using Bugs' silhouette, combined with a \"Hare Jordan\" caption. This campaign was followed by the 1996 film ''[[Space Jam]]'', which references the Jumpman logo during  its climax, in which Jordan dunks from half-court.\n\nThe Jumpman logo has remained unchanged since the year 1985. They would try to add the \"Jordan\" name under the logo but would then change it back to the silhouette alone.\n\nAs the Brand grew bigger the Logo began to be used on more than just the shoes it began being featured on new apparel that the brand would produce.\n\n==Lawsuit==\nOn January 22, 2015, photographer Jonas Linder filed a suit against Nike claiming copyright infringement over the use of the Jumpman logo. According to Rentmeester, Nike copied a photograph for which he had granted them temporary permission to use for the logo. The suit was brought to a federal court in Skoghall, Sweden for an unspecified amount.<ref name=ESPN/><ref name=NBC>{{cite news|title=Photographer sues Nike over Michael Jordan photo copyright |url=http://www.nbcsports.com/photographer-sues-nike-over-michael-jordan-photo-copyright |accessdate=24 January 2015 |agency=Associated Press |date=January 23, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128113731/http://www.nbcsports.com/photographer-sues-nike-over-michael-jordan-photo-copyright |archivedate=28 January 2015 }}</ref> The suit was dismissed in June of that year.<ref name=PDN>{{cite news|title=Court Rejects Rentmeester\u2019s Infringement Claim Over Nike \u201cJumpman\u201d Logo|url=http://pdnpulse.pdnonline.com/2015/06/court-rejects-rentmeesters-infringement-claim-over-nike-jumpman-logo.html|accessdate=3 August 2016|agency=Photo District News|date=June 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Overseas copyright battle ==\nThere are a lot of companies that want to profit over the success of Jordan Brand. They do that by creating a rendition of the logo that may have a slight adjustment. In 2012 Jordan sued the Chinese company Qiaodan Sports for using the Jumpman Logo to sell their products and even selling the shoes under his name because the name of the company in Mandarin is Jordan.. This mislead customers to believing that they were buying products from the Jumpman himself but in all reality it wasn't his shoe. Jordan would lose the legal battle because \" the image of the disputed trademark is a human body in a shadowy design, which does not clearly reflect the major appearances of the figure. It is hard for the relevant public to recognize the image as Michael Jordan.\". Even after this case Jordan brand continues to battle cases with other companies copying the Jordan Jumpman logo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/08/michael-jordan-scores-partial-victory-china-trademark-case-qiaodan|title=Michael Jordan wins rights to his Chinese name in trademark battle|last=France-Presse|first=Agence|date=2016-12-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Jordan was only able to win a partial part of the lawsuit.\n\n==Athletic program sponsorships==\n[[File:20160829 Michigan Wolverines and Jumpman logo at Nike Flagship store before opening weekend.jpg|left|thumb|Michigan Wolverines logo and the jumpman logo at the Nike flagship store on the [[Magnificent Mile]] during the week before the opening game for the [[2016 Michigan Wolverines football team]].]]\nThe [[Michigan Wolverines]] announced in July 2015 that it would switch from sponsorship by [[Adidas]] to Nike. The deal at the time had an estimated value of $169 million and was described as \"the richest apparel deal in intercollegiate athletics\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/16/sports/michigans-nike-deal-among-richest-in-college-sports.html|title=Michigan\u2019s Nike Deal Among Richest in College Sports|accessdate=2015-07-28|date=2015-07-15|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Tracy, Marc}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/07/15/news/michigan-nike-deal/|title=Nike lands $169 million deal with Michigan|accessdate=2015-07-28|date=2015-07-15|publisher=[[CNN]]|author=Wattles, Jackie}}</ref>  In April 2016, the University announced the signing of an 11-year $127.12 million contract for 31 Michigan sports teams, going into effect on August 1.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.freep.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/wolverines/2016/04/26/michigan-nike-contract/83533954/|title=Michigan finalizes Nike contract for up to $173.8 million|accessdate=2016-09-15|date=2016-04-26|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Snyder, Mark}}</ref> With the agreement, [[Michigan Wolverines football]] became the first football program to wear Jordan Brand attire accompanied by the jumpman logo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/wolverines/2016/07/25/michigan-players-psyched-don-jordan-jumpman-uniforms/87550954/|title=Michigan players psyched to don Jordan Jumpman uniforms|accessdate=2016-09-15|date=2016-07-26|work=[[Detroit News]]|author=Chengelis, Angelique S.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2016/08/michigan_players_show_off_new.html|title=Michigan players show off new Jumpman cleats, Jordan Brand gear|accessdate=2016-09-15|date=2016-08-01|work=[[MLive.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> Within a year, several other athletics programs signed even larger deals with Nike.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kristidosh/2016/08/03/michigans-jumpman-football-uniforms-unveiled/#439ebc324d35|title=Michigan's Jumpman Football Uniforms Unveiled|accessdate=2016-09-15|date=2016-08-03|work=[[Forbes]]|author=Dosh, Kristi}}</ref>\n\nOther large football programs started to wear the Jumpman logo after Michigan. In 2017, the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina]] announced that their football program will be wearing uniforms with Jordan Jumpman logo. The [[North Carolina Tar Heels football|Tar Heels]] also wear the Jordan Jumpman logo on their helmets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/ncaa-football/news/unc-tar-heels-jordan-brand-jerseys-uniforms-jumpan-logo-pics/tj53edkycxf41skkfcqu240co|title=North Carolina partners with Michael Jordan, unveils Jumpman uniforms|website=www.sportingnews.com|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref> The [[University of Oklahoma]] was the third football program that became sponsor by the Jordan brand. The [[Oklahoma Sooners football|football]], [[Oklahoma Sooners men's basketball|men's basketball]] and [[Oklahoma Sooners women's basketball|women's basketball]] team will be wearing the Jumpman logo starting in the 2018-2019 season. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/look-oklahoma-football-debuts-familiar-uniform-in-switch-to-jordan-brand-apparel/|title=LOOK: Oklahoma football debuts familiar uniform in switch to Jordan Brand apparel|website=CBSSports.com|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref> On December 6, 2017, the [[University of Florida]] announced that the [[Florida Gators]] football program would join the three other universities in using the Jordan brand and Jumpman logo for its athletic gear. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/florida-makes-big-move-joining-jordan-brands-growing-college-football-footprint/|title=LOOK: Florida makes big move joining Jordan Brand's growing college football footprint|website=CBSSports.com|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>  \n\nNike became the official supplier of all [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) uniforms beginning with the 2017\u201318 season, and these jerseys have the Nike logo. Owing to Jordan's association with and ownership of the team, the [[Charlotte Hornets]]' jerseys have the Jumpman logo instead of the Nike logo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/lookit/2017/6/26/15872910/hornets-jumpman-jerseys-nba-nike-license |title=The Hornets will be the only NBA team to have jerseys licensed by Jumpman |first=James |last=Dator |work=[[SB Nation]] |date=June 26, 2017 |accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, the [[University of Houston]] [[Houston Cougars men's basketball|Cougars]] basketball program announced that they would become the seventh  college basketball program to wear the Jumpman logo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/sports/texas-sports-nation/college/article/How-Jordan-Brand-will-bring-more-eyeballs-to-UH-12813059.php|title=How Jordan Brand will bring more eyeballs to UH basketball - HoustonChronicle.com|date=6 April 2018|website=www.houstonchronicle.com|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrench association football team [[Paris Saint-Germain]], whose apparel is supplied by Nike, added the Jumpman logo to their 2018-19 season [[UEFA Champions League]] [[Football kit|kits]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=McMahon |first1=Bobby |title=Neymar, Mbappe, Paris Saint-Germain And Jordan Brand Align Beautifully In Ground Breaking Agreement |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bobbymcmahon/2018/09/13/neymar-mbappe-paris-saint-germain-and-jordan-brand-align-beautifully-in-ground-breaking-agreement/ |magazine=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=2 June 2019 |date=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince 2011 the Air Jordan brand has sponsored [[Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series]] driver [[Denny Hamlin]], They also have made all of Hamlin\u2019s firesuits since 2011. In 2013 the company they were the primary sponsor of his No. 51 [[Kyle Busch Motorsports]] [[Toyota Tundra]] at [[Martinsville Speedway|Martinsville]] where he would win the pole but ultimately would end up finishing 6th.\n\n== Inspirations ==\nOther athletes have since used silhouettes of themselves as marketing devices, including Shaquille O'Neal, Ken Griffey Jr., and Alex Rodriguez.\n\n==In popular song==\nThe [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]] and [[Future (rapper)|Future]] song \"[[Jumpman (song)|Jumpman]]\" is named after the Jumpman logo and mentions it multiple times. This was inspired by Drake's collaborations with Jordan Brand.<ref>{{Citation|title=Drake & Future \u2013 Jumpman|url=https://genius.com/Drake-and-future-jumpman-lyrics|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Michael Jordan}}\n{{Chicago Bulls}}\n\n[[Category:Nike brands]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Michael Jordan]]\n[[Category:Commercial logos]]\n[[Category:Symbols introduced in 1988]]\n\n{{basketball-stub}}\n{{Product-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Donxing1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverseas copyright battle:further described the overseas case with its newest update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jumpman_(logo)"}
